<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fig Industry Struggles To Survive / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRESNO, Calif. (AP) -- At the turn of the century, an  
enterprising young lawyer from Kansas moved to town and literally 
blasted his way onto the fig scene. 
</P>
<P>
	Using about 1 million sticks of dynamite, J.C. Forkner drilled  
holes into the hardpacked soil of northwest Fresno and planted acre 
after acre of trees in a region that became known as the nation's 
fig garden. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, most are just skeletons, scattered in dusty orchards fast  
becoming graveyards or paved over by housing subdivision and malls. 
</P>
<P>
	The big worry for fig farmers is that shrinking acreage could be  
a sign of things to come if the industry cannot restore the 
popularity of fig cookies and find new markets for the dried fruit 
and its paste. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we don't succeed in new product development and expansion  
of fig bar consumption, that could be a problem,'' said Paul 
Mesple, whose family has been in the business for more than 50 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Jew, vice president of industrial sales and technical  
services for Valley Fig Growers, a farming cooperative, said the 
biggest obstacle is that ``consumers don't know what figs are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although considered a fruit, the fig is actually a flower  
inverted onto itself. The seeds are drupes -- the real fruit. The 
tree is a member of the mulberry family, with a broad, spreading 
canopy. 
</P>
<P>
	Figs have the highest dietary fiber content of any common fruit,  
nut or vegetable. They are also free of fat, sodium and 
cholesterol. 
</P>
<P>
	As legend has it, the soft, sweet, droplet-shaped fig was  
introduced to mankind by Bacchus, the ancient Roman God who is 
often depicted wearing a crown of fig leaves. 
</P>
<P>
	Forkner brought figs to Fresno County in the early 1900s,  
planting 600,000 trees on 12,000 acres now being swallowed up or 
turned into urban islands by subdivisions and shopping malls. The 
last planting was in 1995 on five acres. The amount of fig land 
actively farmed in the county is estimated between about 1,000 and 
2,300 acres. 
</P>
<P>
	California's total fig acreage has remained at 16,000 or so  
acres the past 10 years. The state is the only commercial producer 
of dried figs in the nation and normally yields 15,000 tons a year, 
said Ron Klamm, head of the California Fig Advisory Board. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the world's fig crop is sun dried after the ripened figs  
are picked. But in California, the fruit usually remains on the 
tree until they are semidry and drop. They are then gathered at 
frequent intervals and further dried. 
</P>
<P>
	The goal is to grow as many figs as possible that can be  
packaged as whole fruit, as high consumer demand provides a better 
profit margin in comparison to fig paste. 
</P>
<P>
	But even in a good year, well over half of California's dried  
figs are turned into a chewy, seedy paste, used by Nabisco Inc. and 
other bakeries for cakelike cookies and fruit bars. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1990s, farmers could not seem to keep up with the  
demand, helped by promotions geared toward health-conscious 
Americans. But then all types of fat-free fruit cookies and other 
health bars became popular. 
</P>
<P>
	The fig industry, which says it lost market share because of the  
expansion and ended up with more paste than it could sell, then had 
to drop prices even lower after last year's El Nino season. It 
could be a year before the surplus is unloaded. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, farmers and others in the business are trying to broaden  
the market by developing a concentrated extract for flavoring and 
baking; adding colors and flavors to diced figs; and grounding figs 
into a powder for use as a health and dietary supplement. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have our work cut out for us,'' Klamm said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
