<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Vs. Most Major Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against most major currencies  
Wednesday, gaining against the yen on falling Japanese interest 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's rise against the euro came as European economic  
fundamentals remained stagnant, its major stock markets falling 
Wednesday on negative sentiment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not surprising to see the dollar strong,'' said  
Guillermo Estebanez, a foreign exchange economist at the Bank of 
America in San Francisco, noting recent reports indicating strength 
in the U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 121.77  
Japanese yen, up from 120.23 on Tuesday. Also in late trading, the 
euro was quoted at $1.0890, down from $1.0925. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders jumped at the opportunity to dump yen and buy dollars  
during Asian trading when the Bank of Japan flooded the interbank 
loan market with cash by buying short-term government bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	That action drove the call rate, used by big banks making  
overnight loans to each other, down to a miniscule 0.02 percent 
from 0.07 percent the day before. Long-term bond rates fell as 
well. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan is fighting its worst recession in decades. Lowering  
interest rates makes cheap cash available in the hope of spurring 
spending and building, but the steps are receiving mixed reviews. 
</P>
<P>
	``We continue to see the Japanese flailing their arms, trying to  
make monetary policy work,'' Estebanez said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4597 Swiss francs, up from  
1.4571, and 1.5267 Canadian dollars, up from 1.5208. The British 
pound fell to $1.6134, down from $1.6145. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the countries participating in the euro no longer  
are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Wednesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.7960 German 
marks, up from 1.7902; 6.0241 French francs, up from 6.0024; and 
Italian lire, 1,779.36, up from 1,773.05. 
</P>
</TEXT>
