<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	First Lady Visits New York  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton is in the city today,  
speaking at a public school about art education. She had nothing to 
say about the possibility of running for the Senate. At 
Intermediate School 25 in the borough of Queens, the first lady 
unveiled a new national report plugging arts education. Polls taken 
a few weeks ago gave her a commanding lead in a hypothetical 
match-up with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for the Senate seat being 
vacated by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan in 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	Uganda Apologizes for Killings  
</P>
<P>
	KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- The FBI is investigating the murder of  
eight foreign tourists in a gorilla reserve investigating the 
killings. Apologizing for the deaths, President Yoweri Museveni 
promised to capture or kill the rebels who used machetes to slay 
the tourists -- including two Americans -- Monday in the mountainous 
rain forest near the Rwandan area made famous in the 1988 film 
``Gorillas in the Mist.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Execution of German Still Planned  
</P>
<P>
	FLORENCE, Ariz. (AP) -- Gov. Jane Hull ignored international  
pleas to halt today's scheduled execution of convicted killer 
Walter LaGrand, a German citizen whose brother was put to death 
last week for the same crime. Germany sued last night in the 
International Court of Justice to try to halt LaGrand's execution, 
scheduled for this afternoon. LaGrand's 35-year-old brother, Karl, 
was executed last week for fatally stabbing Marana bank manager 
Kenneth Hartsock and slashing his throat during a botched robbery 
in 1982. 

</P>
<P>
	Court: Schools Must Pay Nurses  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal law requires the nation's public  
school districts to pay for professional nurses to accompany some 
disabled students throughout the school day, the Supreme Court 
ruled today in the case of an Iowa teen-ager. The court, by a 7-2 
vote, said such continuous care is not medical treatment, and 
therefore must be publicly funded under the federal Individuals 
with Disabilities Education Act. 

</P>
<P>
	Lewinsky Says Clinton Is Sorry  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Monica Lewinsky, in an interview clip aired  
today, said she felt President Clinton was ``sorry he got caught'' 
when their affair was revealed to the nation. Ms. Lewinsky revealed 
that she felt like a piece of trash the day Clinton was forced to 
admit their affair on national television and apologized to the 
nation -- but not to her. Portions of Ms. Lewinsky's interview with 
Barbara Walters played on ABC's ``Good Morning America.'' The full 
interview is to be aired tonight at 9 p.m. EST. 

</P>
<P>
	Leather Jackets Outlawed by Taliban  
</P>
<P>
	KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) -- Leather jackets are now the latest  
item prohibited by Afghanistan's ruling Taliban religious army. 
Taliban soldiers used knives to slash the leather jackets young men 
were wearing in Kabul today, saying the jackets were prohibited 
under Islam, witnesses said. Since taking power in 1996, the 
Taliban have imposed their brand of harsh Islamic laws. They have 
banned music, video cassette recorders, televisions, cameras and 
books published outside of Afghanistan. 

</P>
<P>
	Singer Dusty Springfield Dies  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Singer Dusty Springfield, whose cool, husky voice  
fueled such 1960s hits as ``Son of a Preacher Man'' and ``Wishin' 
and Hopin','' has died after a long battle with breast cancer. She 
was 59. Springfield died last night at her home in 
Henley-on-Thames, about 30 miles west of London, said her agent, 
Paul Fenn. Springfield was to be inducted next week into the Rock 
and Roll Hall of Fame at a ceremony in New York, along with Paul 
McCartney and Bruce Springsteen. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Mixed; Dow Up 5  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 1 p.m. EST, the Dow industrials were  
up 5.71 to 9,303.32. NYSE decliners led advancers 1,429-1,286. The 
Nasdaq index was up 4.07 to 2,263.10. 

</P>
<P>
	Webster Accused Again of Forging  
</P>
<P>
	MONACA, Pa. (AP) -- Mike Webster, the Pittsburgh Steelers center  
who was elected to the NFL Hall of Fame, has been accused of 
forging prescriptions at another pharmacy. Webster, 46, who was 
charged last week with forgery at a pharmacy in Rochester, was 
charged with presenting bogus prescriptions for Ritalin at three 
pharmacies in Center Township, about 25 miles northwest of 
Pittsburgh. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by KATHLEEN SAMPEY  
</P>
</TEXT>
