<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lewinsky: I Had a 'Foolish Dream' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Looking back, Monica Lewinsky says, her hope  
of living happily ever after with Bill Clinton was ``a pretty 
foolish dream.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As moony as a romance novel, occasionally self-pitying,  
sometimes angry or sniping, Ms. Lewinsky's version of events is 
full of the emotional melodrama America has come to expect from its 
most famous former intern. It's also spiced with confessional 
detail: her other affairs, an abortion, antidepressants and 
thoughts of suicide, chronic angst about her weight, frequent 
crying jags. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some days that I regret that the relationship ever  
started,'' Ms. Lewinsky told interviewer Barbara Walters. ``And 
there are some days that I just regret that I ever confided in 
Linda Tripp'' -- the former friend who disclosed the affair to 
investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky comfortably and almost cheerfully fielded questions  
on national TV, sporting a new, slicked-back hairstyle, laughing 
softly and occasionally looking down at embarrassing moments. 
</P>
<P>
	The ABC interview was part of a promotional blitz for ``Monica's  
Story,'' written by Andrew Morton with her extensive help, which 
goes on sale Thursday. In 288 pages, the book covers her life from 
birth in San Francisco 25 years ago through her videotaped 
testimony Feb. 1 for Clinton's Senate impeachment trial. 
</P>
<P>
	At that deposition, one of Clinton's attorneys read Ms. Lewinsky  
a statement saying the president was ``very, very sorry for what 
happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I was hit by the fact that I don't have him in my life  
anymore,'' she later told Morton tearfully. ``I just miss him so 
much right now,'' she said of the man she sometimes thought of as 
her ``little boy lost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But she also called Clinton ``a selfish man who lies all the  
time'' and said sometimes ``I have to turn off the TV because I 
feel sick looking at him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In some passages she portrays herself as a bungee-jumping,  
leg-waxing, e-mail-joking Beverly Hills girl of the '90s; in others 
she comes across as emotionally overwrought. 
</P>
<P>
	The path to her affair with the president -- Ms. Lewinsky says  
they ``fooled around'' in an Oval Office bathroom and inner office 
-- began when a friend of her mother helped arrange a White House 
internship. 
</P>
<P>
	There was lots of gossip at the White House about presidential  
womanizing, but the new intern thought of Clinton as an old guy 
with a ``big red nose and coarse, wiry-looking hair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then she saw him in person, and nearly swooned from the  
``butterflies fluttering in my tummy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He had a glow about him that was magnetic,'' Ms. Lewinsky  
gushes about watching the president from a distance. ``He exudes a 
sexual energy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She began pursuing brief opportunities to flirt with him along  
rope lines and at a staff party. She read up on Gennifer Flowers' 
account of her own alleged relationship with Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The flirtation was mutual, she says: ``He undressed me with his  
eyes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She says it was her now-famous come-on, in which she lifted her  
jacket to reveal a glimpse of her thong panties, that prompted 
their first sexual encounter on Nov. 15, 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	And it was the president, she says, who initiated their  
late-night, sexual phone chats. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months after their first encounter, on Jan. 21, Ms. Lewinsky  
boldly demanded more emotional intimacy. Clinton provided it. 
According to the book, the president became misty-eyed as he told 
her how anguished he was to learn that day about the death of an 
American soldier in Bosnia. 
</P>
<P>
	``It brought me one step further to falling in love with him,''  
Ms. Lewinsky said. At one point, he suggested he might be divorced 
after leaving office, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Morton says Ms. Lewinsky ``never really considered that he was a  
married man'' until Clinton briefly broke off their trysts in 
February 1996, saying he didn't want to hurt his wife Hillary and 
daughter Chelsea. Ms. Lewinsky's guilt, according to the book, was 
``muted by the exhilaration of the affair'' and by her thoughts 
that the Clintons' marriage might well end when he left office. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton cried the day in May 1997 when he finally broke things  
off for good, Ms. Lewinsky told ABC. ``It was an intense 
relationship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky's low self-esteem, especially her fear that she was  
too fat to be attractive, is a recurring motif. At one point, when 
her earlier affair with a married man in Oregon was discovered, Ms. 
Lewinsky told the wronged wife that ``the relationship had only 
come about because of her insecurity about her weight,'' the book 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky's view of sexuality is unabashedly liberal. It's  
not ``something to hide away in the dark or be ashamed of,'' she 
says. She reveals a three-month romance with a Pentagon employee in 
1996 (at the same time she was secretly meeting the president) that 
resulted in an abortion. She called the procedure ``horrible and 
very depressing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her self-acknowledged sense of melodrama permeates the book. The  
chapter about her questioning by Kenneth Starr's investigators, at 
a suburban Ritz-Carlton, is titled ``Terror in Room 1012.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with the prospect of betraying the president's trust, she  
considered throwing herself out the hotel room window to her death, 
Morton writes. 
</P>
<P>
	She was stung by his harsh tone when the president publicly  
denied sexual relations with ``that woman, Ms. Lewinsky.'' And when 
she learned that Clinton had told a presidential aide she was a 
``stalker'' who threatened her, she told Walters: 
</P>
<P>
	``That was the defining moment when I really knew and fell out  
of love with him.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
