<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 10:12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rock Beat: Paul Westerberg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- There's no escape these days for Paul  
Westerberg. 
</P>
<P>
	When he sits down at the piano and 8-month-old Johnny Paul is  
anywhere within earshot, his son screams to join him. The boy loves 
nothing more than to sit on dad's lap and tunelessly pound the 
keys. 
</P>
<P>
	Westerberg secretly welcomes the distraction, though, and he  
even straps his son on his back sometimes when he's playing guitar. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm already wishing that I can play an instrument better so I  
can teach him something,'' Westerberg says. ``A baby might improve 
my skills. One of these days I may have to sit down and show him a 
scale.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There's been little escape for Westerberg professionally,  
either. Many of his fans won't let go of the boozy, bash-'em-out 
persona he created with the Replacements more than a decade ago. 
The Replacements loved to have a good time, but what set them apart 
was the smart punk at the band's center, the one with a heart and a 
wickedly creative pen. 
</P>
<P>
	That Westerberg hasn't disappeared; he's just grown up. And he's  
opened up, with a strong new album born of the darkness in his 
soul. ``Suicaine Gratifaction'' reveals a songwriter who reaches 
the top of his game when he hits an emotional bottom. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the songs date back to 1996, when Westerberg ended a  
concert tour and returned home to Minnesota. He'd just lost the 
security of his record deal, faced an uncertain future, and he sank 
into a depression. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't have a clue and I sought comfort in my recording  
machine in the basement,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He came up with some of his most starkly beautiful music,  
exploring the mood without wallowing in it. On ``Sunrise Always 
Listens,'' the brooding narrator talks to himself but admits, ``I 
believe I have just started to bore the only guy who's listening.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I was in a very manic mode when the initial part of this  
record was born,'' he said. ``I was not sleeping and becoming sort 
of obsessive and dark.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A series of songs about missed connections reaches an emotional  
depth some of his peers can only hint at. Westerberg also takes a 
hard look at himself and the barriers that a rock 'n' roll 
lifestyle places between him and his fans on ``It's a Wonderful 
Lie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't pin your hopes or pin your dreams,'' he sings, ``to  
misanthropes or guys like me. The truth is overrated, I suppose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Westerberg said the song is addressed to fans and friends who  
have tried but failed to get close to him. ``It was my way of 
saying, `This is the reason why,''' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It sounds like many of these songs were born in the hours before  
sunrise, but Westerberg sticks to daylight. ``I have this theory 
that if it's sad in the afternoon, it will tear your heart out at 
two in the morning,'' he said. ``If you write at two in the 
morning, sometimes at noon it's kind of like, `Oh, that's 
pathetic.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Westerberg took his time turning the songs into a record and  
signing a new deal with Capitol Records. He turned to producer Don 
Was, known for his work with Bonnie Raitt and the Rolling Stones, 
for help. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Was is known for his highly polished sound, that was  
something of an odd choice. But he and Westerberg agreed that Paul 
had finished half the album by himself in his basement and not much 
else was needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like a line drawing as opposed to a painting,''  
Westerberg said. ``It's just one simple line, and to try to add 
color would be to distract from the shape.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The disc's quieter, more contemplative sound -- particularly its  
emphasis on the piano -- will be one more shock to the system for 
old fans obsessed with the Replacements. They might as well get 
over it. Westerberg doesn't spend much time reminiscing about those 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think of it so rarely, except now when I do interviews and  
I'm asked to think about it,'' he said. ``If it were up to me, I'd 
no more think of my old band than I think of my high school 
schoolmates. It's like something I did, it's over with, it was good 
fun and it's gone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Westerberg is wrestling now with whether he wants to perform  
these songs publicly. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never made a batch that lend themselves less to  
performing than these,'' he said. ``It's already been a while and 
some of these are so fragile. I listened to the record again 
recently, late at night, and there was a tear in my eye. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I can distance myself from it and look at it as a work of  
art, I'm very proud of it,'' he said. ``At the time I was doing it 
I wasn't proud, I was just trying to survive the day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They aren't the sort of songs you take to a crowded, noisy bar  
with a rock band. That's all he's known, though, and it's what he 
still likes. So he's trying to find a middle ground. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe I'll hire a dance troupe or something,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
