<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UNC Frustrated As Tourney Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Ed Cota looks around and this is what he  
sees: mistakes, and more mistakes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We go over the same stuff (in practice), but some of the guys  
still ain't getting it,'' the North Carolina point guard said. ``I 
don't know if it's boring to them or what.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This is no time to be bored. The Atlantic Coast Conference  
tournament begins Thursday, and the No. 15 Tar Heels (22-8) are 
two-time defending champions. 
</P>
<P>
	But that does not count for much now. After starting 8-0 and  
winning 12 of their first 13 games, the Tar Heels have taken 
several steps back. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can see if we were out there running the plays correct and  
not playing well, but we're out there looking like chickens with 
our heads cut off,'' Cota said. ``It's like somebody is always 
forgetting the play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cota's comments came in the wake of a 20-point home loss last  
weekend to No. 1 Duke -- a game he called ``an embarrassment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the frustration goes beyond Saturday's loss for Cota, who  
enjoyed playing with the likes of Antawn Jamison, Vince Carter and 
Shammond Williams during consecutive Final Four runs. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, North Carolina's scoring average of 70.6 points a game is  
the lowest in 17 seasons. The team's 47 percent shooting is the 
worst since 1968. And to top it off, the Tar Heels have been last 
in the ACC in turnover margin most of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am frustrated with the way we're playing. I can't believe  
we're playing at this level right now,'' said Cota, who has watched 
the Tar Heels close the regular season with an 8-5 mark. 
</P>
<P>
	``The coaches are trying to have patience with us. I don't know  
if they're frustrated or not, but I know they are disappointed with 
the way we're playing right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Bill Guthridge has said he's pleased, suggesting fans may  
have gotten hopes too high when the team won the Preseason NIT back 
in November with wins over Purdue and Stanford. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told our team before the season started they shouldn't feel  
any pressure to keep any of our streaks going,'' he said. ``For the 
most part, they've worked hard and gone about their business 
hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There were so many question marks. I can't remember a team  
going into the season that had so many question marks as this 
year's team did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	North Carolina has played in 10 of the last 12 ACC title games,  
winning four titles in the '90s. But Cota isn't too sure at this 
point if the Tar Heels can even get by first-round opponent Georgia 
Tech on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tar Heels have been limited to 68 points or less in each of  
their last five games. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Duke and Maryland each scored 81 and 89 points in a  
pair of wins over North Carolina. They are the two teams the Tar 
Heels probably will have to beat to become the first team since the 
North Carolina (1967-69) to win three straight ACC crowns. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, not only is our offense hurting us, but our defense  
is killing us out there. It's like we can't stop nobody,'' said 
Cota. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the younger players said the Duke loss still lingers --  
and that irks Cota. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the guys are mature enough to concentrate on the next  
game and not the past,'' he said. ``If they are that worried about 
the Duke game they will come out fired up and ready to play and 
show some improvement. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we go out there and play another lazy game I don't know  
what our chances are.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
