<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Met Announces 1999-2000 Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The world premiere of American composer John  
Harbison's ``The Great Gatsby'' is the marquee event on the 
Metropolitan Opera's 1999-2000 schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	Artistic director James Levine will conduct the ``The Great  
Gatsby'' on Dec. 20. Based on F. Scott Fitzgerald's novel, Harbison 
composed and wrote the libretto, with Murray Horwitz contributing 
popular song lyrics. 
</P>
<P>
	Dawn Upshaw will sing Daisy Buchanan and Jerry Hadley will sing  
Jay Gatsby. Mezzo-soprano Lorraine Hunt will make her Met debut as 
Myrtle Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
	Another highlight of the season announced Wednesday will be the  
new production of Boito's ``Mefistofele,'' which opens Nov. 6 with 
Samuel Ramey in the title role, Richard Leech as Faust and Maria 
Guleghina as both Margherita and Elena. 
</P>
<P>
	The Met also will present Lehar's ``The Merry Widow'' for the  
first time, starring mezzo-soprano Frederica von Stade in the title 
role, written for a soprano, and Placido Domingo. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be three complete ``Ring'' cycles during the 32-week  
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Levine also conducts ``Tristan und Isolde,'' not heard at the  
Met since the 1983-84 season, beginning Nov. 22. 
</P>
<P>
	The season will opens Sept. 27, with ``Cavalleria Rusticana''  
and ``Pagliacci.'' Domingo, singing Canio in ``Pagliacci,'' will be 
making his 18th opening night performance, breaking Enrico Caruso's 
Met record of 17, set in 1920. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
