<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't Fines Northwest, Delta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government fined Northwest Airlines and  
Delta Air Lines on Wednesday for failing to tell passengers that 
tickets they were buying actually would be filled with service on 
another airline's planes. 
</P>
<P>
	Under so-called code share arrangements, partner airlines can  
market another carrier's flights as their own. That allows the two 
carriers to coordinate service and provide for seamless passenger 
connections. 
</P>
<P>
	But federal rules state the airlines must tell passengers at the  
earliest opportunity that a ticket on Northwest, for example, 
actually will be fulfilled with flights on a code share partner, 
such as the commuter airline Northwest Airlink. 
</P>
<P>
	Transportation Department investigators called reservation  
agents for both Delta and Northwest and found that in a number of 
instances, the agents failed to disclose that a flight would be 
fulfilled with service on a partner carrier -- even when 
specifically asked. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest was assessed a civil penalty of $45,000, half of which  
will be forgiven if the carrier does not commit additional 
violations in the next year. Delta was penalized $25,000. 
</P>
<P>
	While neither carrier admitted any wrongdoing, both agreed to  
cease and desist from violations in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	The code share disclosure violations were Delta's second and  
Northwest's third over the past 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater said he had ordered his  
Aviation Enforcement Office to increase scrutiny in the area. The 
department soon will take action on a rule that would expand 
code-share disclosure requirements. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
