<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury To Decide Fate of Marine Pilot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- An eight-man military jury began  
deliberating manslaughter charges Wednesday against a Marine pilot 
accused of flying recklessly into Italian ski gondola cables, 
sending 20 people to their deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was too low, too fast, too aggressive,'' Maj. Daniel  
Daugherty, a prosecutor, said in his closing statement. ``He was 
outright dangerous. ... He's on a rocket sled through there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Capt. Richard Ashby, 31, of Mission Viejo, Calif., was at the  
controls of the EA-6B Prowler jet when it hit the cable Feb. 3, 
1998, near the Alpine town of Cavalese, Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Frank Spinner said it ``was a training accident  
and nothing more'' caused by a visual misperception that drew Ashby 
too low just before he flew into the cables, suspended about 370 
feet above the valley floor. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury deliberated for about four hours Wednesday afternoon  
and planned to continue Thursday morning. Six jurors must find 
Ashby guilty for there to be a conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby is charged with 20 counts of involuntary manslaughter. He  
also faces one count each of dereliction of duty, failure to plan 
the flight properly, destruction of government property and 
destroying private property. 
</P>
<P>
	He faces 206 years in prison if convicted of all charges.  
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened on the final leg of a 42-minute training  
route the four-man radar-jamming jet flew through the Italian Alps. 
Italians responded by demanding that U.S. landing rights be revoked 
at bases in their country. 
</P>
<P>
	Daugherty said Ashby ignored the mission speed limit of 517 mph  
and was traveling at 621 mph when he hit the cable. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutor, who at one time referred to a chart labeled  
``The Blame Game'' to list Ashby's excuses, also said the pilot 
ignored altitude restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses testified the altitude limit was 2,000 feet; Ashby  
said he thought it was 1,000 feet and didn't know the mission had a 
speed limit. 
</P>
<P>
	While defense experts questioned whether Ashby could know how  
low he was and judge his speed, Daugherty said there were plenty of 
cues. He dismissed the theory that Ashby experienced an optical 
illusion as ``psychobabble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You have the roads, the cars, the houses, the humanity of it  
all,'' Daugherty said. ``Captain Ashby ignores it all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spinner said the case revolves around ``six to eight seconds in  
the life of Captain Richard J. Ashby and a decision he had to make, 
if he was aware of what was going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby's navigator, Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, faces similar  
charges and is scheduled to stand trial this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
