<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Leisure World Wants To Be City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAGUNA HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- Leisure World residents voted to  
turn their retirement enclave into an incorporated city, creating 
what activists call the nation's first gated municipality strictly 
for senior citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	By late Tuesday, 10,336 ballots had been counted with 51.7  
percent voting in favor of cityhood, while 48.3 percent voted 
against. A final count -- including some absentee ballots -- was 
expected today, said Evelyn Bell of the Orange County Registrar of 
Voters office. 
</P>
<P>
	The 15,489 registered voters also elected to rename the city  
Laguna Woods, though the gated portion will be called Leisure World 
at Laguna Woods. 
</P>
<P>
	Proponents of cityhood touted the change as a way to give this  
18,000-member retirement community more control over local issues, 
such as long-term economic goals. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents feared turning the community into a place where  
political leaders would add bureaucratic hassle to their previous 
self-governing system. 
</P>
<P>
	The community, about 50 miles south of Los Angeles, advertises  
itself as the largest retirement center on the West Coast. The 
minimum age for residents is 55, and the average is 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Laguna Woods will be run by a five-member city council that  
begins official operations March 24, taking over for Orange County 
officials who controlled the community's public safety services, 
traffic enforcement, street maintenance and building and planning 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	Laguna Woods officials will also be in charge of social and  
recreational services that had been controlled by the county. The 
transfer of services and name change is not expected to be 
completed until the end of this month, Ms. Bell said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
