<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Intern: Clinton Sorry He Got Caught </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Monica Lewinsky, in an interview clip aired  
today, said she felt President Clinton was ``sorry he got caught'' 
when their affair was revealed to the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky revealed that she felt like a piece of trash'' the  
day Clinton was forced to admit their affair on national television 
and apologized to the nation -- but not to her. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt dirty and I felt used and I was disappointed,'' Ms.  
Lewinsky said in a portion of her interview with Barbara Walters, 
played on ABC's ``Good Morning America.'' The full interview is to 
be aired tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked by Ms. Walters whether Clinton really cared for her, Ms.  
Lewinsky said, ``Some days I think yes and some days I think no.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky was shown on the clip watching Clinton's televised  
apology to the nation last Aug. 17, the day he gave his grand jury 
testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked by Ms. Walters whether she believes Clinton felt remorse,  
Ms. Lewinsky said that as a politician, ``I think he's sorry he got 
caught.'' But she added that ``when I think of the person I thought 
Bill Clinton was, he had genuine remorse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The short portion was the first videotape aired of the  
interview, although partial transcripts have leaked out. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Walters asked the former White House intern whether Clinton  
really cared for her. ``Some days I think yes and some days I think 
no,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	But she also said, ``I felt like a piece of trash'' after  
Clinton gave his Aug. 17 address. ``I felt dirty and I felt used 
and I was disappointed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether Clinton gave the impression that she simply  
serviced him, Ms. Lewinsky replied. ``That was the impression he 
gave.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In material that leaked out earlier, Ms. Lewinksy said she  
regrets her role in causing pain and suffering not only for her own 
friends and family, but for Clinton's family. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've apologized in private to my family and to my friends ...  
I would like to publicly acknowledge that I recognize the pain and 
the suffering that they've gone through because of this,'' Ms. 
Lewinsky says in an interview with ABC News to be aired tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't dream of asking Chelsea and Mrs. Clinton to forgive  
me,'' she says. ``But I would ask them to know that I am very sorry 
for what happened and for what they've been through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady's spokeswoman, Marsha Berry, had no comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Barbara Walters of ABC won the first interview with Ms. Lewinsky  
since the former White House intern's affair with Clinton burst 
into the headlines on Jan. 21, 1998. Ms. Lewinsky, who received 
immunity from prosecution for cooperating with investigators, was 
prohibited from speaking publicly until Independent Counsel Kenneth 
Starr's office gave the go-ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	The interview was timed to help promote her book -- ``Monica's  
Story,'' written with Princess Diana biographer Andrew Morton -- 
which goes on sale Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times reported in today's editions that Ms.  
Lewinsky is so critical of Starr in the book that several of her 
friends and associates fear Starr will try to revoke her immunity 
agreement and prosecute her. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times says she told Morton she was so despondent at her  
treatment by prosecutors who initially confronted her at a hotel in 
suburban Virginia that she briefly considered jumping out of a 10th 
floor window in their presence. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times report said prosecutors had confronted her with a copy  
of her false affidavit in which she swore that she had not had an 
affair with Clinton, even though it had not been filed yet with a 
federal court in Little Rock, Ark. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times said Starr has said his office was sent the affidavit  
anonymously by James A. Moody, a lawyer for Linda Tripp, who had 
obtained it from lawyers for Paula Corbin Jones, who had a sexual 
harassment suit pending against the president at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office learned of the Clinton-Lewinsky affair from Mrs.  
Tripp. The extent, timing and nature of any contacts between 
Starr's office and the Jones lawyers are under review by the 
Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Barry Toiv refused to comment on the  
Lewinsky interview and book. But asked on Tuesday whether Ms. 
Lewinsky's words would finally bring an end to the story, Toiv 
said, ``I think I can safely say 'No' to that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ABC released brief excerpts from the interview on Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``Is Bill Clinton a sensuous, passionate man?'' Walters asked  
the 25-year-old woman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gosh, I'll probably get in trouble for saying this,'' Ms.  
Lewinsky began, before describing the president as ``a very sensual 
man'' who feels conflicted because of his ``strong religious 
upbringing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he struggles with his sensuality because I don't think  
he thinks it's OK,'' she said. ``I think he tries to hold himself 
back. And then can't any more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky had stinging words for her former friend, Mrs.  
Tripp, who secretly tape-recorded their telephone conversations 
about the president and turned them over to Starr's investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	``I pity her,'' Ms. Lewinsky said. ``I would hate to be her.''  
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky said she was drawn to Mrs. Tripp at the Pentagon  
because both of them had worked at the White House, where Ms. 
Lewinsky longed to return. She said she confided the affair to Mrs. 
Tripp after her co-worker kept saying such things as ``You're just 
the type of girl the president would like'' and ``I bet you could 
have an affair with him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Daily News in New York reported in today's editions that Ms.  
Lewinsky was questioned Walters about a brief affair she had with a 
42-year-old Pentagon official after she was assigned there in the 
spring of 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd tease him (Clinton) about it and tell him he had  
competition,'' the paper quoted her as saying on an audio tape of 
part of the Walters interview. 
</P>
<P>
	The Daily News obtained the tape Monday and reported in  
Tuesday's editions on other details contained on it. It was not 
clear how much, if any, of the matters covered on the audio tape 
will be broadcast by ABC, which is trying to determine who leaked 
the audio tape to the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky's relationship with the Pentagon official, who was  
unmarried at the time, has been reported previously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
