<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	German's Execution Delayed  
</P>
<P>
	FLORENCE, Ariz. (AP) -- Amid pleas of mercy from the German  
government, a federal appeals court today ordered Arizona not to 
use the gas chamber to execute a German man whose brother was put 
to death last week. The 9th Circuit Court of Appeals refused to 
issue a stay for Walter LaGrand, 37, who was scheduled to die today 
for his role in the 1982 murder of a bank manager. But the judges 
did say that the gas chamber is cruel and unusual punishment, and 
therefore unconstitutional. The state appealed to the Supreme 
Court, but it was unclear when the execution would proceed. 

</P>
<P>
	Starr Got Lewinsky Memo Early  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Monica Lewinsky has assailed Kenneth Starr's  
office for ``dubious methods'' and raised new questions about the 
origins of his investigation of President Clinton's affair with her 
and the following cover-up. Ms. Lewinsky asserts in ``Monica's 
Story'' that the independent counsel's investigators had obtained a 
copy of her false affidavit denying an affair with Clinton before 
the document had been filed with a court. Starr acknowledges he had 
the affidavit early, but he says he got it from a source other than 
Paula Jones' lawyers. 

</P>
<P>
	Supreme Court Rules on School Care  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Public schools must finance one-on-one nursing  
care for some disabled students throughout the school day, the 
Supreme Court ruled today in a decision that may strain educational 
budgets across the nation. Voting 7-2 in the case of an Iowa 
teen-ager, the court said public financing is required under the 
Individuals with Disabilities Education Act because the federal 
law's exemption for ``medical services'' applies only when a 
doctor's help is needed. 

</P>
<P>
	Anti-Smoking Pill Said To Top Patch  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In the first head-to-head comparison, the  
anti-smoking drug Zyban proved twice as good as the nicotine patch 
in helping people kick the habit, and both together were even more 
effective. Used together, they helped more than 35 percent of 
smokers stay off cigarettes for a year. The patch had disappointing 
results, working no better than a dummy pill or patch. But the 
researchers themselves disagreed over whether the findings were a 
fluke, since other studies have shown the patch works. The maker of 
Zyban paid for the study by University of Wisconsin researchers. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Levies Sanctions in Trade Fight  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration said today that  
more than $500 million worth of European imports will be subject to 
eventual punitive trade sanctions because of an ongoing trade fight 
between the United States and Europe over bananas. The sanctions 
would take effect immediately but would be paid retroactively when, 
and if, a World Trade Organization panel approves the United 
States' request to penalize the importers. The 100 percent punitive 
duties, by doubling prices, could effectively knock products 
ranging from French handbags to German coffeemakers out of the U.S. 
market. 

</P>
<P>
	Aid Agencies Help Kosovo Albanians  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Humanitarian workers took advantage  
of a lull in fighting to rush aid today to thousands of displaced 
ethnic Albanians massed along Kosovo's border with Macedonia. 
Defying NATO warnings, Yugoslav army and Serbian police forces have 
pounded suspected Kosovo Liberation Army rebel positions along the 
border for several days. The fighting has cast increasing doubt on 
the chances for success when suspended peace talks resume March 15 
in France. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate Panel OKs Y2k Lawsuit Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Senate committee today approved a bill aimed  
at curbing what many fear could be up to $1 trillion in lawsuits 
arising from Year 2000 computer failures. The industry-backed 
measure, endorsed by the Commerce Committee on a party-line 11-9 
vote, would limit damages from economic losses, allow a ``good 
faith'' defense for companies trying to make the needed repairs and 
establish a 90-day waiting period for filing suits so companies can 
make those repairs. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Mixed; Dow Closes Down 21.73  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks ended mixed today after technology shares  
rallied from a deep slump in the final hour, pulling broad market 
indexes up with them. At the close, the Dow Jones industrial 
average was down 21.73 at 9,275.88. Declines on the NYSE 
outnumbered advances 1,640-1,306. The Nasdaq composite was up 6.17 
at 2,265.20. 

</P>
<P>
	White House May Help in IOC Scandal  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. Olympic Committee's top official  
sought White House help today in cleaning up the bribery scandal 
from Salt Lake City's successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games. 
USOC President Bill Hybl asked the Clinton administration to bring 
the International Olympic Committee, which picks the host cities, 
under coverage of the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act. The law 
prohibits bribing of foreign government officials. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  
</P>
</TEXT>
