<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP's Herbert Kelley Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REVERE, Mass. (AP) -- Herbert C. Kelley, the head of technical  
services for The Associated Press in Massachusetts and Rhode 
Island, has died. He was 63. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelley died Tuesday of a heart attack at his home on Revere  
Beach. He had worked for the wire service for 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Herb was the best, a class act,'' said John Reid, AP vice  
president for technology. ``He was justifiably proud of all his 
accomplishments during his three decades with the AP, but he was 
even prouder of the people he worked with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kelley began with the AP when it moved stories over land lines  
at 55 words a minute. He helped oversee its transition to the 
computer age, with transmissions via satellite that handle 1,000 
times that amount. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelley rose through the ranks of the Boston office, taking  
charge of northern New England operations and then Southern 
California in 1975. He rose to deputy director of communications 
operations for the entire AP before coming back to Boston in 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelley is survived by daughters Lisa DeGrandis of Boston, June  
Durante of Huntington Beach, Calif., and Kathy Mahoney of Peabody; 
son Herbert of Hopkinton; sister Pat Hawes of Peabody; and seven 
grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	A wake will be at the Buonfiglio Funeral Home in Revere on  
Thursday, followed by a funeral Friday at St. Anthony's Roman 
Catholic Church in Revere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
