<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- A high-ranking army general charged with  
keeping cash-stuffed suitcases seized from drug traffickers was 
removed from his post, President Alberto Fujimori said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Tomas Marky was named the army's second-in-command in  
January. But he was arrested last month after a lieutenant 
imprisoned on drug charges accused him of walking off with three 
suitcases believed to contain $1 million in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope the investigation continues and it will become clear  
what happened,'' said Fujimori, who had previously said he thought 
Marky to be innocent. 
</P>
<P>
	Marky, the highest ranking member of Peru's armed forces ever  
implicated in a drug case, is in prison awaiting trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Peru is one of the world's largest producers of the coca leaf,  
the base ingredient of cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	TUXTLA GUTIERREZ, Mexico (AP) -- Kidnappers freed a Spanish  
businessman and his Mexican fiancee Wednesday after taking them 
captive last week in southern Chiapas state, relatives said. 
</P>
<P>
	The kidnappers reportedly demanded a ransom of $600,000. Family  
members would not comment on whether any payment was made and state 
prosecutors refused to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Riviera, father of kidnap victim Miguel Riviera Gonzalez,  
28, said his son was ``worn out''. 
</P>
<P>
	Masked gunmen seized Riviera Gonzalez and his fiancee, Mayte  
Villatorro, on Thursday outside his family's small furniture store 
in Tuxtla Gutierrez, 430 miles east of Mexico City. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- Nicaragua's army is dispatching  
hundreds of soldiers to combat a wave of kidnappings, allegedly by 
former Contra rebels, Defense Minister Gen. Joaquin Cuadra said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Between 300 and 400 troops will be sent to the Jinotega,  
Matagalpa and Boaco provinces, the area where a civil war was 
fought in the 1980s. Cuadra said former rebels kidnapped more than 
100 people last year, sometimes killing their victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will not engage in a major combat because we are dealing  
with small groups,'' he said. ``But it is necessary to maintain a 
permanent presence there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- An inmate opened fire on fellow prisoners at  
a penitentiary in the northern state of Sinaloa on Wednesday, 
killing one inmate and wounding five others. 
</P>
<P>
	The shooting apparently occurred as part of a dispute among  
inmates at the facility in the state capital of Culiacan, 640 miles 
northwest of Mexico City, local media reported. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear how the inmate obtained the gun, but the  
Television Azteca network cited the incident as ``one more proof 
that guns freely circulate in Mexican prisons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The wounded prisoners were taken to a local hospital for  
treatment, where one was reported to be in serious condition. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- A week after taking over the post, the  
head of Venezuela's cultural office has resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter published Wednesday in local newspapers, Luis Britto  
Garcia said he was quitting because of conflicts with other members 
of the National Culture Council over job appointments. 
</P>
<P>
	Britto Garcia is the second high-level government official to  
resign since President Hugo Chavez took office Feb. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Carmen Ramia, head of the information office, quit last week,  
saying the situation inside her department would have made it 
difficult to realize her goal of promoting civic responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- The Dominican  
Republic's foreign minister joined other countries Wednesday in 
calling for an end to shipments of nuclear waste through the 
Caribbean. 
</P>
<P>
	Caribbean countries are worried about accidents that could  
release radiation, and Foreign Minister Eduardo Latorre urged them 
to band together to lobby international organizations against the 
shipments. 
</P>
<P>
	He said President Leonel Fernandez would bring up the issue  
during a summit of the Association of Caribbean States in the 
Dominican Republic on April 16. 
</P>
<P>
	The 15-member Caribbean Community is also expected to discuss  
the shipments during a meeting in Suriname on Thursday. 
</P>
