<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 06:26:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Backs Nursing Home Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nursing homes would be barred from evicting or  
transferring residents solely because they rely on Medicaid, under 
legislation endorsed by a House subcommittee on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Nursing homes could still decide to stop accepting new Medicaid  
patients. However, such homes would have to notify any new 
residents who might be able to pay their own way at first, that 
they might have to move if they eventually ran out of money and 
needed to rely on the government health insurance program for the 
poor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nursing home residents and their families will not have to  
live with the fear of eviction. Enactment of this legislation will 
remove that threat,'' said Rep. Michael Bilirakis, R-Fla., chairman 
of the House Commerce health and environment subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is expected to reach the House floor later this spring  
and the Senate Finance Committee is scheduled to vote on similar 
legislation later this week. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., a physician, said Tuesday  
that requiring nursing homes to keep Medicaid patients regardless 
of payment levels could have unintended consequences. 
</P>
<P>
	``No new nursing homes are going to be built for Medicaid  
patients,'' said Coburn. 
</P>
<P>
	Coburn said he will offer an amendment that would exempt homes  
from the new rules in states that cut their Medicaid payment rates 
in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	The patient-protection legislation was prompted after one of the  
nation's largest nursing home operators, Vencor Inc., tried last 
year to remove Medicaid patients from some of its homes in several 
states, including Florida and Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Complaints caused the Louisville, Ky.-based company to  
reconsider, and Vencor and nursing home industry groups have 
endorsed the proposed safeguards, along with advocates for the 
elderly. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Vencor executives say inadequate Medicaid payment rates  
are the root of the problem, and have told stockholders they plan 
to try to increase the company's share of wealthy private payers in 
its nursing homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Medicaid, a health insurance program paid for jointly by the  
federal government and the states, generally is thought of as help 
for poor families and children. However, long-term care for older 
Americans in and out of nursing homes accounts for almost a fifth 
of Medicaid's entire cost. 
</P>
<P>
	Two-thirds of elderly nursing home patients rely on Medicaid to  
help pay for their care, and with nursing home costs averaging 
around $40,000 a year, about half who initially pay their own way 
must turn to Medicaid within three to five years. 
</P>
<P>
	On average, state Medicaid programs pay about $27 less per day  
than the amount nursing homes can charge private payers. 
</P>
<P>
	Nursing homes do not have to take Medicaid patients, although  
most now do in part because of the sheer numbers of elderly people 
who must rely on the program. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
