<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 12:35:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Starr Got Lewinsky Memo Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Recounting her story on television and in a  
tell-all book, Monica Lewinsky assails Kenneth Starr's office for 
``dubious methods'' and raises new questions about the origins of 
his investigation of President Clinton's affair with her and the 
following cover-up. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky asserts in ``Monica's Story,'' a book by Princess  
Diana biographer Andrew Morton, that the independent counsel's 
investigators had obtained a copy of her false affidavit denying an 
affair with Clinton before the document had been filed with a 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	In making her first personal attacks on the prosecutor after 13  
months of silence, Ms. Lewinsky raises the prospect that Starr had 
been secretly coordinating with Paula Jones' lawyers to catch the 
president in wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr acknowledges he had the affidavit early, but he says he  
got it from a source other than Mrs. Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	``Understandably, Starr's tactics have been a matter for grave  
public concern,'' her book says. ``The whole exchange about 
immunity was a waste of time except insofar as it exposed the 
dubious methods employed by Starr's investigators.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Associated Press obtained excerpts from the book, due out  
later this week, from a source outside the publishing world. 
</P>
<P>
	In both the book and TV interview, Ms. Lewinsky volunteers  
detail about intensely personal matters in her life, including 
acknowledging in the book that she had an abortion after becoming 
pregnant by another man. That occurred during the latter part of 
1996, while she was still seeing Clinton in secret meetings at the 
White House. 
</P>
<P>
	She also expresses disdain for both Linda Tripp, the friend who  
betrayed her confidences, and the prosecutor who transformed her 
affair into an impeachment crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Independent Counsel Jackie Bennett said today he could  
not comment on the book because his office hadn't seen it. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a document obtained by the AP, Starr told Congress in a  
private letter two months ago that his office had gotten Ms. 
Lewinsky's false affidavit, not from Mrs. Jones' lawyers but rather 
in an unmarked fax that was traced to the office of one of Linda 
Tripp's attorneys, James Moody. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp had previously told Starr's office about the  
affidavit, and ``when we received it we understood that it had been 
provided to us by Mr. Moody,'' Starr wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutor also disputed claims his office had mistreated  
Ms. Lewinsky, saying that while she was ``understandably upset and 
distraught'' by her first encounter with prosecutors, it was not 
due to ``her treatment by this office'' but rather the ``gravity of 
the situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky recounts in unflattering terms her first experience  
with Starr's prosecutors the day they confronted her at a hotel, 
urged her to cooperate with the investigation of Clinton and 
threatened to prosecute her if she didn't. 
</P>
<P>
	She says that encounter was so disturbing that she considered  
hurling herself from the 10th floor window and killing herself. 
</P>
<P>
	She asserts that Starr prosecutor Michael Emmick called her  
attorney, William Ginsburg, during one exchange that day in January 
1998 and ``offered to fax her new attorney a copy of her false 
affidavit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The two FBI agents, however, pulled him roughly away from the  
phone. They realized Ginsburg would instantly understand that the 
OIC had seen a copy before it had been filed, which meant in all 
probability it had come from Paula Jones' lawyers,'' Morton wrote 
based on his interviews with Ms. Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Though her affidavit had not been filed in court, her lawyer had  
sent it to Mrs. Jones' lawyers earlier that day, Ms. Lewinsky 
asserts. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department is investigating whether Starr improperly  
detained Ms. Lewinsky and failed to disclose possible contacts with 
Mrs. Jones' lawyer to the department before it gave Starr 
permission to investigate. 
</P>
<P>
	The book and a separate interview to be aired by ABC tonight  
gave Ms. Lewinsky the first opportunity to tell her story outside 
of a federal grand jury room or the impeachment trial, where she 
testified by videotape. 
</P>
<P>
	In a snippet of the TV interview with Barbara Walters aired this  
morning by ABC, Ms. Lewinsky also questions the sincerity of the 
president's apology for the entire episode, saying she believes he 
was ``sorry he got caught.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky said that she felt like ``a piece of trash'' the  
day Clinton was forced to admit their affair on national television 
and apologized to the nation -- but not to her. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt dirty and I felt used and I was disappointed,'' Ms.  
Lewinsky said. The full interview will be aired tonight on ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked by Ms. Walters whether Clinton really cared for her, Ms.  
Lewinsky said, ``Some days I think yes and some days I think no.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky was shown on the clip watching Clinton's televised  
apology to the nation last Aug. 17, the day he gave his grand jury 
testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked by Ms. Walters whether she believed Clinton felt remorse,  
she said that as a politician, ``I think he's sorry he got 
caught.'' But she added that ``when I think of the person I thought 
Bill Clinton was, he had genuine remorse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The short portion was the first videotape aired of the  
interview, although partial transcripts have leaked out. 
</P>
<P>
	In the earlier material, Ms. Lewinsky said she regretted her  
role in causing pain and suffering not only for her own friends and 
family, but for Clinton's family. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've apologized in private to my family and to my friends ...  
I would like to publicly acknowledge that I recognize the pain and 
the suffering that they've gone through because of this,'' Ms. 
Lewinsky said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't dream of asking Chelsea and Mrs. Clinton to forgive  
me,'' she said. ``But I would ask them to know that I am very sorry 
for what happened and for what they've been through.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
