<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Three Houston Octuplets Go Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- The family of the Houston octuplets danced and  
sang Wednesday as three of the children finally came home after 
spending the first few months of their lives in the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was dancing and rejoicing,'' said the babies' father,  
Ikye Louis Udobi. ``My mother-in-law was kind of singing, rejoicing 
and praising the Lord.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Udobi and his wife, Nkem Chukwu, brought home daughters Ebuka  
and Echerem and son Jioke, who have been among the largest and 
healthiest since their births -- Ebuka on Dec. 8, and the others on 
Dec. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	``They opened their eyes when they got home, signifying, `We're  
home,''' Udobi said. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors said the three are breathing and maintaining body  
temperature on their own and are on full diets of breast milk and 
formula. 
</P>
<P>
	Chima, a sister who also has progressed well, is fighting off an  
intestinal ailment and should be home within a few weeks, Dr. Patti 
Savrick said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chidi and Gorom, both girls, continue to get 24-hour care in the  
neonatal intensive care unit at Texas Children's Hospital. The 
weakest and smallest tot is the only other boy, Ikem, who was back 
on a ventilator after surgery overnight to repair an inflamed 
bowel. 
</P>
<P>
	The smallest octuplet, Odera, born at just 10.3 ounces, died a  
week after birth. 
</P>
<P>
	The three infants at home are living in an open area of the  
family's four-bedroom house in southwest Houston. The parents say 
they're getting help from Ms. Chukwu's mother and members of their 
church. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
