<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 09:35:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kansas City Mayoral Field Narrows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- A businesswoman and Kansas City's mayor  
pro tem won the top primary spots to advance to the March 30 
general election. 
</P>
<P>
	Kay Waldo Barnes, a former member of the City Council who was  
considered the front-runner in a field of six, led the balloting in 
Tuesday's primary with 15,280 votes, or 29 percent, to George 
Blackwood's 13,065, or 25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	One of them will succeed Mayor Emanuel Cleaver, who became the  
city's first black mayor eight years ago and by law could not seek 
a third term. 
</P>
<P>
	Waldo Barnes would become Kansas City's first female mayor if  
she beats Blackwood, a member of the City Council for the past 
eight years. The only other time a woman made it past the primary 
was in 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very exciting for me,'' Waldo Barnes said. ``I feel ready  
for the challenge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another local businesswoman, Janice Ellis, finished third with  
11,206 votes, or 21 percent. She was the only black person on the 
ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	Waldo Barnes, 60, who runs a consulting firm, launched a massive  
campaign, raising about $500,000. She blanketed the city of 430,000 
with her ``Kay for Kansas City'' yard signs and toured 
neighborhoods in a Winnebago, inviting residents inside to discuss 
local issues over a cup of coffee. 
</P>
<P>
	Blackwood, a 59-year-old attorney, was elected mayor pro tem in  
1995. He has served as chairman of the council's Ethics Committee 
and headed a plan to convert Richards-Gebauer Memorial Airport 
south of the city into an international freight center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
