<DOCNO> APW19990303.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 15:21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Dodgers' Sheffield Likes Left Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Gary Sheffield smiled, knowing the  
question was coming. 
</P>
<P>
	No, he said quietly, he didn't object to a move to left field  
because he'll do anything to help the Los Angeles Dodgers win. 
</P>
<P>
	Now 30, Sheffield thinks that because of a reputation that goes  
back to the late 1980s when he was playing for Milwaukee, and 
perhaps because of his high salary, people have preconceived 
notions about him. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Dodgers signed Devon White to play center field during  
the offseason, that meant for certain that Raul Mondesi would move 
back to right, as he preferred, and Sheffield would go from right 
to left. 
</P>
<P>
	Immediately, it was speculated Sheffield would balk at the  
change. 
</P>
<P>
	Never happened, he said. And general manager Kevin Malone  
agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is a team player,'' Malone said. ``I don't know how Gary  
was in the past, I know how he is now. I had heard about his 
reputation. I don't know who this guy used to be. He just wants to 
win. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'll play first, third, wherever. He's been working out hard,  
he's real focused. I've always respected him as a player, I've 
gotten to know and respect him as a person. He's much more cerebral 
than he's given credit for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sheffield set a single-season salary record last year, earning  
more than $14.9 million. His earnings were boosted by a $5 million 
bonus he received for agreeing to a trade from the Florida Marlins 
in May, a trade he has no regrets about now. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm comfortable here, I want to spend the rest of my career  
with the Dodgers,'' he said. ``This is a great organization that 
treats its players right. 
</P>
<P>
	``We go out as one, we've got to think as one. The No. 1 goal is  
to win ball games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sheffield has had two terrific seasons -- 1992 with San Diego  
(.330, 33 homers) and 1996 with the Marlins (.314, 42 homers). But 
he's always been hampered by injuries, and last year was no 
exception -- he missed the final 25 games because of a severely 
sprained ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, he hit .302 with 22 homers, 85 RBIs and 22 stolen  
bases. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ankle's fine,'' he said. ``They say I would have been  
better off breaking it. It took the whole season of working out, it 
took four months for the swelling to go down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sheffield was injured in a rundown between third base and home  
plate, and he believes he learned a lesson from it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being too aggressive gets you hurt,'' he said. ``I think  
that's what's happened to me. That's mainly how my injuries have 
occurred, on the basepaths, trying to make something happen that's 
not there. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time I come into camp, (staying healthy) is my No. 1  
goal. If I can play 150, 160 games, my numbers can be among the 
best in the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Malone certainly agrees.  
</P>
<P>
	``His bat speed compares to anybody,'' he said. ``I've seen him  
carry a team offensively by himself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sheffield admitted his ability in left was one of the few  
question marks on the Dodgers, but added, ``I didn't think twice 
about it, to be honest with you. There's no reason I can't play the 
position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Malone: ``I think he's going to be a natural in left  
field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sheffield, a key member of Florida's World Series-winning team  
in 1997, relishes the role of team leader. He also realizes the 
knock on his reputation won't disappear overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's something I'll have to live with the rest of my life,''  
he said. ``I know I am (a good person). There's no doubt in my 
mind. I feel like I can make a lot of things happen, on and off the 
field. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't look for what kind of numbers I can put up. Numbers  
aren't the most important thing. It's when you produce.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 15:21:02 </DATE_TIME>
