<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 13:55:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Duke Is Favored in ACC Hoops Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Even Duke's challengers are doubtful that  
anyone can beat the top-ranked Blue Devils in the Atlantic Coast 
Conference tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke (29-1) swaggers into the Charlotte Coliseum for the  
four-day event after compiling a record-setting 16-0 league mark 
and 24.3-point average winning margin. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen of Duke's ACC wins were by double digits, and no team  
got closer than eight points against a starting five that all made 
one of the first three all-conference teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody is going to beat Duke. Who is going to beat them?''  
said Virginia coach Pete Gillen. ``As Dave Odom has said, as Bill 
Guthridge has said, it's going to be boring. They're a wrecking 
machine. I hate to say that, but I'm just being frank.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gillen, whose ninth-seeded club lost twice to Duke by 46 points  
in the regular season, even joked that his team might ``take a 
vacation or forfeit'' instead of playing its first-round game 
Thursday night against the Blue Devils. 
</P>
<P>
	``We voted on whether to play the game or not,'' said Gillen.  
``Our seven walk-ons said, `Play the game,' and our six healthy 
scholarship said, `No.' So, we will play. 
</P>
<P>
	``The walk-ons like the meal money, staying at a hotel and  
missing school. Our scholarship guys want to be with their 
girlfriends. But we will be there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Duke is riding a 24-game winning streak and has generally  
toyed with the rest of the ACC all season, history shows that going 
undefeated in league play doesn't necessarily guarantee an ACC 
title. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the previous seven undefeated teams in ACC play went on  
to lose in the tournament, including the two most recent teams -- 
North Carolina in 1984 and '87. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you are the favored team, other teams look at that as a  
great opportunity to get a notch in their belt. And this would be 
something if somebody was to beat Duke. It would be a great 
accomplishment,'' said North Carolina coach Bill Guthridge. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Devils have dominated the ACC regular season in the  
'90s with six championship, but has gone 4-6 in the league 
tournament since winning its only crown of the decade in '92. 
</P>
<P>
	So, coach Mike Krzyzewski is well aware of the pitfalls -- no  
matter how dominant his teams has looked. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of things that can happen,'' said Krzyzewski.  
``At this time of the year you get even more attention than you do 
during the regular season. You can start listening to the wrong 
things. This team has not done that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the other thing is if you change focus, you start  
playing it safe, you don't attack and you don't look to get better. 
Those are also dangerous things that can happen to a team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many believe Duke's closest competition will come from No. 5  
Maryland, a team still with a chance at a No. 1 seed in the NCAA 
tournament if it can knock off the Blue Devils. 
</P>
<P>
	The second-seeded Terrapins (25-4) set a school-record with 13  
wins in the ACC, but still finished three games behind Duke in the 
standings and lost to them by 18 points twice. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've had a great deal of success against us but we've  
beaten them at times in the last five or six years,'' Maryland 
coach Gary Williams said of Duke. ``Nobody has beaten Duke this 
year. If we have a mental block against them then everybody else 
does too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Terrapins would love another shot at Duke, but Williams said  
playing in the Puerto Rico Shootout back in November helped his 
team learn a lesson about looking ahead to opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	``We played three games in three days and we were supposed to  
play Kentucky in the championship game, but it didn't work out that 
way,'' Williams said of the Wildcats losing before the title game. 
</P>
<P>
	``We understand it's a win or go home situation. You don't get  
any takeovers. To look past any game to get ready for a certain 
team is ridiculous at this time of year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland will play the winner of the Florida State-Clemson game,  
which opens the tourney on Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The other two games Friday will pit No. 4 seed Wake Forest  
(16-12) against No. 5 seed N.C. State (17-12), while two-time 
defending champion North Carolina, the No. 3 seed, takes on No. 6 
seed Georgia Tech (15-14) in the nightcap. 
</P>
<P>
	The 15th-ranked Tar Heels (22-8) are gunning for their fifth ACC  
tournament title of the '90s, but are coming off a 20-point home 
loss against Duke and haven't been playing particularly well of 
late. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what has happened. We've gotten too relaxed, too  
comfortable out there,'' UNC point guard Ed Cota said of North 
Carolina's recent slump. ``We're not making the extra passes 
anymore. People are putting their heads down and looking to score 
on their own. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you watched us play early in the season, the ball movement  
we had, how we played defense together, and you watch us know, it's 
totally different.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 05:56:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eugene Robinson Accepts Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The stigma of Eugene Robinson's Super Bowl weekend  
arrest for soliciting oral sex from an undercover police officer is 
likely to linger for years. The charge, though, should disappear by 
the time training camp arrives. 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta Falcons safety, through his attorney, agreed to a  
diversion program Tuesday that would clear his record upon 
completion. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope that Mr. Robinson will do what he needs to do on  
pretrial diversion, and he and this office can move on,'' said Don 
Ungurait, spokesman for the Miami-Dade County Attorney's Office. 
</P>
<P>
	Pretrial diversion programs are often offered to first-time  
misdemeanor offenders and require no plea. Robinson's attorney, 
Jeffery Allen, met with prosecutor Marc Weinstein to strike the 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson did not appear before Judge Teretha Lundy Thomas in  
Miami-Dade County Court for his arraignment on a charge of 
soliciting prostitution. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pro Bowl safety would be ineligible for the program if  
Thomas discovers he has been convicted or charged with a crime in 
Florida or another state. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, Robinson has to have an HIV test and  
complete a course on AIDS. He will be able to complete the program 
in his home state of Washington, where he lives outside Seattle 
with his wife and two children. 
</P>
<P>
	Once Robinson completes the program, charges will be dropped  
after another court hearing. If convicted of solicitation, he could 
have faced a maximum penalty of about 60 days in jail. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say this is the standard resolution for solicitation  
cases,'' Ungurait said. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen did not return phone calls Tuesday seeking comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, 35, was arrested Jan. 30 for allegedly offering an  
undercover officer $40 for oral sex. He was among about 25 people 
caught in a police sting on Biscayne Boulevard, a major street in 
downtown Miami frequented by prostitutes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons lost to the Denver Broncos 34-19 in the Super Bowl  
the next day, with Robinson beaten on the game's pivotal touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, who also played in two Super Bowls with Green Bay and  
leads active NFL players with 53 interceptions, is known as ``The 
Prophet'' for his deep religious beliefs. 
</P>
<P>
	His arrest came about 12 hours after a Christian athletes group  
presented him with an award for high moral character. He later 
returned the award. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
