<HEADLINE> Stocks Slide Further; Dow Off 67.64 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were lower this afternoon after a mixed  
morning, as technology stocks got hit again with a warning about 
softening computer sales. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 67.64 at 9,229.97. The blue-chip index had risen as high as 
9,337.00, up nearly 40 points, before retreating. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators turned lower as technology shares sank.  
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 7.30 at 1,218.20, and the 
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index was down 11.88 at 2,247.15. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues led advancers by 13 to 9 on the New York Stock  
Exchange, where volume came to 591 million shares, even with 
Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	Computer stocks dropped after 3Com Corp., which sells Internet  
data, voice and video systems, said late Tuesday that third-quarter 
operating earnings will be about 23 cents a share, far below 
analysts' previously expected 36 cents. 
</P>
<P>
	The company blamed an ``unexpected slowdown'' in sales to  
businesses in the United States and Latin America. 3Com stock was 
down 3 1/4 at 23 3/4 in leading volume in Nasdaq trading, after dropping 
Tuesday in after-hours trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks were also pushed lower by the bond market, where prices  
sank after the National Association of Purchasing Management said 
its index of non-manufacturing activity rose to 57.0 percent in 
February, from January's 54 percent. But, the group's index of 
non-manufacturing prices eased, to 46.5 percent from 47 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-year Treasury was down 23/32 point at 5.66 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	``The higher interest rates will exacerbate a slower economy, so  
that things are feeling kind of toppy in the stock market here,'' 
said Michael Farr, a partner at Farr, Miller &AMP; Washington in 
Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan restated his  
reservations about President Clinton's proposal to invest a 
significant portion of the nation's Social Security Trust Fund in 
the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	Addressing a Congressional subcommittee this morning, Greenspan  
said such a plan could encourage investments for political reasons 
in companies that aren't well run, or discourage investments in 
companies that could earn the best return for future retirees. 
</P>
<P>
	Investing Social Security funds in the stock market could also  
lead to higher overall interest rates and curb economic growth, 
while doing ``little or nothing'' to make sure the retirement needs 
of the next century are met, Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan's remarks ruffled a market that was already poised to  
continue a sell-off of technology shares while no other sector has 
stepped forward to lead the market higher, said Scott Bleier, chief 
investment strategist at Prime Charter in New York. ``This market 
is locked in a trading range,'' Bleier said. ``You are in the 
process of building some very serious negative sentiment, far more 
negative than we've see in several months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added Farr: ``You're looking to what might be a stimulus for the  
markets, and it's certainly not coming from Mr. Greenspan this 
morning,'' he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
