<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cable Car Case To Go to Jury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A Marine pilot was ``outright  
dangerous'' the day he flew his jet into an Italian ski lift cable, 
killing 20 people, a prosecutor told jurors today. The defense 
countered that it was an accident ``and nothing more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When he violated all these things and didn't know local rules  
and regulations, people died and a $60 million aircraft is in 
ruins,'' said the prosecutor, Maj. Daniel Daugherty, during closing 
arguments at Capt. Richard Ashby's court-martial. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason the accused is guilty ... is he was too low, he was  
too fast, he was too aggressive. He was outright dangerous,'' 
Daugherty said. 
</P>
<P>
	In his closing statement, defense attorney Frank Spinner posed  
the question of whether the tragedy was ``a training accident or 
was it something more?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a training accident and nothing more,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The judge, Lt. Col. Robert Nunley, said the case will go to the  
eight-man jury of Marine officers this afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Testimony in Ashby's manslaughter trial began Feb. 8 and ended  
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby, 31, of Mission Viejo, Calif., was at the controls of an  
EA-6B Prowler jet on Feb. 3, 1998, when it struck the Mount Cermis 
gondola cable near Cavalese, Italy. He is charged with involuntary 
manslaughter and other counts and could get 206 years in prison if 
convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	In his 45-minute summation, Daugherty said the safe conduct of  
the flight depended on Ashby's decisions, but he made bad choices -- 
flying the jet above the 517 mph restriction for the low-level 
training mission, and far below the 2,000-foot altitude limit. 
Ashby's jet hit the cable 370 feet above the valley floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Daugherty argued that Ashby should have known he was flying too  
low and too fast by merely looking around. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have the roads, the cars, the houses, the humanity of it  
all. Captain Ashby ignores it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby testified he didn't know about the mission's speed limit  
and thought the altitude restriction was 1,000 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors contend Ashby intentionally flew too low and too  
fast. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened on the final leg of a 42-minute training  
route through the Italian Alps. Europeans were outraged, and 
Italians demanded that U.S. landing rights be revoked at bases in 
their country. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't recall in 20 years of investigating accidents any  
pilot being held criminally responsible for an accident,'' said 
Jeff Edwards, an investigator who worked for the defense team. ``I 
believe he's very worried.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers have suggested the aviators were charged because  
of political pressure that went as high as the White House. They 
also said Ashby's jet had a malfunctioning radar altimeter, that he 
may have been victim of an optical illusion that made him think his 
jet was higher than it actually was, and that his superiors didn't 
provide up-to-date information on speed and altitude limits. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides agree the gondola cable wasn't marked on the map  
Ashby was issued by the Air Force. Ashby testified last week that 
he didn't know of the ski lift and that he didn't see the cable 
until the last second. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby's navigator, Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, 31, faces similar  
charges and a separate court-martial. Charges against the other two 
crewmen were dismissed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
