<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel Postpones Vote on Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House committee abruptly postponed plans to  
vote on the year's first spending bill after Republican leaders 
ordered members Wednesday to find savings to pay for the emergency 
$1.2 billion measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Appropriations Committee had planned to vote Thursday  
on the legislation, which has money to help hurricane-ravaged 
Central America, aid struggling U.S. farmers and bolster Jordan 
after King Hussein's death. The funding was requested by President 
Clinton, who wants to use this year's expected budget surplus to 
pay for most of it. 
</P>
<P>
	But House leaders, eager to show they are more fiscally  
responsible than Clinton, decided against spending part of the 
surplus in their very first spending measure of the year -- 
especially for a bill dominated by foreign aid. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a general feeling we ought to find offsets'' to pay  
for the bill, said House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, in a 
brief interview. ``It's been a thing we've done'' for emergency 
domestic spending in recent years, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The leadership acted after GOP fiscal conservatives complained  
that the measure should be paid for -- especially because this 
year's expected $109 billion budget surplus comes entirely from 
Social Security trust fund surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we spend money, we won't steal it out of Social Security,  
and that's the first case out of the box,'' said conservative Rep. 
Tom Coburn, R-Okla., who had insisted on finding savings. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska,  
plans to push a similar bill through his panel Thursday. He has 
said his measure will contain enough savings to pay for itself, 
putting added pressure on House leaders to do the same. 
</P>
<P>
	Appropriations panel aides said they already had planned to trim  
defense and foreign aid funds to pay for the $100 million in aid to 
Jordan. But now, they are also hunting for savings to offset $956 
million for Central America and $152 million for American farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Morra, spokeswoman for House Appropriations Committee  
Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla., said the panel might vote on the 
measure next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The bulk of the money is to help Honduras, Nicaragua, El  
Salvador and Costa Rica recover from Hurricane Mitch. The October 
storm, considered the worst natural disaster in the Western 
Hemisphere, killed more than 9,000 people, left more than 3 million 
homeless and destroyed more than $8.5 billion worth of property. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton travels to Central America to view recovery efforts on  
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The agriculture aid is to help U.S. farmers facing a weak export  
market caused largely by Asia's economic problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
