<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House May Help in IOC Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. Olympic Committee's top official  
sought White House help today in cleaning up the bribery scandal 
from Salt Lake City's successful bid for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	USOC President Bill Hybl, in a letter to President Clinton,  
asked the administration to bring the International Olympic 
Committee, which picks the host cities, under coverage of the 
Foreign Corrupt Practices Act. The law prohibits bribing of foreign 
government officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a move would represent an important step in ridding the  
Olympics of the ``global crisis'' resulting from the disclosure 
that Salt Lake's bidders paid more than $1.2 million in trying to 
secure the winning bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``To do any less would mean facing a future that might include  
the loss of the games and noble ideals they profess,'' Hybl said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hybl, who called USOC oversight of Salt Lake's bidders  
``abysmal,'' and Dick Schultz, USOC's executive director, pledged 
that such vote-buying would not recur. 
</P>
<P>
	They also outlined reforms for the organization, including a ban  
on bid-city assistance funds for IOC members and foreign athletes, 
and stricter USOC controls over U.S. cities bidding for the 
Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The USOC will increase participation by Olympic-level athletes  
in its decision-making and place a permanent staff member in Salt 
Lake to oversee organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	The recommendations were among a series of proposals Monday from  
an ethics panel, led by former Senate Majority Leader George 
Mitchell, that found the IOC had fostered ``this mess'' by 
accepting increasingly lavish gifts from communities trying to land 
the Olympic Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The two USOC officials, in a telephone call early Wednesday,  
told IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch about the USOC's changes 
and the White House request. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was pleased we would call and tell him what we were going  
to do,'' Schultz said. 
</P>
<P>
	USOC leaders said they would wait for the IOC to carry out its  
own promised reforms at a special general assembly March 17-18 in 
Lausanne, Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine IOC members have resigned or been expelled, and at least 19  
more remain under investigation. The IOC had 115 members before the 
scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Two former Olympic stars from the United States said the IOC had  
to continue to move quickly and forcefully. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do hope the IOC continues to clean its house,'' said Olympic  
track champion Jackie Joyner-Kersee, now a special assistant to 
Hybl. 
</P>
<P>
	Joyner-Kersee and four-time Olympic swimming gold medalist John  
Naber said athletes were upset over tales of IOC members receiving 
expensive gifts, lavish travel, college help for their families and 
cash payments. 
</P>
<P>
	``For athletes, the Olympic Rings are a dream. They may have  
been tarnished, but for the athletes the rings must still shine,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Naber, a TV commentator and head of a U.S. Olympic alumni  
association, said anyone who ``willfully and intentionally'' broke 
IOC rules ``should immediately and forevermore lose the right to 
make those rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added, ``I'm not sure we're finished yet with the  
bloodletting.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
