<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New York Is Heart Attack Captial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	If you can make it in New York, maybe you really can survive  
anywhere. 
</P>
<P>
	A researcher at the University of California at San Diego says  
people visiting New York City are 34 percent more likely to die of 
a heart attack than if they'd visited another town. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being in New York may be good for the rest of you, but leave  
your heart in San Francisco,'' said psychologist Nicholas 
Christenfeld, who is to present his findings Friday at a meeting of 
the Society for Behavioral Medicine in San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven million New Yorkers aren't immune, either. Big Apple  
dwellers are 55 percent more likely to die of a heart attack than 
people living in other U.S. cities, Christenfeld said. When they 
leave the hustle and bustle of the city, the risk drops 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Fran Reiter, president and chief executive of the New York  
Convention and Visitors Bureau, called the study silly and offered 
Christenfeld this characteristic New York advice: ``Get a life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Christenfeld based his conclusions on 20 million U.S. death  
certificates from 1985 to 1994, focusing on heart attack 
fatalities. 
</P>
<P>
	He studied New Yorkers who died in the city; non-New Yorkers who  
died while visiting the city; and New Yorkers who died while 
traveling out of the city. About 44,000 tourists and the same 
number of New Yorkers died of heart attacks during the decade 
examined. 
</P>
<P>
	He compared the heart attack deaths against those in other  
states and ruled out other possible explanations, including age, 
sex and race. 
</P>
<P>
	Christenfeld made similar analyses for residents and visitors to  
the country's 10 other largest cities: Los Angeles, Chicago, 
Houston, Philadelphia, San Diego, Dallas, Phoenix, Detroit, San 
Antonio and San Jose. Typically, visitors to those cities had about 
a 1 percent higher rate of coronary deaths, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	While the findings do not identify what it is about New York  
that leads to the increased risk, Christenfeld says stress is the 
likely factor. 
</P>
<P>
	``New York gives you the full experience -- stress, excitement,  
pressure, density,'' he said. ``This won't cause a heart attack in 
a healthy young person, but if you're at high risk and teetering on 
the edge of a heart attack, it could push you over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Richard Stein, a spokesman for American Heart Association,  
questioned the findings. 
</P>
<P>
	``The researchers suggested that New Yorkers live in a more  
stressful environment, but there's nothing in the data that 
indicates that this is stress,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are 400 or 500 possible explanations for this. And if it  
is stress, you certainly wouldn't want to move. Moving is one of 
the most stressful things you can do in life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The results came as no surprise to Sue Schonman, a broker who  
has been commuting to New York from Stirling, N.J., for the past 
nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to do this every day!'' she said, pressing through the  
crowds to catch a train. ``You have to endure a three hour commute 
here just to have a life. Years of this really take it out of 
you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Ward Casscells of the University of Texas-Houston Medical  
School said the study was ingenious for examining a transient risk, 
not long-term factors like smoking or poor diets. 
</P>
<P>
	He said business and pleasure travelers to New York engage in  
activities which increase their risk temporarily -- lugging around 
heavy suitcases, eating fatty meals, rushing to appointments, 
active evenings. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a heart-stopping city,'' he said. ``It's going to  
stimulate you, maybe to death.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
