<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amway Plans New Web site in Sept. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Amway may be venturing into the faceless world  
of the Internet, but the direct-selling giant will still depend on 
real people to promote its business online. 
</P>
<P>
	Amway, known for its cheery salespeople who sell household goods  
to friends in their living rooms, announced today that it will 
launch a new Web site, Quixtar.com, in September. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the latest move by direct sellers to broaden the way they  
pitch their products. Avon has begun opening retail stores. Last 
month Tupperware announced it would offer its food storage products 
online by the end of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	``Going door-to-door, to people's homes, is more difficult today  
than ever before. More people just don't have time,'' said David 
Rush, who works at the retail consulting firm Kurt Salmon 
Associates in Atlanta. ``The Internet is a way to knock on 
someone's door or have them knock on your door when they have 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amway's move online isn't a reach for the Ada, Mich.-based  
company. It has already solved one of the biggest challenges faced 
by Internet retailers -- it has an established distribution network 
in place. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also has a built-in promotional staff -- its army of  
3 million eager sales representatives, who have already started 
touting the new Web site to their customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Amway already operates an Amway.com site as a promotional  
vehicle. It decided against using its own name for the new site 
because it plans to sell thousands of goods and services from other 
companies. Quixtar.com will also be filled with familiar Amway 
names, such as Nutrilite vitamins and SA8 laundry detergent. 
</P>
<P>
	This new sales approach is a big change for Amway. Founded in  
1959, the company has long prided itself on its network of 
representatives using face-to-face meetings -- whether at a 
neighbor's house or at the local coffee shop -- to woo business. 
</P>
<P>
	Amway's salespeople are known for their almost evangelical  
spirit, but the company says they won't lose commissions to the Web 
site. 
</P>
<P>
	Salespeople will sign up their customers to become ``members''  
of Quixtar.com, which will allow them to order goods online, some 
at discounted prices. The salespeople will get a commission from 
those orders. 
</P>
<P>
	Salespeople will continue to encourage their customers to become  
Amway representatives themselves and will continue to get a 
percentage of the commissions earned by their recruits. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also hopes the Web site will broaden its reach.  
Anyone, regardless if they are a member or not, can purchase goods 
on Quixtar.com. The profits from such sales will be randomly 
assigned to Amway representatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Amway's move online comes as the company looks for new avenues  
of growth. Its representatives' pep rallies and motivation meetings 
haven't helped boost business in the last year, especially in 
financially strapped Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	Amway's sales for the year ended in August 1998 fell 18 percent  
to $5.7 billion. About 70 percent of Amway's operations take place 
outside North America. Amway, which is privately held, doesn't 
disclose profits. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 13:16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lewinsky May Face McDougal Subpoena </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Whitewater figure Susan McDougal's lawyers are  
weighing whether to subpoena Monica Lewinsky and another figure 
from the impeachment drama to testify at her upcoming trial on 
charges of obstructing the Whitewater investigation, sources 
familiar with her case say. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a move would likely draw public interest to Mrs. McDougal's  
trial, set to begin next week in Little Rock, Ark., but the sources 
said they expected the trial judge would have to rule on the 
controversial idea. 
</P>
<P>
	The sources, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said Mrs.  
McDougal's defense team is discussing whether to subpoena Ms. 
Lewinsky and Julie Hiatt Steele to testify about their experiences 
with prosecutor Kenneth Starr. Both women have criticized the 
tactics of the independent counsel investigating President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal, a former business partner of Clinton and his  
wife, Hillary, is to be tried in federal court on criminal contempt 
and obstruction of justice charges for refusing to cooperate with 
Starr in the Whitewater investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The sources said subpoenas have not yet been requested from U.S.  
District Judge George Howard Jr., who is overseeing the trial, but 
that Starr's office was aware of the defense team's idea. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Independent Counsel Jackie Bennett said Tuesday he could  
not comment on the matter. Attorney Mark Geragos, who represents 
Mrs. McDougal, also declined comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Summoning Ms. Lewinsky could transform Mrs. McDougal's trial  
from a sideshow in the long-running Whitewater investigation to a 
major event. Mrs. McDougal's lawyers probably would have to show 
that Ms. Lewinsky and Ms. Steele have testimony directly relevant 
to the alleged offenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal, who along with her late ex-husband, James, formed  
the Whitewater land venture with the Clintons, is charged with 
defying a judge's order and refusing to answer Starr's questions 
before a federal grand jury investigating Whitewater. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McDougal has repeatedly said she refused to answer Starr's  
questions because she did not trust the prosecutor, a Republican, 
and believes Starr has waged a vendetta against the Clintons. She 
has said she believed Starr would prosecute her if she failed to 
deliver damaging evidence against the Clintons, adding that she 
knows of no illegal acts by the first family. 
</P>
<P>
	But her former husband, a longtime Clinton supporter who  
defended the first family for years, reversed course a year and a 
half before his death and testified that the president and first 
lady were involved in wrongdoing in their Arkansas business 
dealings. 
</P>
<P>
	The sources said Mrs. McDougal's legal team would like to use  
testimony from Ms. Lewinsky and Ms. Steele to argue that their 
experiences bore out their client's fears about cooperating with 
Starr. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky has alleged that Starr's prosecutors, during their  
initial encounter with her, threatened her with prosecution if she 
refused to cooperate against the president, kept her at a hotel for 
hours and urged her not to call her lawyer. Ms. Lewinsky also 
alleges they urged her to wear a body wire to try to implicate 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	After months of tortuous negotiations, the former White House  
intern struck a deal to cooperate with Starr in exchange for 
immunity from prosecution, but she harbors bitterness toward him. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele was charged earlier this year with three counts of  
obstruction of justice and one of making a false statement for 
providing testimony that cast doubt on her former friend Kathleen 
Willey's allegation that Clinton made an unwanted sexual advance. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr alleged he has evidence showing Ms. Steele made up her  
account. 
</P>
</TEXT>
