<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cargo Ship Runs Aground Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YACHATS, Ore. (AP) -- The bow section of a burned and broken  
cargo ship ran aground again today after a storm ripped the 
oil-laden hulk free from the tug that was towing it out to sea for 
burial in deep water. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's back on the beach,'' said Coast Guard Lt. j.g. Mathew  
Brewer. ``We're going to go out and try to reconnect with her and 
take her back out before it hardens back in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The broken-off bow of the New Carissa ship was mired in the sand  
several hundred yards off a rocky stretch of coast between Waldport 
and Yachats. 
</P>
<P>
	Within hours of the grounding, sticky tar balls began showing up  
on the beach, apparently from the bow's tanks that are still 
holding up to 130,000 gallons of heavy bunker fuel. Booms were 
being set up at nearby Alsea Bay to protect the environmentally 
fragile estuary where the Alsea River flows into the ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	Huge storm swells were delaying efforts to bring in another tug  
and there was no estimate when another salvage operation might take 
place. 
</P>
<P>
	The tug Sea Victory had laboriously dragged the bow section off  
the coast where it first ran aground, about 60 miles south of the 
spot where it ran aground again today. The tug had made it 50 miles 
to sea when its 10-inch-diameter tow line snapped in Tuesday 
evening's storm. 
</P>
<P>
	Unable to keep up with the broken bow as wind and waves carried  
it back to shore, the tug lost sight of it during the night. 
</P>
<P>
	As the bow drifted toward the coast, cleanup crews as far north  
as Newport, about 100 miles southwest of Portland, got ready for 
the threat that a second grounding could spill the 130,000 gallons 
of thick, gooey oil still carried in the bow's fuel tanks. 
</P>
<P>
	Stormy seas carried the 640-foot New Carissa aground Feb. 4  
while the ship waited to enter Coos Bay to pick up a load of wood 
chips. Stuck in the pounding surf, it eventually started leaking 
some of the 400,000 gallons of oil it carried as fuel for its 
engines. 
</P>
<P>
	Demolition crews were able to burn off some of the ship's oil,  
but the ship broke in two, spilling 70,000 gallons. At least 48 
birds have died from exposure to oil. 
</P>
<P>
	Efforts to tow the bow section out to sea started Friday. The  
tug slowly hauled the hulk through two coastal sandbars before 
pulling it out to open water Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Milwee, salvage consultant to the ship's Japanese owners,  
said $10 million has been spent to date on the operation, with much 
more to come. The cost is being born by the ship's insurer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oregon Division of State Lands will likely lead an  
environmental assessment of options for what to do with the 
220-foot stern section, still stuck on the beach near Coos Bay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
