<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fishermen Sue To Protect Steelhead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GRANTS PASS, Ore. (AP) -- Sport fishermen and environmentalists  
sued Wednesday to force the federal government to list southern 
Oregon and Northern California steelhead as a threatened species. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court in San Francisco  
against the National Marine Fisheries Service closely parallels one 
in Portland that forced the agency to list coho salmon in coastal 
Oregon as a threatened species last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Earthjustice Legal Defense Fund filed the lawsuit.  
</P>
<P>
	Just as they had with coho salmon, the fisheries service  
initially recommended steelhead in the Klamath Mountains Province 
and the Northern California unit merited protection under the 
Endangered Species Act. As with coho, the agency decided to hold 
off the listing because of state efforts initiated by Oregon Gov. 
John Kitzhaber and followed to a lesser degree by California. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oregon Salmon Plan emphasized voluntary efforts by private  
landowners to restore and protect spawning habitat, a sharp 
departure from the Endangered Species Act, which imposes penalties 
for destroying habitat and protected species. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Endangered Species Act does not permit the federal  
government to make a decision not to list a species on the grounds 
that there are state conservation efforts in effect when those 
state conservation efforts are voluntary or unimplemented,'' said 
Mike Sherwood, an attorney for the Earthjustice Legal Defense Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisheries Service spokesman Brian Gorman said the coho reversal  
and the latest lawsuit did not change the agency's feeling that the 
Oregon Salmon Plan represents a better way to save species from 
extinction. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're convinced this approach of getting grassroots support  
through conservation plans is the right way to go,'' Gorman said. 
``It appears to be working in some areas of Oregon.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
