<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Davidson Deal To Buy Team Finalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- William Davidson has taken on the monumental  
task of rebuilding the Tampa Bay Lightning. 
</P>
<P>
	The owner of the NBA's Detroit Pistons finalized his purchase of  
the Lightning and the lease for Tampa's Ice Palace on Wednesday, 
reportedly for around $110 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our main attraction was the arena, probably even more than the  
hockey team,'' Davidson during a news conference at the Ice Palace 
on Wednesday. ``I've been a longtime hockey fan. The hockey we like 
... I won't say we love it yet, but that remains for the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pending approval from the NHL Board of Governors, Davidson will  
take over a struggling Tampa Bay franchise that is headed for the 
NHL's worst record for the second consecutive season. 
</P>
<P>
	Davidson is acquiring the team from Art Williams, who had bought  
the franchise last May for $117 million. Williams estimates he will 
loss $20 million this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is with mixed feelings we have decided to sell the Tampa  
Bay Lightning,'' Williams said in a statement. ``Certainly, we 
didn't do all that we set out to do. I believe we left the 
franchise in better shape than we found it a year ago and I'm proud 
of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lightning are also struggling at the gate, with an  
attendance average of 10,802, 55 percent of capacity at the 
19,758-seat Ice Palace. 
</P>
<P>
	``The building was a key in the equation, but at the end of the  
day it starts with your sports team,'' said Tom Wilson, the point 
man for Davidson in the transaction. ``We realize that hockey today 
is a dangerous investment. Energies, efforts and focus are going 
into the hockey team. We may have a great, very successful arena, 
but at the end of the day if the team is doing well, everybody 
looks favorable on us. If the team is struggling, then it seems 
like we're all struggling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams entered into a purchase agreement for the debt-ridden  
team from the Japanese-based Kokusai Green on May 18, 1998. The NHL 
Board of Governors approved the deal on June 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Davidson appeared to be the frontrunner to obtain the Lightning  
last year before Williams' successful bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bill (Davidson) has taken companies that were struggling and  
turned them around. That's our goal here,'' Wilson said. ``We think 
it's a tremendous opportunity for us. We hope its a tremendous 
opprtunity for you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davidson is the principal owner of Palace Sports and  
Entertainment Inc. and the managing partner of the Pistons. The 
organization also owns the Palace of Auburn Hills, the WNBA's 
Detroit Shock and the International Hockey League's Detroit Vipers. 
</P>
<P>
	Davidson plans on completing the current season before deciding  
if there will be any changes involving key Lightning management 
officials, including coach-general manager Jacques Demers, 
assistant general manager Jay Feaster and senior advisor to the 
general manager Cliff Fletcher. 
</P>
<P>
	``What Mr. Davidson is saying is, this is a business and we're  
going to be run like a business,'' Demers said. ``There is no 
insurance. What I heard today is they're going to build. What I 
heard was positive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deal also includes control of six acres of land located near  
the Ice Palace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
