<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans, Retreat / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures retreated Wednesday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade as a two-day rally prompted increased 
farmer selling of ample stored supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers were taking advantage of sharply higher prices seen  
earlier in the week to get rid of crops that have seen little sign 
of increasing in value over the past few months, as weak demand 
walks hand-in-hand with large world supplies. There also was less 
concern about recent hot, dry weather in South America, as 
forecasters predicted beneficial weekend rains in corn and soybean 
growing regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat retreated on perceptions cool, wet weather in the winter  
wheat belt would benefit young crops by slowing the rapid pace of 
development and providing needed moisture, analysts said. The 
losses were contained, however, by continued underlying strength 
following a rebound in export demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans fell under pressure from a worsening currency crunch in  
Brazil, which may lead to increased selling of competing crops 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn followed wheat and soybeans lower.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for May delivery fell 3 1/4 cents to $2.60 1/2 a bushel; May  
corn fell 1 cent to $2.14 3/4 a bushel May oats fell 3/4 cent to $1.04 1/2; 
May soybeans fell 3 3/4 to $4.67 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while feeder cattle retreated, lean hogs were lower and 
pork bellies were higher. 
</P>
<P>
	April live cattle rose .55 cent to 68.25 cents a pound; March  
feeder cattle were down .30 cent to 73.10 cents a pound; April lean 
hogs were down .50 cent to 42.55 cents a pound; March pork bellies 
were up .73 cent to 48.50 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
