<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador's Currency Plunges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Ecuador's currency, the sucre, plunged  
Wednesday as traders were unnerved by rumors the government planned 
to seize dollar bank accounts to buy sucres and concern over a huge 
budget deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	The sucre's value dropped by 17 percent in a wild day of  
trading, closing at 12,000 per dollar. It started the day at 
10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, the sucre has lost 43 percent of its value.  
</P>
<P>
	The Central Bank intervened in the money market, buying $5  
million in sucres to bolster the sagging currency and promised to 
buy more sucres if needed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I make a call to ignore unsubstantiated rumors about a  
possible seizure of foreign currency and other rumors that only 
generate nervousness,'' Central Bank President Luis Jacome told a 
hastily arranged news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Three weeks ago, Ecuador allowed its currency to float to stave  
off speculators from the battered sucre. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were also unappeased by President Jamil Mahuad's  
announcement late Tuesday of economic measures to cut public 
spending and boost tax revenues to cut a giant budget deficit, 
Francisco Cano, a trader at Aserval Bank, said. 
</P>
<P>
	The measures would limit public servants' salaries to $5,000 a  
month or less, accelerate privatizations and boost revenues through 
tax reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecuador is embroiled in its worst economic crisis in the past 20  
years due to falling oil prices and $2.6 billion in damage caused 
by the freakish El Nino weather last year. It is running a fiscal 
deficit of $1.2 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
