<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Lighter Side of Business /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHEN A STAR EMPLOYEE FADES: Sometimes even the best employees go  
through a slump and their usually stellar performance slips. 
Management consultant Personnel Decisions International has 
suggestions to help bosses re-energize these workers. First, let 
the employee know in a non-accusing manner that there's been a 
change, and ask the employee how he or she sees the situation. 
Second, try to find out the reasons for the change -- is there a 
problem in the employee's personal life, or is something going on 
at work? Once the problems have been identified, involve the 
employee in finding a solution. And keep in mind that expressing 
appreciation will help motivate him or her. 

</P>
<P>
	THE LOWDOWN ON CHOCOLATE: Many people consider Consumer Reports  
the place to go for information about the best cars, dishwashers, 
table saws, child safety seats and other staples of life. But the 
March issue of the magazine goes off in a more decadent direction -- 
chocolate. High-priced brands like Teuscher and Godiva are compared 
with household names like Hershey and Nestle. And for the most 
part, the pricier treats had the highest ratings. Roberta 
Karpatkin, president of magazine publisher Consumers Union, says 
the testing staff probably enjoyed working on this project more 
than most others. 

</P>
<P>
	PRODUCT PLACEMENT: Did you like that car you saw in a movie, or  
the sofa you saw on that TV show? Chances are that the manufacturer 
paid thousands of dollars to get it there, hoping to elicit exactly 
that response from audiences. Richard Heslin, a Purdue University 
psychology professor, says this practice, known as product 
placement, is an effective form of advertising because, ``when we 
watch a movie or something on television, our defenses are down and 
we become more receptive to the messages that are coming at us.'' 
Manufacturers know that even if you don't see or notice labels or 
brand names when you're watching a movie or TV program, you might 
see the product in a store later and decide to buy it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
