<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smithsonian Africa Show Is Revamped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seven years after closing its antiquated  
exhibit on Africa, the Smithsonian Institution is preparing a new 
look at the continent's geography, history, culture and people. 
</P>
<P>
	``This exhibition is going to present Africa in a new light  
based on the most recent scholarship,'' said Sulayman Nyang, a 
Howard University professor and the lead developer of the new 
exhibit, which is scheduled to open in December at the National 
Museum of Natural History. ``We have avoided all the booby traps of 
generalization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of people participated during the years, since 1992,  
that the new exhibit has been under development, Nyang said, 
providing answers to the question: ``What do Africans want to tell 
Americans about what it means to be African.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, decisions on what to include and leave out came only  
after countless hours of listening to the ideas and suggestions of 
individuals, said Natural History Museum Director Robert Fri. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit will include personal accounts from contemporary  
interviews, as well as proverbs, prayers, folk tales and oral 
epics, Fri said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new exhibit occupies the same general area as the old  
African hall, which had come under criticism for generalities and 
inaccuracies. 
</P>
<P>
	The main focus of the $5.5 million project is a permanent new  
Hall of African History and Culture. It will open Dec. 15, 
occupying 6,500 square feet on the museum's second floor. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the exhibit hall, an Internet connection will be  
in place through which people can study the exhibit from afar and 
even learn more detail than can be presented at the museum itself. 
The exhibit will be kept up to date with continuing performances, 
seminars, lectures and program changes. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit will begin, as did humankind, with the early  
hominids of Africa's Olduvai Gorge. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the history exhibits will be looks at the Nile cultures of  
Egypt and Nubia, the great Mali empire, the Almoravids of North 
Africa who fused African and Islamic culture and invaded Spain and 
Portugal, the rise of the slave trade and history in the making in 
South Africa today. 
</P>
<P>
	A living spaces gallery provides a glimpse at the diverse  
cultures of Africa from a busy Benin city to a rural Somali home. 
Visitors hear the voices of Somali women as they construct a 
portable house. 
</P>
<P>
	The African diaspora, the wide scattering of people throughout  
the world, especially through the slave trade, is presented. 
Included is a section in the words of Olaudah Equiano, who was 
enslaved in what is now Nigeria, sold to a Royal Navy officer and 
in 1789 wrote a book about his experiences. 
</P>
<P>
	The small Freedom Theater, which seats about 20, will provide  
film and the words of such leaders as the Americans W.E.B. DuBois, 
Martin Luther King Jr. and Malcolm X, the Africans Kwame Nkrumah 
and Bishop Desmond Tutu and others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
