<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New York Is Heart Attack Captial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	New York City will break your heart.  
</P>
<P>
	A researcher at the University of California at San Diego says  
tourists who visit New York are 34 percent more likely to die of a 
heart attack than visitors to other cities. 
</P>
<P>
	The people who live there aren't safe, either. New Yorkers are  
55 percent more likely to die of a heart attack in their hometown 
than people living in other U.S. cities, said psychologist Nicholas 
Christenfeld. 
</P>
<P>
	New Yorkers' risk of dying of a heart attack drops by 20 percent  
when they are outside the city. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being in New York may be good for the rest of you, but leave  
your heart in San Francisco,'' said Christenfeld, who will present 
his findings Friday at a meeting of the Society for Behavioral 
Medicine in San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	Christenfeld based his data on U.S. death certificates from 1985  
to 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	While the findings do not identify what it is about New York  
that leads to such a high risk, Christenfeld said the stress is 
likely the factor. 
</P>
<P>
	``New York gives you the full experience -- stress, excitement,  
pressure, density,'' he said. ``This won't cause a heart attack in 
a healthy young person, but if you're at high risk and teetering on 
the edge of a heart attack, it could push you over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Christenfeld studied New Yorkers who died in the city; non-New  
Yorkers who died while visiting the city; and New Yorkers who died 
while traveling out of the city. About 44,000 tourists and the same 
number of New Yorkers died of heart attacks during the decade 
examined. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar analyses were conducted for residents and visitors to  
the 10 largest U.S. cities besides New York: Los Angeles, Chicago, 
Houston, Philadelphia, San Diego, Dallas, Phoenix, Detroit, San 
Antonio and San Jose. 
</P>
<P>
	Typically, visitors to other cities have about a 1 percent  
higher rate of coronary deaths, according to Christenfeld. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Stein, a spokesman for the American Heart Association  
and Chief of Cardiac Prevention and Rehabilitation at Lenox Hill 
Hospital in New York, said he wasn't sure what the results meant. 
</P>
<P>
	``The researchers suggested that New Yorkers live in a more  
stressful environment, but there's nothing in the data that 
indicates that this is stress,'' Stein said. ``At the end of the 
day, it's clear that the take home message is you get your heart 
disease by how you live not where you live.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fran Reiter, president and chief executive of the New York  
Convention and Visitors Bureau, said Christenfeld ``has really got 
to get a life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``New York is the most exciting place in the world,'' she said.  
``People flock here for the experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However the results came as no surprise to Sue Schonman, a  
broker who has been commuting to New York from Stirling, N.J., for 
the past nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to do this every day!'' she said, pressing through the  
crowds to catch a train. ``You have to endure a three hour commute 
here just to have a life. Years of this really take it out of 
you.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
