<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Helps Torricelli Raise $2M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- President Clinton paid back the loyalty of  
one of his staunch impeachment defenders Wednesday, helping 
Democratic Sen. Robert Torricelli raise $2 million for a 
re-election campaign three years away. 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing at a $1,000-per-ticket reception for Torricelli's 2002  
re-election bid, Clinton praised him as a ``ferocious advocate'' 
for New Jersey and human rights and thanked him for his support. 
``He has been my friend in good times and bad, and I will never 
forget it,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The event at the New Jersey Performing Arts Center drew 1,500  
guests who gave the maximum amount. Some supporters gave donations 
but did not attend. 
</P>
<P>
	While the White House did not cast Clinton's appearance as an  
expression of gratitude for Torricelli's unwavering loyalty during 
Clinton's impeachment, it acknowledged that the president wanted to 
show his support for the junior senator from New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	``The senator asked the president to come,'' said White House  
spokeswoman Amy Weiss, and Clinton agreed because Torricelli had 
been ``an avid defender of the president's policies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also was the keynote speaker for a 1996 Torricelli  
fund-raiser for a campaign that ultimately raised more than $9 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Torricelli spoke before the president Wednesday night.  
</P>
<P>
	``In all the times of all the nations of the world, no nation  
has ever enjoyed the economic circumstances we enjoy,'' Torricelli 
said, embracing Clinton's plans to strengthen the nation's 
education and retirement systems for the next century. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope every member of Congress ... will join hands with us,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Torricelli, who heads the Democratic Senatorial Campaign  
Committee and has urged first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton to run 
for Senate in New York, joked that he deserved a title befitting 
the speculation that has surrounded her future plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am the man who created and am managing the Hillary Rodham  
Clinton campaign for the United States Senate,'' he quipped. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those attending were actors Kevin Spacey and Joe Pesci,  
and singers Cissy Houston and Gloria Gaynor. Ms. Houston -- mother 
of pop diva Whitney Houston -- performed the national anthem, while 
Ms. Gaynor serenaded Clinton with her signature song. ``I Will 
Survive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Anybody who thinks they've survived can stand up,'' Gaynor  
said, and sooon the entire crowd was on its feet, swaying and 
singing along with the refrain. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, who was listening backstage, said he had wondered  
whether it was more appropriate for him to sing along with ``I Will 
Survive'' -- drawing a hearty laugh from the audience -- or ``Never 
Can Say Goodbye.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the same donors planned to attend a second, $1,000  
fund-raiser Thursday at the East Brunswick Hilton for former U.S. 
Sen. Bill Bradley's presidential campaign. Though supporters of 
Bradley and Torricelli acknowledge the timing was unfortunate, 
neither camp expected to suffer financially. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
