<DOCNO> APW19990303.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 09:25:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Bites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	``Trail'' (Bohemia Beat) -- Jimmy LaFave  

</P>
<P>
	Jimmy LaFave's voice is honey-smooth and whiskey-rough, weepy  
but manly, armor-piercing and heat-seeking, and, though he can make 
it swoop, soar and turn somersaults, he always uses it for the sake 
of the song. ``Trail,'' a two-CD collection culled from outtakes, 
concerts, radio appearances and living room jams showcases that 
great voice in a variety of settings, from supercharged roadhouse 
rockers to sweet acoustic ballads. It also answers the calls for an 
album of Bob Dylan covers by including a dozen of them among its 
two-plus hours of music. 
</P>
<P>
	From the kicking version of ``Positively 4th Street'' that opens  
the album through the intimate and beautiful ``One Too Many 
Mornings'' near the end, LaFave shows that he is the preeminent 
Dylan interpreter because he makes the songs his own. He does the 
same with songs by other great writers on ``Trail,'' including Joe 
Ely, Woody Guthrie and Bruce Springsteen, as well as offering up 
interesting versions of some mighty fine Jimmy LaFave tunes. 
</P>
<P>
	All in all, ``Trail'' is the most satisfying work yet from a  
rock 'n' roll road warrior with the best voice in the business. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``What I Deserve'' (Rykodisc) -- Kelly Willis  

</P>
<P>
	Kelly Willis' first full-length album in seven years is a  
dazzler. Willis just went on making terrific, twangy, rootsy music 
while she was in record company limbo. And what music she makes on 
``What I Deserve,'' which is clearly her best album. Willis has a 
classic country voice, packing more heartache into one phrase than 
a whole jar full of those big-haired Nashville country singers. 
</P>
<P>
	Willis' quaver sounds best on two songs written by her husband,  
Bruce Robison -- ``Wrapped'' (the title track on his own fine album) 
and the most addictive song on the album, ``Not Forgotten You,'' 
which ought to be a crossover hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I Deserve'' sounds like the sort of album that's country  
enough to appeal to country fans (at least those whose idea of 
country is broad enough to take in some Texas twang) and edgy 
enough to grab alt-country diehards, too. What this album deserves 
is a lot of time in your CD player. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Through a Glass Darkly'' (Philo) -- David Olney  

</P>
<P>
	Many of the songs on David Olney's deep, dark and delicious new  
album play out like miniature black-and-white movies about rural 
life between the World Wars. Olney is a writer of tremendous power 
and clarity, and his tales of hard times and hard choices gain 
further authenticity from their spare, mostly acoustic settings. 
Fans of Townes Van Zandt (whose ``Snowin' on Raton'' Olney covers 
beautifully) or Bill Morrissey ought to enjoy this one for its 
unflinching character studies and country-folk music. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``The Secret Handshake'' (HighTone) -- Geoff Muldaur  

</P>
<P>
	``The Secret Handshake'' is an almost perfect distillation of  
country-blues and folk with a dollop of New Orleans second-line and 
fife-and-drum music thrown in. Geoff Muldaur tops that potent mix 
with a sweet voice that has aged into a beautifully expressive 
instrument. The most heavenly offering on this album, subtitled 
``American Blues and Gospel'' is ``I Don't Feel at Home in This 
World Anymore,'' but, start to finish, this a great roots album. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Half Mad Moon'' (Sire/Watermelon) -- The Damnations TX  

</P>
<P>
	``Half Mad Moon'' is a seemingly casual blend of garage rock,  
acoustic strumming, Americana and the occasional great pop song. 
Sisters Amy Boone and Deborah Kelly lead the band and share both 
songwriting and singing. Occasionally, the casual feel gets to be 
too much -- the title track, for example, drags -- but at their best, 
The Damnations TX sound like an inspired band having a blast in 
someone's basement, and making some mighty fine rock 'n' roll. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Tryin' to Make a Little Love'' (Bullseye) -- Michelle Willson  

</P>
<P>
	Oh my, yes. So many of today's blues singers have all the  
passion of a bored Chicago band in the sanitized North Side tourist 
clubs sleepwalking through ``Sweet Home Chicago'' for the 769th set 
in a row. But Michelle Willson swings with fire, passion and, best 
of all, soul. Most listeners should find it pretty much impossible 
to be still while ``Tryin' to Make a Little Love'' is playing. 
Those uninspired by this meeting of New Orleans funk (LOVE that 
rhythm section) with northern blues ought to consult a physician. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By Eric Fidler, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Simply Baroque'' (Sony Classical) -- Yo Yo Ma, Ton Koopman and  
the Amsterdam Baroque Orchestra 

</P>
<P>
	Always known as a musician willing to experiment -- he's done  
collaborations with jazz/improvisational vocalist Bobby McFerrin 
and with Appalachian bluegrass players -- cellist Yo Yo Ma has gone 
back to the roots of his instrument to find a new sound. On 
``Simply Baroque,'' Ma uses a Baroque-style cello, which has no 
stand and must be supported by the player's legs, to create a more 
delicate, more moving sound than his previous work. The album is a 
collection of compositions by Bach and Luigi Boccherini, an 
18th-century Italian cellist who wrote concertos to show off his 
own talent. And using a scaled down Baroque-style orchestra, which 
features only strings and a harpsichord and no horns, allows the 
lighter tone to shine through, although Ma sometimes defers too 
much to his fellow musicians. Still, this step back is a definite 
step forward for a giant of classical music. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Pilcher, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``My Secret Life'' (Capricorn) -- Sonia Dada  

</P>
<P>
	The name of this Chicago eight-piece band basically means  
irreverent music, but ``My Secret Life'' is far from that. A jumble 
of styles, including blues, salsa, gospel and freeform rock -- think 
recent Paul Simon crossed with the Grateful Dead with a splash of 
the Neville Brothers -- Sonia Dada's third release works on several 
levels. Sadly, one of the most important is lacking, as the band 
doesn't have a true lead vocalist to go with the fine playing. 
Still, the precise musicianship -- all the songs are recorded live 
in the studio -- and the level of expert experimentation evident on 
``My Secret Life'' ensure that Sonia Dada won't be secret for long. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Pilcher, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
