<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 02:24:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lewinsky Gets Her Say in Interview </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Monica Lewinsky says she regrets her role in  
causing pain and suffering not only for her own friends and family, 
but for President Clinton's family. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've apologized in private to my family and to my friends ...  
I would like to publicly acknowledge that I recognize the pain and 
the suffering that they've gone through because of this,'' Ms. 
Lewinsky says in an interview with ABC News to be aired tonight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't dream of asking Chelsea and Mrs. Clinton to forgive  
me,'' she says. ``But I would ask them to know that I am very sorry 
for what happened and for what they've been through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady's spokeswoman, Marsha Berry, had no comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Barbara Walters of ABC won the first interview with Ms. Lewinsky  
since the former White House intern's affair with Clinton burst 
into the headlines on Jan. 21, 1998. Ms. Lewinsky, who received 
immunity from prosecution for cooperating with investigators, was 
prohibited from speaking publicly until Independent Counsel Kenneth 
Starr's office gave the go-ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	The interview was timed to help promote her book -- ``Monica's  
Story,'' written with Princess Diana biographer Andrew Morton -- 
which goes on sale Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times reported in today's editions that Ms.  
Lewinsky is so critical of Starr in the book that several of her 
friends and associates fear Starr will try to revoke her immunity 
agreement and prosecute her. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times says she told Morton she was so despondent at her  
treatment by prosecutors who initially confronted her at a hotel in 
suburban Virginia that she briefly considered jumping out of a 10th 
floor window in their presence. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times report said prosecutors had confronted her with a copy  
of her false affidavit in which she swore that she had not had an 
affair with Clinton, even though it had not been filed yet with a 
federal court in Little Rock, Ark. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times said Starr has said his office was sent the affidavit  
anonymously by James A. Moody, a lawyer for Linda Tripp, who had 
obtained it from lawyers for Paula Corbin Jones, who had a sexual 
harassment suit pending against the president at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office learned of the Clinton-Lewinsky affair from Mrs.  
Tripp. The extent, timing and nature of any contacts between 
Starr's office and the Jones lawyers are under review by the 
Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Barry Toiv refused to comment on the  
Lewinsky interview and book. But asked on Tuesday whether Ms. 
Lewinsky's words would finally bring an end to the story, Toiv 
said, ``I think I can safely say 'No' to that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	ABC released brief excerpts from the interview on Tuesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``Is Bill Clinton a sensuous, passionate man?'' Walters asked  
the 25-year-old woman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gosh, I'll probably get in trouble for saying this,'' Ms.  
Lewinsky began, before describing the president as ``a very sensual 
man'' who feels conflicted because of his ``strong religious 
upbringing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he struggles with his sensuality because I don't think  
he thinks it's OK,'' she said. ``I think he tries to hold himself 
back. And then can't any more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky had stinging words for her former friend, Mrs.  
Tripp, who secretly tape-recorded their telephone conversations 
about the president and turned them over to Starr's investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	``I pity her,'' Ms. Lewinsky said. ``I would hate to be her.''  
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky said she was drawn to Mrs. Tripp at the Pentagon  
because both of them had worked at the White House, where Ms. 
Lewinsky longed to return. She said she confided the affair to Mrs. 
Tripp after her co-worker kept saying such things as ``You're just 
the type of girl the president would like'' and ``I bet you could 
have an affair with him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Daily News in New York reported in today's editions that Ms.  
Lewinsky was questioned Walters about a brief affair she had with a 
42-year-old Pentagon official after she was assigned there in the 
spring of 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd tease him (Clinton) about it and tell him he had  
competition,'' the paper quoted her as saying on an audio tape of 
part of the Walters interview. 
</P>
<P>
	The Daily News obtained the tape Monday and reported in  
Tuesday's editions on other details contained on it. It was not 
clear how much, if any, of the matters covered on the audio tape 
will be broadcast by ABC, which is trying to determine who leaked 
the audio tape to the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky's relationship with the Pentagon official, who was  
unmarried at the time, has been reported previously. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 14:35:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blues Hope Carey Can Regain Form </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Three years removed from the Vezina Trophy,  
24-year-old Jim Carey is anxious to show the St. Louis Blues that 
he can be a star goaltender again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to get back in there and prove to myself that I'm back,  
that I can play at this level, that I've accomplished things at 
this level,'' Carey said Wednesday. ``The opportunity is going to 
come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carey signed a two-year deal with the Blues on Monday, the same  
day he agreed to a contract buyout with the Boston Bruins. He joins 
a team that has already started four goalies this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a young goaltender who has had some success in the past  
and drifted off in the wrong direction,'' general manager Larry 
Pleau said. ``We're hoping he can find his way back. We're looking 
for somebody to be the No. 1 goaltender.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues don't think Grant Fuhr, 36, is the answer anymore.  
Fuhr underwent his third knee operation in three years in December, 
and was ineffective before that. 
</P>
<P>
	Backup Jamie McLennan also has struggled. The Blues are the  
stingiest team in the NHL in shots allowed but they're only two 
games above .500 because their goalies also have the worst save 
percentage. 
</P>
<P>
	Rookies Rich Parent and Brent Johnson have had the most success  
lately. Parent won four of five before being sidelined by a freak 
injury in the middle of February -- a ruptured testicle when a 
pre-game warmup shot broke his cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 21, is the No. 1 of the moment, having been in the nets  
during the team's current three-game winning streak. He has a very 
impressive .954 save percentage and will get the call again 
Thursday night against Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	But sooner or later, Carey will get his chance.  
</P>
<P>
	``The opportunity is going to come,'' he said. ``Johnson is hot  
right now and they're going to ride him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides winning the Vezina in 1996, Carey won the Calder Trophy  
as the NHL's top rookie the previous year. He's fallen off the 
hockey map recently with only 10 games in the NHL the past two 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Carey's career has been in decline since the Bruins acquired him  
in a six-player deal on March 1, 1997. He struggled down the 
stretch that season with a 5-13 record and 3.82 goals-against 
average, then after seven games the following season he lost his 
job to Byron Dafoe and was sent to Providence of the AHL. 
</P>
<P>
	He reportedly agreed to a $1.2 million buyout of a contract that  
was to have paid him $2.3 million this year and $2.7 million next 
season, just for a chance to play again. The Blues got him cheap, 
paying him $200,000 for the rest of this season and $600,000 next 
season with incentives that could boost his salary to $1.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``You take one step back to go two steps forward,'' Carey said.  
``It wasn't a money issue, it was more about playing. Most guys 
would do that, I think. There's nothing like playing in the NHL, 
and if you feel you belong there, money is not an issue.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 10:07:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Turn Lower; Dow Down 52.16 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock indexes turned lower in late morning, as  
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan reiterated reservations 
about President Clinton's proposal to invest a significant portion 
of the Social Security funds in equities. 
</P>
<P>
	At 11 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 52.16 at 9,245.45. The blue-chip index had risen as high as 
9,337.00, up nearly 40 points, before retreating. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators turned lower as well. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was down 3.06 at 1,222.44, and the 
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index down 5.33 at 2,253.70. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues overtook advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 231.87 million 
shares, up from Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	Addressing a Congressional subcommittee this morning, Greenspan  
warned that large-scale investments in equities by the Social 
Security Trust Fund could render the stock market less efficient. 
It could also harm the economy, he said, by potentially channeling 
investment dollars into poorer performing companies. 
</P>
<P>
	As the fourth-quarter earnings reporting season winds down, the  
market is stalled and looking for new direction, said Michael Farr, 
a partner in the investment firm of Farr, Miller &AMP; Washington, in 
Washington D.C. ``You're looking to what might be a stimulus for 
the markets, and it's certainly not coming from Mr. Greenspan this 
morning,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow industrials were led lower by Union Carbide, which was  
down 2 1/8 at 42 11/16 after rising 9 percent Tuesday on takeover 
speculation. Consumer stocks were also lower, with Eastman Kodak 
down 1 3/4 at 63 5/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks were mixed after another warning about  
declining computer sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest one, from 3Com Corp., which sells data, voice and  
video systems for the Internet and intranets. The company said late 
Tuesday that third-quarter earnings from ongoing operations will be 
about 23 cents a share, far below analysts' previously expected 36 
cents. 
</P>
<P>
	The company blamed an ``unexpected slowdown'' in sales to  
businesses in the United States and Latin America. 3Com stock was 
down 2 3/4 at 24 1/4 in leading volume in Nasdaq trading, after dropping 
Tuesday in after-hours trading. 
</P>
<P>
	But the rest of the technology sector was mixed. Intel was up 3/8  
at 110 3/16 in Nasdaq trading, and Dow component Hewlett-Packard, 
which gained Tuesday on a restructuring announcement, was down 5/16 
at 68 5/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices were lower after the National Association of  
Purchasing Management said its index of non-manufacturing activity 
rose to 57.0 percent in February, from January's 54 percent. But, 
the group's index of non-manufacturing prices eased, to 46.5 
percent from 47 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The bullish economic data erased a slight gain in bonds. The  
30-year Treasury was down 23/32 point at 5.66 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The higher interest rates will exacerbate a slower economy, so  
that things are feeling kind of toppy in the stock market here,'' 
Farr said. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average soared 1.79 percent,  
after falling 2.11 percent on Tuesday, as investors were cheered by 
a decline in interest rates and a falling yen. In afternoon trading 
in Europe, Germany's DAX index was down 1.09 percent, Britain's 
FT-SE 100 was up 0.39 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 0.28 
percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
