<HEADLINE> Man, 96, Sentenced in Hit-and-Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- A 96-year-old man who struck and  
killed a 15-year-old girl with his car and then fled the scene was 
sentenced to five years' probation Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Cox was also ordered to pay restitution into a fund to  
promote state legislation that would make it more difficult for 
elderly drivers to renew their licenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox had pleaded no contest to felony hit-and-run charges in  
December and has since surrendered his license. He struck Brandi 
Mitock on Nov. 5 and then apparently became disoriented. He fled 
the scene and turned himself in to police later that day. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Bernard Kamins said he was shocked by medical reports that  
showed Cox had been having strokes since 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``The driver laws need to be revamped,'' Kamins said.  
</P>
<P>
	Brandi's death has sparked a legislative push for tougher  
testing of elderly drivers. Cox's restitution will go into a fund 
to promote a bill that would take legally blind motorists off the 
road and require drivers over 75 years of age to undergo vision and 
road tests to get their licenses renewed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
