<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Capitol Suspect Refuses To Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The man accused of killing two U.S. Capitol  
Police officers refused to talk to psychiatrists on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``On the advice of my attorneys I have no comment,'' Russell  
Eugene Weston Jr. said in response to repeated questions from U.S. 
District Judge Emmet Sullivan, who plans to proceed with a 
competency hearing April 19. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will consider his cooperation or lack thereof,'' said  
Sullivan, who stepped down from the bench Wednesday to explain to 
Weston that the competency proceedings had nothing to do with his 
guilt or innocence. 
</P>
<P>
	Weston, 42, is accused of gunning down officers John Gibson and  
Jacob J. Chestnut in a corridor of the Capitol on July 24. He was 
returned to the District of Columbia Tuesday after spending 30 days 
at the U.S. Medical Facility for Federal Prisoners in Springfield, 
Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	``The defendant has steadfastly refused to talk with and be  
examined by either the court-appointed experts or the government's 
expert,'' federal prosecutors wrote in a motion filed with the 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. James Wolfson, a government psychiatrist, told the court  
that ``Mr. Weston's unwillingness to cooperate does not mean that a 
psychiatric examination has not been going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wolfson noted that observances of Weston's body language, eye  
movements and expressions would also play a role in his assessment. 
</P>
<P>
	Weston was examined by a court-appointed government psychiatrist  
last October. Dr. Sally Johnson, associate warden at the Federal 
Corrections Institute at Butner, N.C., determined that he was 
incompetent to stand trial and recommended indefinite 
hospitalization. 
</P>
<P>
	In ordering a second evaluation, Sullivan cited the possibility  
that Weston could face the death penalty if convicted. A 
government-appointed psychiatrist who has attempted to examine 
Weston since Jan. 28 was refused again on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Debra DePrato, director of the Law and Psychiatry Center at  
Louisiana State University, has sought three more weeks to examine 
Weston, who is now at the District of Columbia Corrections 
Treatment Facility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
