<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar rose against the yen early Thursday on  
declining interest rates in Japan. Tokyo share prices edged higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.94 yen in early trading, up 0.76 yen from  
late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above its level of 121.77 yen in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average was up 6.47 points, or 0.05 percent,  
moving to 14,176.83 in early trading. On Wednesday, the average 
closed up 249.30 points, or 1.79 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar continued to gain ground  
against the yen after Japan's central bank had pumped liquidity 
into the Japanese banking system. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Bank of Japan flooded the interbank loan  
market with cash by purchasing short-term government bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	The action drove the call rate, used by major banks making  
overnight loans to each other, down to a minuscule 0.02 percent 
from 0.07 percent the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan is now struggling to bail out of its worst recession in  
decades. Lowering interest rates make cheap cash available and spur 
more spending, while helping cash-stripped companies. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 132.96 yen, up from  
132.25 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, the lower interest rates and stronger  
dollar helped keep share prices in a narrow range. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 2.55 points, or 0.23 percent, to 1,102.36 
points. The TOPIX closed up 7.73 points, or 0.71 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the yield on the 10-year Japanese government bonds  
rose to 1.675 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.670 percent, 
driving its price down to 101.00 yen from 101.04 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
