<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Soar / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks soared today as investors were cheered  
by a decline in interest rates and a falling yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 249.30 points,  
or 1.79 percent, to close at 14,170.36. On Tuesday, the average 
closed down 300.69 points, or 2.11 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar jumped to 121.18 yen in late afternoon trading, up  
1.10 yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and higher than its late New 
York level of 120.23 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks rose after the central bank drove Japan's already super  
low short term interest rates to nearly zero by flooding the 
interbank loan market with cash. 
</P>
<P>
	The call rate, which big banks use when they make overnight  
loans to each other, fell to as low as 0.02 percent, from 0.07 
percent the day before. Other interest rates, including those for 
long term bonds, fell in line. 
</P>
<P>
	The lower rates were welcomed by the stock market, where  
investors had worried that a recent rise in interest rates would 
erode corporate profits by raising borrowing costs. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the weakening yen boosted exporter stocks  
because Japanese products are more competitive abroad when the yen 
falls. 
</P>
<P>
	By the close of trading the Nikkei had nearly recovered from its  
big decline Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday's drop was overdone,'' said Kazuhiro Nomura, head of  
trading at Paribas Capital Markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 7.73 points, or 0.71 percent, to 1,099.81 
points. The TOPIX closed down 15.73 points, or 1.42 percent, the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading on the main section fell to 395.30 million shares, from  
457.38 million shares Tuesday. Rising shares outnumbered declines 
691 to 411, while 195 issues finished the day unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the falling Japanese interest rates pulled  
the yen lower against the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining interest rates could lower the return to investors on  
everything from bank deposits to government bonds. A country's 
currency often falls when interest rates do on the theory that some 
investors will pull their money out of the county to seek higher 
returns elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	After trading as low as 119.88 yen in the morning, the dollar  
surged to as high as 121.30 yen in the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at 132.25 yen, up from 131.08 yen late  
Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 203 10-year Japanese  
government bond fell to 1.690 percent from Tuesday's finish of 
1.805 percent, driving its price up to 100.88 yen from 99.96 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
