<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 09:26:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court OKs Witholding Worker Comp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- State workers' compensation system insurers  
cannot be sued for withholding health-care benefits for 
work-related injuries while they decide whether the treatment is 
reasonable and necessary, the Supreme Court said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The unanimous ruling, in a Pennsylvania case, said both public  
and private insurers can withhold payment while that deciding. 
</P>
<P>
	``The law expressly limits an employee's entitlement to  
'reasonable' and 'necessary' medical treatment,'' Chief Justice 
William H. Rehnquist wrote for the court. Injured workers ``do not 
have a property interest ... in having their providers paid for 
treatment that has yet to be found reasonable and necessary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The court added that private companies that serve as workers'  
compensation insurers cannot be sued because they did not act in 
the role of the state. Only government action, not a private 
citizen's acts, can violate someone's constitutional rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices reversed a lower court decision that let a group of  
injured workers sue insurers for withholding their benefits pending 
a review of their treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Like other states, Pennsylvania requires employers to pay for  
medical care for workers who suffer job-related injuries and 
diseases, and to partially replace lost wages. The state law 
requires payment for ``reasonable and necessary'' medical services. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, the state legislature responded to the rising cost of  
workplace injuries by allowing insurers to withhold payments for 
disputed medical treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of injured workers sued state officials and private  
insurers, saying the withholding of benefits violated their 
due-process rights. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge threw out the claims against the private  
insurers on grounds they were not state agencies, and said the 
state officials' actions did not violate the workers' due-process 
rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated the lawsuits,  
saying the private insurers were acting for the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the 3rd Circuit court's decision last year, Pennsylvania  
has changed its procedures. No benefits are withheld until an 
employee receives notice that a review has been requested and has a 
chance to submit written testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court reversed the appeals court's ruling. Rehnquist  
wrote that injured workers have a right only to reasonable and 
necessary medical treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	``What (the workers) ask in this case is that insurers be  
required to pay for patently unreasonable, unnecessary and even 
fraudulent medical care without any right, under state law, to seek 
reimbursement from providers,'' he added. Further, he said, a 
decision by private insurers to withhold payment pending review 
cannot be considered a state action. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is American manufacturers Mutual Insurance Co. vs.  
Sullivan, 97-2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 11:46:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan: Caution on Budget Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- If budget surpluses now are going to help pay  
for Social Security in the future, the key issue confronting 
Congress is how to make sure the extra money is somehow saved, 
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said today. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whichever direction the Congress chooses to go, whether toward  
privatization or fuller funding of Social Security, augmenting our 
national savings has to be the main objective,'' Greenspan told a 
House Commerce subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	Surpluses could be saved through a plan like President Clinton's  
that would pay down the national debt, making it more likely the 
government will continue to run large surpluses that could be used 
for Social Security in the future, Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Or, the surpluses could be used to help start private investment  
accounts that many Republicans would like to see replace some 
future benefits. In that case, individual Americans would do the 
saving themselves, Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	While the central bank chairman said he likes Clinton's plan, he  
also said he fears that politicians inevitably would be tempted to 
spend future budget surpluses on other things -- such as tax cuts or 
other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the capacity to have a fully funded private system is  
far higher ... than in a public system where you have the 
possibilities of having to deal with very large surpluses, which 
can be employed for other means,'' Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed chairman, however, said moving Social Security money  
into stock market investments -- whether done by individuals or in 
bulk by the federal government -- cannot in and of itself improve 
the nation's overall preparedness for the coming retirement of the 
huge baby boom generation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any increase in returns realized by Social Security must be  
offset by a reduction in returns earned on private portfolios, 
which represent, to a large extent, funds also held for 
retirement,'' Greenspan said. ``It's a shuffling of claims and 
doesn't increase the real resources.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and Republican leaders in Congress have agreed to use  
about 60 percent of the budget surpluses expected over the next 15 
years to bolster Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	Right now, the Social Security payroll taxes collected from  
workers each year is more than enough to cover the needed 
retirement benefits paid out each year. 
</P>
<P>
	But in 2013, after baby boomers begin to retire, the program  
will not collect enough taxes from workers to cover the baby 
boomers' benefits. Lawmakers now are trying to decide how best to 
prepare for that shortfall. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has proposed paying down the national debt to help grow  
the economy and therefore increase future tax revenues. He also 
wants the government to invest some money in the stock market to 
try to increase its value. 
</P>
<P>
	However, many Republicans -- and some Democrats -- would prefer to  
use the surpluses to develop a new system of personal accounts, 
which workers could invest in the stock market themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Younger workers would be allowed to divert into such accounts  
some of the payroll taxes they would otherwise pay. The surpluses 
would be used to help maintain current Social Security benefits for 
those already retired or near retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	The hope is that, for the younger workers, stock market accounts  
would grow big enough to replace some Social Security benefits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
