<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Takes Anthrax Hoaxes Seriously </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With phony anthrax threats popping up daily  
around the nation, the FBI is investigating every one in the hope 
that federal prosecution of the culprits will halt the disruptive 
hoaxes. 
</P>
<P>
	The fake threats ``have gotten publicity and scare the normal  
citizen. They create a fear factor,'' Neil J. Gallagher, FBI 
Assistant Director in charge of the national security division, 
said Tuesday. ``They disrupt American life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, all the anthrax threats have been hoaxes, but the bureau  
must respond seriously to every one. 
</P>
<P>
	``My personal fear is that someday there will be a real anthrax  
threat, and American society will react by saying, `There's another 
hoax','' Gallagher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sporadic threats of contamination with the potentially lethal  
anthrax bacterium date back several years. But beginning last fall 
and accelerating in the past few weeks, the FBI has seen a spate of 
letters, containing a sticky substance or a dark powder and the 
ominous warning: You've been contaminated by anthrax. 
</P>
<P>
	The letters have arrived in almost every region -- often at 10 or  
15 similar targets in a city. The targets have varied widely: 
Abortion clinics, Catholic schools, nightclubs, department stores, 
hospitals, post offices, courthouses, news media offices, FBI 
offices and even the Old Executive Office Building beside the White 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not a day goes by without us hearing from somewhere in the  
United States about an anthrax threat,'' Gallagher said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anthrax threats have become what bomb threats once were or  
product tampering threats in the 1980s'' after the Tylenol 
poisoning in Illinois, said FBI spokesman Bill Carter. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only way to slow this down is for us to prosecute  
someone,'' said Gallagher's deputy Dale L. Watson. ``So we are 
diligently investigating'' the hoaxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the hoaxes are federal felonies.  
</P>
<P>
	Mailing a threat to injure someone is punishable by up to six  
years in prison. Threatening to use a weapon of mass destruction, 
including a biological agent like anthrax, can bring life in 
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles accountant Harvey Craig Spelkin, 53, was charged at  
the end of the year with such a biological threat. Federal 
prosecutors accuse him of trying to avoid a Dec. 18 appearance in 
U.S. Bankruptcy Court by telephoning the courthouse with a warning 
that anthrax might be in the air conditioning system. 
</P>
<P>
	Another man, charged in January with telephoning anthrax threats  
to a Los Angeles area hospital, is undergoing psychiatric tests. 
</P>
<P>
	They are among very few people charged so far, none of them with  
the letter-threat hoaxes. The FBI has investigated 42 incidents 
since the beginning of this year; the Justice Department could not 
say exactly how many have been charged. 
</P>
<P>
	Letter threats are difficult to investigate, Gallagher said.  
</P>
<P>
	``They don't walk into a post office where they can be spotted.  
They use a remote mailbox. You can't trace a letter to a particular 
mailbox, only to a time of day and a part of town,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not being done by one person or one group,'' Gallagher  
added. 
</P>
<P>
	Some senders obviously want to publicize a cause, as in the  
letters to abortion clinics. Others are just copy cats. Sometimes 
the motive isn't apparent. Sometimes, agents believe, the sender 
wants to get a look at the response of law enforcement and rescue 
workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``That large response ... encourages others who want the same  
response,'' Gallagher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lexington, Ky., is one of several cities where a batch of  
letters have been postmarked. Nearly 30 letters and cards 
postmarked from Lexington have been sent to women's clinics 
nationwide in the last few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI Laboratory's Hazardous Materials Response Unit responds  
when local authorities don't have proper equipment. They can do 
tests at the scene for anthrax, said Tom Kubic, deputy assistant 
director of the lab. Further testing in the lab can show the purity 
of any anthrax that might be found. 
</P>
<P>
	``The availability of anthrax harmful to individuals is fairly  
small,'' Kubic said. ``The steps to purify anthrax to a hazardous 
or deadly level are not generally available to the public.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Exposure isn't always fatal. Bleach destroys anthrax, Kubic  
said, so people at some threat sites have been rinsed with a bleach 
solution as a precaution. 
</P>
<P>
	After one to six days, anthrax produces flu-like symptoms in  
people who inhale its spores. Once fully established, it can kill 
within 24 hours if not treated with antibiotics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
