<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Seeks Help From Tobacco Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The World Health Organization asked  
tobacco farmers Wednesday to support its efforts to reduce the 
cultivation and consumption of the crop. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency blamed 4 million deaths worldwide each year on  
diseases allegedly caused by tobacco and said that number could 
rise to 10 million within two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``WHO is not against tobacco farmers, but ... WHO is committed  
to addressing the tobacco epidemic,'' said Dr. Derek Yach, head of 
the organization's tobacco free initiative. 
</P>
<P>
	Yach and other representatives of the U.N. agency met with the  
International Tobacco Growers Association to gain support for a 
public health treaty, called the Framework Convention on Tobacco 
Control. 
</P>
<P>
	WHO has invited tobacco growers, international agricultural  
agencies and the World Bank to develop long-term strategies to 
substitute other crops for tobacco. 
</P>
<P>
	The organizations are also trying to reduce the number of the  
world's smokers from 1.2 billion to 800 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
