<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Mrs. Clinton Teases with Comment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton left her supporters more  
excited than ever about her potential Senate candidacy with a 
comment that was tantalizingly vague. 
</P>
<P>
	``You cannot drop out of the political process and leave it to  
others,'' she told 900 people at a Democratic National Women's 
Leadership Forum luncheon at the Plaza Hotel today. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not clear whether she was referring to herself or merely  
encouraging women to get involved in electing candidates who will 
represent their interests. But many in the audience interpreted the 
statement as a sign of her own interest in running. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sounded like she might be leaning toward running. It  
sounded very positive to me,'' said Manhattan Borough President 
Virginia Fields. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton also teased her audience by asking why attendance  
at the luncheon was so high -- 400 people were added to the guest 
list after the original 500 tickets sold out, and many of the 
latecomers were seated in an adjacent room where they actually 
could not see Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was talk I might have an announcement to make,'' Mrs.  
Clinton said. She then paused and added: ``I do not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some in the audience groaned.  
</P>
<P>
	Her comment about not dropping out of the political process was  
made while stressing the positive effect politics can have on 
people's lives. When the speech ended, her supporters began 
chanting ``Go, go, go! Run, Hillary, run!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, she was greeted at a Queens middle school with raucous  
applause from students, education officials and local politicians. 
She spoke about the importance of arts education and unveiled a new 
report that cites the school, I.S. 25 in Flushing, for its 
attention to the arts. 
</P>
<P>
	Students in the chorus, fidgeting nervously in a hallway before  
performing for the first lady, said they hoped she would run. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's cool, she's not snotty, she's like a real, regular  
person,'' said 14-year-old Tiffany Mance. 
</P>
<P>
	This is her first trip to New York since announcing she was  
considering a run for office. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who would be Mrs. Clinton's most likely  
rival should she run, did not attend the event -- he was in 
Washington. But earlier this week, his staff noted that the arts 
program Mrs. Clinton was championing did not receive any federal 
funding. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some students don't learn well just sitting and listening,''  
Mrs. Clinton said in the school auditorium. ``They need to move, 
they need to use their hands, and then ... the arts are a part of 
who we are,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She added: ``As a tone-deaf person in elementary school, I was  
told I could sit with my friends in the soprano section if I 
lip-synched.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She also met with nine students in one of the classrooms. Some  
were sketching with pastels; others performed a short interpretive 
dance for her. 
</P>
<P>
	Polls taken a few weeks ago gave her a commanding lead in a  
hypothetical match-up with Giuliani for the Senate seat being 
vacated by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	But another statewide poll released today showed a narrowing of  
the potential race. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone poll of 702 registered voters conducted Sunday and  
Monday by Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion found Mrs. 
Clinton favored by 50 percent of voters with Giuliani the choice of 
46 percent. The gap was the same as the poll's margin of error of 
plus or minus 4 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Tonight she is to dine at the home of Roger Altman, a Wall  
Street financier. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, she is to talk at the United Nations about the  
forthcoming International Women's Day before returning to a 
classroom to view an HBO documentary on women and sports at a 
school in the Chelsea district of Manhattan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
