<DOCNO> APW19990303.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 18:12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mass. Treasury Scandal Widens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Two state employees were arrested Wednesday on  
charges of stealing $2.4 million, the latest development in a 
scandal that has rocked the state treasury. 
</P>
<P>
	The two were charged with stealing from the state treasury's  
Unclaimed Check Fund, an account containing money from uncashed 
state checks. Officials believe several million dollars may have 
been siphoned off over the years. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is almost beyond belief,'' Attorney General Thomas Reilly  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Foley, 39, who left his job as deputy treasurer in charge  
of cash management last week, was charged with larceny and bribery. 
Thomas Ciliberto, 51, of Woonsocket, R.I., faces the same charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Reilly said the thefts involved an heir-finder scam and that  
Ciliberto had an heir-finder business, reuniting unclaimed money 
and property with owners for a fee. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no answer at Ciliberto's home Wednesday and Foley's  
number was unlisted. Their lawyers' names were not available. 
</P>
<P>
	Foley is accused of stealing $1.6 million between 1992 and 1993  
and $812,000 in 1994 and 1995. Ciliberto is charged in the latter 
theft, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate case, a longtime treasury employee who was Foley's  
subordinate in charge of the Unclaimed Check Fund was arrested in 
mid-February and charged with helping a friend fraudulently claim 
$6.5 million from the fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 05:47:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Changes Could Disrupt 2000 Census </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Any changes in plans for next year's census  
would be disruptive and waste valuable time, Census Bureau Director 
Kenneth Prewitt says. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are at a point in this census which, if we don't get about  
it, we're not going to get it done,'' he told the House Government 
Reform census subcommittee Tuesday. ``We would reduce accuracy at 
this point if we start trying to introduce new procedures.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., the subcommittee chairman, has outlined  
a series of proposals that he says would produce a more accurate 
head count than the 1990 census. 
</P>
<P>
	They include printing the forms in 33 languages, spending more  
to advertise and promote the census, enlisting Americorp volunteers 
and reviving a program that lets local officials review the 
numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	But while Prewitt said most of Miller's proposals would be  
acceptable, he predicted that legislative changes at this late 
stage would cause problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``These proposals would disrupt Census 2000 and even put it at  
risk'' by reducing its accuracy, he said. Major contracts would 
have to be renegotiated, making it ``extremely difficult'' to meet 
the deadline, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	The census begins in less than 13 months -- on April 1, 2000.  
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Prewitt announced that the bureau would use  
traditional census methods to make the population estimates needed 
to redistribute the 435 House seats among the states. The Supreme 
Court last month said the Clinton administration's plan to use a 
scientific method known as statistical sampling for that process 
was unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	But Prewitt said the bureau would use sampling to determine how  
many people were missed and develop more accurate numbers for 
states to redraw congressional and state legislative boundaries. 
The high court did not prohibit sampling for this purpose or for 
the distribution of billions of dollars in federal financial aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, a harsh critic of sampling, said ``this two-number  
census is a recipe for disaster'' and predicted it would prompt 
lawsuits from ``every state and local government in America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 1990 census, which was the first to be less accurate than  
the one before, missed 8.4 million people and counted 4.4 million 
people twice. 
</P>
<P>
	The sampling plan was designed to avoid another miscount, but  
met strong resistance from congressional Republicans which, coupled 
with lengthy debates over the procedure, ended up delaying the 
Census Bureau's preparations. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats have accused Republicans of opposing sampling for fear  
of losing control of the House. Republicans, insisting on the 
constitutionally required head count, argue that Democrats could 
manipulate a number produced by sampling. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., cited findings of a General  
Accounting Office analysis of the 1990 census to illustrate the 
effects of an inaccurate count. 
</P>
<P>
	The study, by the investigative arm of Congress, found that 27  
states and the District of Columbia lost a combined $4.5 billion in 
federal funds during the decade because of failure to make 
recommended adjustments, Waxman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 15:16:36 </DATE_TIME>
