	``We cannot drop out of the political process,'' she said,  
recalling the suffragists' conference 150 years ago at Seneca 
Falls, N.Y. Her challenge, she added, was to decide ``whether all 
the sacrifices that were made in the past should just be honored by 
rhetoric or honored by action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Action, decided the girl-power cluster outside Intermediate  
School 25. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need, like, a new person in the Senate, especially a woman.  
There's too many guys,'' said Jin Kim, 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Fellow ninth-grader Alexis Rubenstein also approved of Mrs.  
Clinton as a candidate: ``She'll make her mark as first woman 
president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But it's the Senate that Mrs. Clinton is eyeing, another girl  
reminded. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, I mean, this will be the first step,'' Rubenstein said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
