<HEADLINE> Ramon Says He's Headed to Boston </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) -- Ramon Martinez said Wednesday he has  
agreed to a two-year contract to join his brother, Pedro, with the 
Boston Red Sox. The team, however, said the deal was not complete. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramon, recovering in the Dominican Republic from shoulder  
surgery, became available after compiling a .615 winning percentage 
in 11 seasons with the Los Angeles Dodgers, who bought out his 
option. Pedro was 19-7 last season, his first with Boston after 
winning the Cy Young award with Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We agreed on the deal'' for two years, Ramon said in an  
interview with WEEI radio in Boston. ``I made a decision that I'm 
now going to play for the Red Sox.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not done yet, but it sounds like they made pretty good  
progress,'' said Kevin Shea, Boston's director of communications. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Dan Duquette said Monday that the Red Sox had  
been pursuing Ramon for several months and that he had visited the 
Dominican Republic two weeks ago to watch Ramon throw. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramon, 30, was 7-3 with a 2.83 ERA last season but made only 15  
starts before a season-ending rotator cuff injury that required 
surgery June 30. In 11 seasons in Los Angeles, he had a 3.45 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgers ``made some decision and ... I wasn't too happy  
about the situation and the way they handled it,'' Ramon said. 
</P>
<P>
	He told WEEI that he may be ready to pitch before the All-Star  
game, scheduled for Boston's Fenway Park on July 13. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know that it's going to be pretty soon, the way that I  
feel,'' Ramon told WEEI. ``I had a different choice (of teams) but 
I decided to join my brother.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They were teammates with Los Angeles in 1993, when Pedro pitched  
65 games as a rookie, only two of them starts. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will be probably the first time we're going to be in the  
same rotation,'' said Pedro, 27. ``I feel happy to have my brother 
here, my best friend here. To me it would be feeling even more 
secure than I've been.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Ramon is healthy, it also would give manager Jimy Williams  
more security. He already has a rotation of reliable veterans with 
Pedro Martinez, Bret Saberhagen, Tim Wakefield, Mark Portugal and 
Pat Rapp. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very happy,'' Ramon said, ``because now we're going to be  
together again and we can help the team.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
