<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Would Make Air Crashes Equal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Families of victims of airline crashes over  
the ocean would be able to sue for more than just economic damages 
under a bill the House passed today. 
</P>
<P>
	The House voted 412-2 for a bill that would exempt those  
aviation accidents from the 1920 Death on the High Seas Act, which 
bars families from collecting non-economic damages as a result of 
disasters at sea, such as the 1996 TWA 800 crash, in which 230 
people died. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters said it made no sense to treat aviation accidents  
differently depending on whether they occur over water or land. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa., called current law a ``bizarre  
inequity'' that arose as a result of a Supreme Court decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``The effect of this decision is to treat families differently  
depending on whether their relative died in an aircraft that 
crashes into the ocean or one that crashes into the land,'' Shuster 
said during debate on the House floor. 
</P>
<P>
	``This act prevents a family from collecting damage for their  
relative's pain and suffering or for the loss of the companionship 
of their loved one,'' he said. ``There really is no reason why the 
monetary recovery from a lawsuit should depend upon whether the 
plane happens to comedown, whether its into the water or into the 
land.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If passed by the Senate, the bill would apply to civil actions  
filed after the date of passage and to all pending cases where a 
court has not yet rendered a decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The House passed similar legislation last year, but it died in  
the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 603.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
