<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Solo Yachtsman Arrives As a Winner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PUNTA DEL ESTE, Uruguay (AP) -- An Italian yachtsman sailed into  
port a hero and a winner Wednesday, ready for some rest and a 
celebratory glass of wine or two. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everything is fine, everything is marvelous,'' Giovanni  
Soldini said after capturing the third leg of the Around Alone 
regatta with a rescued French competitor aboard. 
</P>
<P>
	Soldini docked his 60-foot boat FILA after a harrowing crossing  
from Auckland, New Zealand. His yacht bobbed in the harbor with a 
slogan painted on the side: ``No more problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And there have been plenty of problems in this solo sailing  
competition, highlighted by the daring rescue of a French sailor 
that has overshadowed the race itself. 
</P>
<P>
	The global odyssey of more than 31,000 miles began last  
September in Charleston, S.C., and will end there in May, capping a 
grueling nine-month adventure. Earlier legs took sailors from South 
Carolina to South Africa and then to New Zealand. 
</P>
<P>
	Few people were on the dock when Soldini arrived at dawn.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is overwhelming,'' he said upon learning of his victory  
in the next-to-last leg. 
</P>
<P>
	The Italian government is expected to decorate Soldini. He plans  
to fly to Italy next week to join his family before the last leg 
resumes in a month. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Wednesday, he said he simply wanted to celebrate with a  
glass of wine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to lift a glass,'' he said. ``Come to think of it, a  
couple of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Isabelle Autissier, who was plucked from the Southern Ocean off  
Antarctica on Feb. 16, was jubilant upon docking. She called 
Soldini a ``gentleman of the seas'' for going into harm's way to 
save her. 
</P>
<P>
	Soldini braved 30-foot waves, scouring the seas until he  
happened upon her yacht. He had to throw a hammer at the overturned 
hull to awaken Autissier, who had waited inside for more than 24 
hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Soldini won the leg ahead of Frenchman Marc Thiercelin despite  
having to go hundreds of miles out of his way. Thiercelin led 
Soldini by 18 hours upon their departure from New Zealand. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Frenchman hit stormy waters in the South Atlantic last  
Thursday, lost a mast and limped last weekend to the Falkland 
Islands for repairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Thiercelin's sister, Emanuelle, told The Associated Press her  
brother might be able to leave the Falklands as early as Monday 
before heading to Punta del Este. 
</P>
<P>
	The last leg of 5,750 miles begins April 10 when the yachts are  
to sail from this port on South America's Atlantic coast to South 
Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Racing authorities said Soldini's unofficial time for the third  
leg was 25 days, 9 hours, 55 minutes, 53 seconds. But they might 
adjust his time because of the rescue. 
</P>
<P>
	Thiercelin was harshly criticized for his failure to aid  
Autissier despite being about 80 miles closer than Soldini. 
Thiercelin led by hundreds of miles at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Soldini said Wednesday a meteorologist with whom he was in  
contact helped him calculate Autissier's location. 
</P>
<P>
	The 32-year-old Italian arrived at Punta Del Este just before 6  
a.m., hours earlier than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``He picked up some really nice winds just after midnight,''  
race director Mark Schrader said. ``He was doing really well.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
