<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Another New Charge on Phone Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's largest local phone company, Bell  
Atlantic, will charge customers a new 24-cents-a-line monthly fee 
to pay for the costs of letting customers keep their local 
telephone numbers after they switch carriers -- even though many 
don't have that choice now. 
</P>
<P>
	Many other local phone companies have either already announced  
or have started billing customers for the new charge, ranging from 
38 to 53 cents a month for each phone line. The fee pays for local 
phone companies' costs of complying with a provision in a 1996 law. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell Atlantic's customers -- from Maine to Virginia -- will begin  
seeing the fee in their May bills, spokeswoman Susan Butta said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Businesses also will pay a fee, which can vary by the services  
they get. 
</P>
<P>
	GTE, which provides local service in 28 states, meanwhile, has  
said it now will charge customers 38 cents a line rather than 43 
cents as originally planned. The fee will appear in most customers' 
bills after March 10. 
</P>
<P>
	New monthly fees last year began popping up on consumers' phone  
bills. Those charges came from a 1997 government overhaul of phone 
fees and from itemized charges for government-ordered subsidies 
once included in rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Like those fees, the newest charges are broken out in phone  
bills, under different names. They come in addition to the 
multitude of existing charges for federal, state or local taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	The concept of portable phone numbers is not new. For years,  
long-distance customers have been able to change their 
long-distance carriers without getting a new phone number. 
</P>
<P>
	The rationale: Consumers would be less inclined to switch to a  
new carrier -- local or long-distance -- if they had to get a new 
phone number each time. That would thwart the goal of competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1996 law requires local phone companies to make technical  
changes that would allow customers to keep their phone numbers 
after they switch to a new local provider. 
</P>
<P>
	However, most of the local competition that has evolved since  
the 1996 law focuses mostly on lucrative, high-volume business 
customers, not on residential customers. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 00:53:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ventura Gives First Major Address </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL (AP) -- Gov. Jesse Ventura sounded familiar themes in  
his first State of the State address, a staid 45-minute speech in 
which he rarely strayed from his notes and didn't tell any jokes. 
His opening observation was elegantly simple. 
</P>
<P>
	``The state of the state is great,'' the governor said in an  
address that stressed broad principles. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides said before Tuesday's speech that the former pro wrestler  
once known as ``the Body'' wants to be taken seriously. So Ventura, 
who often shoots from the lip, stayed low-key as he delivered a 
message heavy on themes of limited government, an involved 
citizenry and increased responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't legislate against every stupid thing people will do,  
and yet the temptation is there to try time and time again,'' said 
Ventura, who won election last November as a third-party candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	The state is jeopardized by the notion that ``taxpayers must  
step forward to provide nearly unlimited resources to anyone who 
faces adversity, who lives with circumstances they brought about 
through their own decision or who lives with consequences of 
choices to act illegally,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The free ride is over,'' said Ventura.  
</P>
<P>
	He said his administration's legacy ``will be provoking people  
out of their apathy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One ``bread and butter'' example from Ventura's speech turned  
out to be wrong, and the state Health Department has set the record 
straight. 
</P>
<P>
	The disputed reference came as Ventura was urging lawmakers not  
to become overzealous regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time government burdens the people with nonsense like  
rules that dictate how to butter bread in nursing homes -- and 
believe it or not, that is a real government regulation -- we remove 
any incentive for doing good work,'' Ventura said in his speech. 
</P>
<P>
	The state has no rule on how nursing home workers must butter  
bread, said Health Department spokesman John Stieger. 
</P>
<P>
	The lone specific new proposal in Ventura's address was a pledge  
to increase the $10 million in his initial budget to help 
struggling farmers to $60 million over the next three years. 
</P>
<P>
	He alluded to one of the biggest issues of the legislative  
session -- whether surplus revenue should be returned via an income 
tax rebate or a sales tax rebate. ``As soon as you're ready to send 
me a sales tax rebate bill, I'm ready to sign it,'' said Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the bread-buttering miscue, Ventura spokesman John Wodele  
wouldn't say how the example made it into the speech. Stieger said 
it's possible the department had a bread-buttering rule several 
years ago during a period of stricter regulation, but ``if there 
was anything like it, there isn't anything like it now.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
