<HEADLINE> Mass. Treasury Scandal Widens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- In a widening scandal at the Massachusetts  
treasury, two state employees have been arrested on charges of 
stealing $2.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Both are charged with stealing from the state treasury's  
Unclaimed Check Fund, an account containing money from uncashed 
state checks. Officials believe several million dollars may have 
been siphoned off over the years. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is almost beyond belief,'' Attorney General Thomas Reilly  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Foley, 39, who left his job as deputy treasurer in charge  
of cash management last week, was charged Wednesday with larceny 
and bribery. Thomas Ciliberto, 51, of Woonsocket, R.I., faces the 
same charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Reilly said the thefts involved an heir-finder scam and that  
Ciliberto had an heir-finder business, reuniting unclaimed money 
and property with owners for a fee. 
</P>
<P>
	Foley is accused of stealing $1.6 million between 1992 and 1993  
and $812,000 in 1994 and 1995. Ciliberto is charged in the latter 
theft, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no answer at Ciliberto's home Wednesday and Foley's  
number was unlisted. Their lawyers' names were not available. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate case, a longtime treasury employee who was Foley's  
subordinate in charge of the Unclaimed Check Fund was arrested in 
mid-February and charged with helping a friend fraudulently claim 
$6.5 million from the fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
