<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Takes Action Against Concorde </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- European authorities thought they were going  
to clean up the environment by cracking down on U.S. airliners 
equipped with engine mufflers known as hush kits. 
</P>
<P>
	Now they face the prospect of having their beloved but  
ear-shattering supersonic Concorde banned from U.S. skies in 
retaliation. 
</P>
<P>
	The House passed a bill today that would bar the Concorde if the  
European Union proceeds with plans to prohibit hush-kitted American 
aircraft from flying over Europe. The bill was passed by voice 
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	'' None of us relishes taking this type of retaliatory measure,  
but fair is fair,'' Rep. Louise Slaughter, D-N.Y., said. ``This 
sends a simple message to our friends across the pond that we will 
respond in kind when they take this type of action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the House Rules Committee approved the bill Tuesday, members  
didn't try to hide their eye-for-an-eye approach. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a straight sort of rattling of swords back and forth, but  
I think that the timing of this is very important, to let them know 
that just because they've rattled their sword, we're not going away 
on the hush kits,'' said Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla., a member of the 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Urged on by environmentalists, the European Parliament voted  
last month to adopt a new set of aircraft engine rules. 
</P>
<P>
	One would prohibit registration of hush-kitted aircraft in  
Europe after April 1. Another would ban hush-kitted aircraft 
registered elsewhere from flying in European skies as of April 1, 
2002, unless they were operating there before the start of next 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	EU officials concede that hush kits reduce noise pollution, but  
they contend they are ineffective at controlling air pollution 
since they are slapped on old engines. The Europeans prefer planes 
with new engines altogether. Final action on the rules is scheduled 
March 29. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials say the rules are arbitrary, because hush-kitted  
airplanes meet new noise limits, known as Stage 3, established by 
the United Nations' International Civil Aviation Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	A Commerce Department official said last month the rules could  
have a $1 billion effect on the United States by devaluing 
airplanes in the U.S. fleet, which are often resold in Europe, and 
harming hush-kit makers, all U.S. companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Concorde legislation is the brainchild of Rep. James  
Oberstar, D-Minn., top Democrat on the House Transportation 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The needle-nosed plane, famous for rocketing through the sky at  
more than twice the speed of sound, made its first flight March 2, 
1969. It is also known as a fuel hog and a noise polluter. 
</P>
<P>
	Oberstar's bill says that if the EU adopts the hush-kit rules,  
any supersonic jet that does not meet Stage 3 engine noise 
requirements will be banned from U.S. skies. The Concorde doesn't 
even meet the current standard, Stage 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Air France and British Airways are the only scheduled airlines  
flying the Concorde in the United States. Air France operates a 
daily round trip between Paris and New York, while British Airways 
flies two daily round trips between London and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	A flight takes 3 1/2 hours, about half the time of a conventional  
jetliner. 
</P>
<P>
	Dean Breest, an Air France spokesman, said, ``If it's banned,  
it's going to inconvenience a lot of business travelers traveling 
to Europe who need the timesaving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Lampl, a British Airways spokesman, added: ``We feel that  
British Airways and ultimately the Concorde is not an appropriate 
target for sanctions in a purely trade dispute.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
