<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disability Ruling Impacts Community </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa (AP) -- Garret Frey maneuvers through his high  
school hallways by blowing into a straw to steer his oversized 
wheelchair. 
</P>
<P>
	A nurse and teacher's aide are always at his side, looking after  
a daily care regimen that includes urinary catheterization, 
clearing his tracheotomy, monitoring blood pressure and responding 
to alarms on his ventilator. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Supreme Court held Wednesday that the boy's school  
district must pay for his nursing care, a decision he called a 
victory for disabled students far beyond the halls of Cedar Rapids 
Jefferson High School. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone has a chance to have a free education,'' Frey said.  
``It's going to help a lot of other kids. Not just me and other 
kids in Iowa. It's going to help all over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But school administrators, while sympathetic to the  
16-year-old's case, fear their new financial burdens could be 
overwhelming. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are 15,000-plus school districts in the country that are  
watching this case,'' said Lew Finch, superintendent of the Cedar 
Rapids School District. ``Where do you draw the line with how you 
handle medically fragile kids?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Richard Ott, executive director of the North Dakota School  
Boards Association: ``We're already strapped. We can't do the 
things we're wanting and trying to do now. The costs of special 
education are mounting continuously, and if you even indicate that 
you want to examine them, you're accused of being opposed to kids 
with handicaps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The federal Individuals with Disabilities Education Act provides  
that all children with disabilities receive a ``free appropriate 
public education.'' The 1975 law requires public schools to provide 
special education services, but an exception is made for medical 
treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	In Frey's case, the court ruled 7-2 that his continuous care  
during the school day is not medical treatment and must be publicly 
funded under the act. 
</P>
<P>
	The district has estimated the ruling will cost $30,000 to  
$40,000 per year in addition to the $10,000 to $12,000 now spent to 
provide Frey with a teacher associate. 
</P>
<P>
	The National School Boards Association estimates there are  
17,000 students nationwide with severe disabilities. The financial 
arithmetic -- conceivably running into the hundreds of millions -- 
frightens the districts. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who is going to provide that money?'' asked Sue Seitz,  
attorney for the Cedar Rapids district. ``So far the federal 
government certainly hasn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government now pays about 12 percent of the nation's  
special education costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Leslie Seid Margolis of the National Association of Protection  
and Advocacy Services, downplayed the fiscal alarms sounded by the 
schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are kids with health needs who have had access to the  
services publicly without a need to battle for them,'' she said. 
``Secondly, there aren't that many kids in this division so, in 
terms of numbers, it's not like the flood gates are going to open 
up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Frey was paralyzed in a motorcycle accident when he was 4 years  
old. Until now, his family has paid for his care with money from a 
$1.3 million settlement with the motorcycle manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are just overwhelmed,'' said Frey's mother, Charlene Frey.  
``I'm very happy. It's been a long road and it's finally over. 
We've been anticipating this day for a long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Frey described waiting for the ruling as ``nerve-racking,'' but  
ultimately satisfying. It did, however, come down on a day the 
sophomore had to take a test and give a speech at school. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was stunned,'' he said. ``I didn't believe what they had  
said. Was it hard to finish that final exam after the news? Yes.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 21:52:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Housing Figures Yet To Slow Market / Commentary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *AP Business Analyst    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- If housing is a leading indicator of economic  
activity and, by extension, of stock market behavior, what will 
investors make of the recent decline in new housing starts? 
</P>
<P>
	Not much, judging at least by the casual manner in which they've  
dispensed with all other threats, real and imagined. A quality of 
self-fulfillment guides this market -- anything is possible if you 
believe. 
</P>
<P>
	That belief has seldom been higher, and never before in history  
has it involved so many people and so much money. In the mind of 
investors, the world is being recreated, and the new world is 
abounding with riches. 
</P>
<P>
	This isn't the reality, of course, any more than the amount of  
cash in a person's pocket is a true reflection of the world 
economy. But as long as enough pockets are bulging, the market 
apparently will rise. 
</P>
<P>
	In such an atmosphere memories grow dim, and many of today's  
investors fail to recall that just nine years ago this summer the 
stock market lost 20 percent of its value in just three months. 
</P>
<P>
	Or for that matter, that just three years before that it  
subtracted 33.5 percent of its value in a similarly brief period. 
And that until last summer, there had been 15 bear markets since 
1948. 
</P>
<P>
	Why go back so far? Some investors barely remember that last  
summer the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 14.6 percent and the 
Nasdaq composite index plunged nearly 20 percent. This market looks 
forward, not back. 
</P>
<P>
	There are compelling reasons for it to rise: The affluence of  
ordinary people benefiting from pay raises, the daring that comes 
with a sense of new wealth, the automatic investments through 
pension funds and 401(k)s. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadly speaking, and at the risk of oversimplifying, you might  
divide today's investors into (1) those who contend they are in for 
the long term and (2) those who think they can time the market. 
</P>
<P>
	The question about the first is whether they really understand  
what ``long-term'' means. All investors live within a time frame 
imposed by age; unless they wish to endow their heirs, ``long 
term'' could be briefer than they want to admit. 
</P>
<P>
	The second group is populated by those who believe that  
foresight or dumb luck will guide their escape from a major 
downturn. The attitude is common among those who recently rode a 
stock to a 200 percent profit. 
</P>
<P>
	For the latter, market historian and adviser Gerald Perritt has  
some words, to wit: 
</P>
<P>
	``More than 50 years of rigorous academic research has failed to  
uncover one indicator that could consistently predict the onset of 
a bear market far enough in advance to improve long-run investment 
returns over a buy-and-hold strategy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perritt, a former mathematics professor and now publisher of the  
Mutual Fund Letter, adheres to the buy-and-hold strategy, declaring 
``successful investors are those who stay in the market over the 
long run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time he must make a concession to human nature.  
``The best way to weather a stock market downdraft is to know who 
you are and to determine how much downside volatility you can 
tolerate,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	Applying that philosophy to our times, a smart investor would  
ask himself (1) am I really in this for the long haul or am I 
kidding myself, and (2) do I really, truly believe I can foretell 
what might happen? 
</P>
<P>
	And, of course, they must ask themselves also whether their  
confidence is based on substance or is just a nice feeling they 
have from all the money in their pocket. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 15:17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> After 100 Years, Coward Celebration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Noel Coward had ``a talent to amuse,'' as the  
lyric in his own song, ``If Love Were All,'' so elegantly put it. 
He also possessed a famously incisive, epigrammatic wit. 
</P>
<P>
	And in this centennial year of his birth, the late English  
dramatist and songwriter is proving ripe for reappraisal, with a 
cavalcade of play revivals, galas and tributes planned at home and 
abroad of virtually every extant piece of Coward -- maybe even his 
``Calvacade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 1950s and '60s embraced gritty, working-class dramas from  
such Angry Young Men as John Osborne. But earlier writers like 
Coward and his contemporaries Somerset Maugham and Terence Rattigan 
look set to endure, as theatergoers realize that plays about 
society swells can be provocative as well as entertaining. 
</P>
<P>
	``Noel deserves our celebration,'' said actress Lynn Redgrave,  
who was directed by Coward in a now-legendary 1964 National Theater 
revival of his ``Hay Fever.'' Redgrave might play the eccentric 
Madame Arcati in a Los Angeles production of Coward's ``Blithe 
Spirit'' at the end of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's our man,'' said Michael Imison, a former agent for the  
Coward estate and coordinator of the current spate of centenary 
goings-on. ``He's one of the great world figures we can claim as 
being English.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-seven years after his death, Coward's soigne  
sophistication still embodies a certain English classiness -- 
cigarette and bon mot always at the ready. 
</P>
<P>
	A stand-up comedian, he wasn't. Ever droll, he remains.  
</P>
<P>
	Consider the following, for example, from ``Blithe Spirit'':  
</P>
<P>
	Ruth: ``If I died, I wonder how long it would be before you  
married again?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charles: ``You won't die. You're not the dying sort.''  
</P>
<P>
	Or lyrics that have become part of the language, such as ``Don't  
put your daughter on the stage, Mrs. Worthington,'' and ``Don't 
let's be beastly to the Germans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was Coward who wrote:  
</P>
<P>
	``The Stately Homes of England,  
</P>
<P>
	``How beautiful they stand,  
</P>
<P>
	``To prove the upper classes  
</P>
<P>
	``Have still the upper hand.''  
</P>
<P>
	And it was ``Mad Dogs and Englishmen'' of 1931 that assured his  
immortality: 
</P>
<P>
	``In the Philippines, there are lovely screens  
</P>
<P>
	``To protect you from the glare;  
</P>
<P>
	``In the Malay states, they have hats like plates  
</P>
<P>
	``Which the Britishers won't wear.  
</P>
<P>
	``At twelve noon, the natives swoon,  
</P>
<P>
	``And no further work is done;  
</P>
<P>
	``But mad dogs and Englishmen go out in the midday sun.''  
</P>
<P>
	For Coward, seriousness -- or, to be more accurate, earnestness --  
was as repellent as the suburban background into which he was born 
and as quickly as possible left behind, first as a child actor and 
then as the author of 50 or so plays. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning with ``The Vortex'' in 1924, a portrait of drug  
addiction and love between an older woman and a younger man 
(nowadays, he would be called a ``boy toy''), Coward depicted 
sexual mores and social finesse -- or sometimes lack thereof -- in 
ways that remain trenchant, funny, and often wounding. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, Coward's writings are almost always on view, even  
without the milestone birthday celebration -- the dramatist was born 
Dec. 16, 1899, in Middlesex, west London. 
</P>
<P>
	``Present Laughter,'' his endearingly narcissistic play about  
vainglorious Garry Essendine, an actor clearly patterned on 
himself, has had four major London and New York revivals in the 
last two decades, with George C. Scott and Frank Langella among the 
actors donning smart dressing gowns to play Gary. The 1942 comedy 
may emerge in the West End once again if Ian McKellen decides to 
take a recent sell-out production in the Yorkshire city of Leeds to 
London. 
</P>
<P>
	Coward's 1930 play, ``Private Lives,'' contains perhaps the most  
famous balcony scene besides ``Romeo and Juliet.'' Elizabeth Taylor 
and Joan Collins are just two legends who have tackled the barbed 
comedy, with mixed results, on Broadway. 
</P>
<P>
	London revisits the play May 13 at the National, where Juliet  
Stevenson is expected to play Amanda Prynne, the divorcee reunited 
on the Riviera with her former husband and favorite sparring 
partner, Elyot Chase (to be played by Anton Lesser). 
</P>
<P>
	Time-honored audience pleasers, these plays are part of a Coward  
canon of favorites that includes ``Design for Living,'' a play 
whose central (and bisexual) menage-a-trois can seem decidedly 
steamy in some directors' hands. 
</P>
<P>
	That play is on course for a late-summer London revival -- the  
first-ever Coward production of veteran director Peter Hall. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a play I've wanted to do for 20 years,'' said Hall,  
adding that he found the 1933 comedy ``very strange and haunting -- 
the last 20 minutes are absolutely amazing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No less amazing is the way the play manages to be deeply serious  
about the characters' frivolity and passion. 
</P>
<P>
	As one exchange puts it:  
</P>
<P>
	Ernest: ``You're -- you're insane! You can't be serious.''  
</P>
<P>
	Gilda: ``I'm not serious! That's what's so dreadful. I feel I  
ought to be but I'm not. ... It's shameful, I know, but I can't 
help it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By the time that revival arrives in London, ``Hay Fever'' should  
be back on the London stage, as well, with 1998 Tony nominee 
Geraldine McEwan (``The Chairs'') playing the daffy Judith Bliss, a 
hostess who takes self-absorption to comical extremes. The role was 
a Broadway success for Rosemary Harris in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	Ever the fantasist, Judith regards her grown children, Simon and  
Sorel, as a rebuke to her advancing age: 
</P>
<P>
	Simon: ``I don't see any point in trying to be younger than you  
are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Judith: ``At your age, dear, it would be indecent if you did.''  
</P>
<P>
	And what about the rest of Coward -- the remaining plays, 300  
songs, collections of short stories and verse, and at least five 
screenplays? 
</P>
<P>
	``There are so many talents Noel had, it's difficult to pin one  
down,'' 80-year-old Graham Payn, Coward's longtime lover, said in 
an interview from the French Riviera resort of Cannes. 
</P>
<P>
	``What you realize, partly because of his sexuality, was that he  
dealt with themes and ideas which are very, very modern,'' said 
Philip Hoare, a Coward biographer. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was never just about blue-rinse matrons going to Saturday  
matinees,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coward is a man who wrote about drug abuse, women taking  
younger lovers, who wrote about sexuality,'' he said. ``His plays 
were openly challenging the status quo of the '20s and '30s.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McKellen, an Academy Award nominee for his performance in ``Gods  
and Monsters,'' had never acted in a Coward play on stage until his 
recent run in ``Present Laughter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Noel's plays are about topics still thought to be pretty  
dangerous in the theater,'' McKellen said, ``and to make comedies 
of them was very clever indeed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On occasion, Coward took self-analysis still further. A frequent  
actor in his own work, he starred in the 1965 West End premiere of 
his ``A Song at Twilight,'' about a successful writer forced one 
baleful evening to own up to his bisexuality. 
</P>
<P>
	Revived in January in London, where actor Corin Redgrave  
(brother of Lynn) made an impressive Coward surrogate, the play 
seemed to pertain less to its nominal inspiration, Somerset 
Maugham, and more to Coward's fascination with masks and facades 
and what is revealed when they fall away. 
</P>
<P>
	Half a dozen other Coward plays, revues and compilations are in  
production. London will have a gala tribute on Oct. 24 at the 
Theater Royal, Drury Lane, while a similar New York event is set 
for Dec. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Too much of a good thing?  
</P>
<P>
	``It is dangerous, I think,'' said Hoare, the biographer. ``If  
you're exposing the work to a new generation that doesn't know his 
entire history, they go and see `A Song at Twilight' and think, 
`Why is this man a genius?' You need also to show them `Private 
Lives.''' 
</P>
<P>
	``My own view of Coward is he's very uneven,'' said Joel Kaplan,  
chairman of the department of drama and theater arts at England's 
Birmingham. ``(But) the best of his work can stand its ground with 
virtually anything the English theater has produced.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's fantastic. It really is,'' Payn, the writer's former  
lover, said of all the hoopla. ``Noel would be very thrilled. He 
really would.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 15:36:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Threatens To Veto Bank Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton threatened to veto financial  
overhaul legislation proposed by Senate Banking Committee Chairman 
Phil Gramm, saying it fails to fully protect consumers and would 
hurt community lending laws. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin on Wednesday  
expressed the administration's ``strong support'' for a bipartisan 
compromise bill in the House. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration supports in principle legislation to  
lift the Depression-era barriers between banks, securities firms 
and insurance companies. But the White House has threatened to veto 
several versions in recent years that took an approach it rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal drafted by Gramm, R-Texas, is more in line with the  
views of Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan than those of the 
administration. The bill calls for most new financial activities to 
be conducted by affiliated companies within bank holding companies. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to Gramm, Clinton said his proposal would  
``undermine the effectiveness of the Community Reinvestment Act 
..., a law that has helped to build homes, create jobs and restore 
hope in communities across America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Clinton wrote, the bill would ``provide inadequate  
consumer protection.'' His letter, dated Tuesday and released 
Wednesday, did not elaborate on that point. 
</P>
<P>
	An administration official cited as an example a provision in  
the compromise House bill, but absent from Gramm's, that would 
require banks selling securities to make sure they are appropriate 
for a consumer's income and circumstances. The official spoke on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will veto the bill if it is presented to me in its current  
form,'' the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm, in response, insisted that his proposal would not weaken  
the community investment law that banks must follow, but would 
``restore its integrity.'' The 1977 law requires banks and thrifts 
to lend to the poor and minorities in their neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm's opposition to the law led him to block financial  
overhaul legislation in the Senate's waning days last fall. The 
legislation had earlier squeaked through the House by one vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Under his new proposal, banks would not have to get a  
satisfactory community-lending rating from the government to set up 
holding companies to conduct new financial activities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Financial services modernization is of such overriding  
importance to the national economy that President Clinton will be 
compelled to sign'' the bill, Gramm said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The moves came a day before Gramm's Senate banking panel and the  
House Banking Committee were to vote on amendments to two separate 
financial overhaul bills. 
</P>
<P>
	In the House, Banking Committee Chairman Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa,  
and Rep. John LaFalce of New York, the panel's senior Democrat, on 
Monday unveiled a bipartisan compromise bill. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to the lawmakers Wednesday, Rubin expressed the  
administration's ``strong support.'' The Treasury chief said the 
bill ``would benefit consumers, businesses and communities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both the House and Senate bills would create huge financial  
``supermarkets,'' offering consumers checking accounts, mutual 
funds, insurance policies and much more. Ralph Nader and other 
consumer advocates have expressed concern that the legislation, by 
allowing banks, brokerage firms and insurers to merge and get more 
deeply into each other's businesses, could bring a dangerous 
concentration of economic power in fewer hands. 
</P>
<P>
	The bills before Congress have been ``cobbled together from wish  
lists of the various industry groups,'' Nader told reporters 
Wednesday. ``In the process, the rights of consumers have been 
trampled or, more often, ignored.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As an example, Nader cited the previous deletion from the House  
bill of a provision that would have required banks to offer 
low-cost, ``no frills'' checking accounts for low-income people. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration, led by the Treasury Department, and  
Greenspan's Federal Reserve have long been at odds over how an 
overhaul of the financial services laws should be accomplished. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration wants to let banks diversify through  
subsidiaries of the bank itself, not just through affiliates within 
the same parent holding company. That arrangement would increase 
the power of the Treasury's Office of the Comptroller of the 
Currency, regulator of nationally chartered banks. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other side of the battle, bills letting banks into other  
kinds of financial activities through a holding company structure 
would expand the independent Fed's role in regulating financial 
services industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
