<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Rainy weather was spreading up and down the East Coast early  
today, as thunderstorms rumbled toward coastal areas of the Pacific 
Northwest. Sierra snow was forecast. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain was possible from New England into the Southeast, with  
patchy areas of freezing rain across some Northeast valleys. 
</P>
<P>
	Thunderstorms were possible from Maryland south through the  
Carolinas and Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain and a few flurries were possible across the southern and  
eastern Great Lakes, with gusty weather developing across the 
Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	Mostly quiet conditions should prevail across much of the  
nation's midsection. 
</P>
<P>
	Western mountain snow was likely, with accumulations of a foot  
possible at higher elevations of the Cascades and Sierra Nevada. 
Blowing snow could reduce visibility to near zero. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain was possible from the coast of Washington into northern  
California, and flash flooding was a threat in some areas. A few 
thunderstorms were likely. 
</P>
<P>
	Gusty conditions should prevail over much of the West, with  
mostly dry weather across Southern California and the Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's hot spots Tuesday in the lower 48 states were the  
Texas towns of McAllen, Kingsville and Corpus Christi, with a high 
of 98. The coldest place was Yellowstone Lake, Wyo., with a low of 
13 below zero. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's temperatures should range from the 20s around the  
western Great Lakes to the 80s in the Southwest, with readings into 
the 30s in the Ohio Valley and Rockies, the 40s for the Northwest, 
the 50s in the Northeast and the central Plains, and the 60s and 
70s across the mid-Atlantic, Southeast and Gulf Coast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
