<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	2nd German Brother To Be Executed  
</P>
<P>
	FLORENCE, Ariz. (AP) -- The World Court in The Hague,  
Netherlands, is urging the federal government to do all it can to 
prevent a German citizen from execution this evening. Walter 
LaGrand, 37, is scheduled to die for stabbing a bank manager to 
death during a botched robbery in 1982. His brother was executed 
last week for the same crime, despite pleas for mercy from the 
German government. 

</P>
<P>
	Lewinsky Lambasts Ken Starr  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Monica Lewinsky asserts that Kenneth Starr  
obtained a copy of her false affidavit denying an affair with 
President Clinton before it had been filed with a court. The 
episode ``exposed the dubious methods employed by Starr's 
investigators,'' the former White House intern says in her new 
book, ``Monica's Story,'' written by British author Andrew Morton. 
The Justice Department is investigating whether Starr improperly 
detained Ms. Lewinsky last year when questioning her about her 
affair with Clinton. Her interview with Barbara Walters airs 
tonight on ABC at 9 p.m. EST. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Visits New York  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton is in the city today,  
speaking at a public school about art education. She did not 
comment on the possibility of running for the Senate. At 
Intermediate School 25 in the borough of Queens, the first lady 
unveiled a new national report plugging arts education. Polls taken 
a few weeks ago gave her a commanding lead in a hypothetical 
match-up with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for the Senate seat being 
vacated by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan in 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan Urges Budget Caution  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told  
Congress today it must make sure budget surpluses are earmarked for 
Social Security. Surpluses could be saved through a plan like 
President Clinton's that would pay down the national debt, making 
it more likely the government will continue to run large surpluses 
that could be used for Social Security in the future, Greenspan 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	Uganda Apologizes for Killings  
</P>
<P>
	KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- The FBI is investigating the murder of  
eight foreign tourists in a gorilla reserve. Apologizing for the 
deaths, President Yoweri Museveni promised to capture or kill the 
rebels who used machetes to slay the tourists -- including two 
Americans -- Monday in the mountainous rain forest near the Rwandan 
area made famous in the 1988 film ``Gorillas in the Mist.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Greaseman Apologizes for Slur  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Radio personality Doug ``The Greaseman''  
Tracht apologized today to ``anyone and everyone'' for a racial 
slur about the dragging death of a Texas man that led to his firing 
from a local radio station. Tracht was fired from WARW Radio last 
week after protests from many in the African-American community. 
Early in the week Tracht played a song by five-Grammy-award-winning 
artist Lauryn Hill then remarked: ``No wonder people drag them 
behind trucks.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Singer Dusty Springfield Dies  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Dusty Springfield is being remembered as ``one of  
the most talented female singers of this century,'' according to 
her agent, Paul Fenn. He says Springfield died last night at her 
home outside London, after a long battle with breast cancer. She 
was 59. Elton John says Springfield was the first performer he 
idolized. And Queen Elizabeth says she's saddened to hear about 
Springfield's death. The pop singer was born in Britain, and big in 
the '60s. Her hits included ``You Don't Have to Say You Love Me,'' 
``Wishin' and Hopin''' and ``Son of a Preacher Man.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Lower; Dow Down 55  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EST, the Dow industrials were  
down 55.69 to 9,241.92. NYSE decliners led advancers 1,600-1,248. 
The Nasdaq index was down 11.88 to 2,247.15. 

</P>
<P>
	Solo Yachtsman Arrives As a Winner  
</P>
<P>
	PUNTA DEL ESTE, Uruguay (AP) -- An Italian yachtsman sailed into  
port a hero and a winner today, ready for some rest and a 
celebratory glass of wine or two. ``Everything is fine, everything 
is marvelous,'' Giovanni Soldini said after capturing the third leg 
of the Around Alone regatta with a rescued French competitor 
aboard. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by KATHLEEN SAMPEY  
</P>
