<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Maine Lobster Catch Nears Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Maine (AP) -- If Maine's lobster population is on the  
verge of collapse, why did the state's total lobster catch for 1998 
come in just shy of 1997's record year? 
</P>
<P>
	Some lobstermen say it's hard to argue that there's an impending  
crisis when they keep pulling up bountiful traps. 
</P>
<P>
	Preliminary figures from the National Marine Fisheries Service  
show Maine lobstermen caught 45.5 million pounds of lobster worth 
about $132 million in 1998. That compares to the 1997 record catch 
of 47 million pounds worth $138 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``The numbers don't surprise me,'' said Pete Daley, president of  
the Maine Lobster Pound Association in Hancock. ``I think it lends 
to the theory that there's too many damn lobsters out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pete Marckoon, who compiles the data for the fisheries service  
in Rockland, said he expected a dip in lobster landings and was 
pleasantly surprised by the numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite several bumper years for lobstermen, scientists have  
been predicting a collapse of Maine's lobster fishery, similar to 
the collapse of New England's groundfish industry. The scientists 
say lobsters are being caught before they can reproduce. 
</P>
<P>
	Moreover, many lobsters died last year, apparently from a  
bacteria that is not harmful to humans. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisheries service spokeswoman Teri Frady said no one disputes  
that there are many lobsters crawling on the ocean floor right now. 
But she contends that the fishery is on the verge of immediate 
collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	``Overfishing is occurring and it won't last forever,'' Frady  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Concern over the lobster fishery has prompted regulations in  
recent years, including reductions in the number of traps in the 
water and adjustments to let small lobsters escape the traps. 
</P>
<P>
	Ed Blackmore, a retired lobsterman from Stonington, said  
conservation efforts must save the fishery in the long run. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the American way: When something gets its head up good,  
kill it -- and I think that's what is going to happen,'' said 
Blackmore, who has hauled traps for more than 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat White, executive director of the Maine Lobstermen's  
Association, said lobstermen in eastern Maine may be doing well, 
but southern Maine lobstermen are seeing a decline in landings. 
</P>
<P>
	``The warning light has come on for us,'' said White. ``We can't  
continue at this rate of harvest. I think we are definitely 
overfishing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For now, the continuing success of lobster fishermen is good  
news for consumers, who enjoy stable prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Craig Andersen, visiting Maine from St. Louis and dining on  
lobster at DiMillo's restaurant, rejoiced in the news. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love lobster. I absolutely love it and I don't want to see  
the stocks depleted. I want them to keep up,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 05:29:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Economic Indicators Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Rising stock prices and an increase in orders at  
the nation's factories carried a key gauge of future economic 
activity higher in January, signaling that the U.S. economy will 
continue to thrive through at least the middle of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	But while the gain in the Index of Leading Economic Indicators  
and a separate government report of robust home sales showed that 
the economy remains very healthy, some analysts warned that its 
rate of growth may slow in the coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board, a private research group, reported Tuesday  
that its Index of Leading Economic Indicators rose 0.5 percent to 
106.9 in January from a revised level of 106.4 in December and 
106.2 in November. The results were slightly better than the 0.4 
percent increase economists had expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the leading index posting three consecutive sharp  
increases, the U.S. economy does not seem to be ready to settle 
down much from the fast pace of growth it experienced in 1998,'' 
said Michael Boldin, senior economist with the Conference Board. 
``Over the past six months, the index has increased 1.2 percent, 
which is far above its historical average, and the prospects for 
growth in income and employment are very bright.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Commerce Department reported that although new  
home sales slipped for the second straight month in January, they 
nonetheless were very strong. Americans bought new homes at a 
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 918,000, down 5 percent from 
966,000 in December and more than 1 million in November. 
</P>
<P>
	With mortgage rates remaining under 7 percent and jobs  
plentiful, at least so far this year, most economists expect robust 
new home sales in 1999, but not quite as strong as the record 
887,000 for all of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists found signs in both reports that the economy's recent  
fast rate of growth would decline in the coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	Maury N. Harris, chief economist with PaineWebber Inc. said the  
jump in leading indicators and the continued strength in housing 
sales were the predicted results of last fall's slumping dollar and 
declines in interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``I suspect that in February, March and April they're going to  
cool off because the dollar is back up and so are interest rates,'' 
he said, referring to a recent increase in mortgage rates. The 
average interest rate on 30-year fixed-rate mortgages rose last 
week for the fourth straight week to 6.89 percent, the highest 
level since mid-November. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine of the 10 leading indicators that make up the Conference  
Board's index rose in January. Leading the way were increases in 
prices of 500 common stocks and manufacturers' orders of 
non-defense capital goods. 
</P>
<P>
	The sole area of decline was in the average factory work week.  
However, the National Association of Purchasing Management, which 
tracks the health of the nation's factories, reported Monday that 
manufacturing strengthened in February, so the one laggard in the 
January indicators might see an improvement in the near future. 
</P>
<P>
	The leading indicators index is designed to forecast economic  
activity six to nine months in advance. It operates from a base of 
100, set in 1992. First calculated in the late 1960s, it is 
periodically fine-tuned and figures from past years are revised. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
