	March 2  
</P>
<P>
	Clarin, Buenos Aires, on Guatemala truth commission:  
</P>
<P>
	In Guatemala, the Commission for Historical Clarification has  
just delivered its report on the violence witnessed by that country 
in the 36 years leading up to the signing of a peace accord in 
1996. It is an account of the hell created by the conflict between 
superpowers, by authoritarian rule and by poverty. In that small 
Central American nation, whose population is about 12 million 
inhabitants, political violence caused the death and disappearance 
of more than 200,000 people. And the report ... holds the army and 
security forces responsible for the vast majority of the crimes. 
... The land of the Mayas suffered a long war which, in addition to 
the huge number of victims, left the national territory devastated 
and much of the population in great poverty. Shedding light on the 
events of the past is an important step toward the consolidation of 
the peace process. 

</P>
<P>
	Feb. 28  
</P>
<P>
	Mainichi Shimbun, Tokyo, on Cambodian loans:  
</P>
<P>
	The third conference on aid to Cambodia ended on Feb. 26,  
agreeing to extend an additional $470 million in assistance. As the 
largest donor to Cambodia, Japan has pledged another $100 million 
in grants and technical assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	Cambodia's problems cannot be attributed solely to its  
underdeveloped politics. Its consumption tax, which was introduced 
in January to strengthen the state's finances, has contributed to 
the confusion because of uncertainty regarding the scope of the tax 
and the methods of tax collection. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, the donors attending the Tokyo conference agreed to  
increase their aid to Cambodia because of a desire to see the 
country achieve self-reliance. We hope that Hun Sen does not betray 
the hopes of the international community. ... 
</P>
<P>
	As Cambodia's largest donor, Japan must play a major role in  
monitoring how assistance money is spent. Eradicating the suspicion 
that the aid money is being diverted to line the pockets of a 
handful of influential Cambodians is a necessary prerequisite to 
achieving political and social stability. ... 

</P>
