<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Logging Deal Saves Redwood Forest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The Headwaters Forest is finally in  
public hands following a $480 million trade praised by some 
environmentalists and condemned by others as offering too much 
money for too little. 
</P>
<P>
	After more than a decade of court battles and demonstrations --  
and a weekend of tense negotiations -- Pacific Lumber Co. agreed 
just before Monday's midnight deadline to turn over the ancient 
redwoods. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition of the 12-square-mile forest gives state and  
federal officials control over the largest stand of ancient 
redwoods that remained in private ownership. Some of the trees are 
as tall as 20-story buildings and more than 2,000 years old. 
</P>
<P>
	Pacific Lumber also accepted new timber-cutting and habitat  
preservation restrictions on its remaining 330 square miles of 
redwoods and other trees, including logging bans for 12 ``lesser 
cathedral'' redwood stands, some dating back roughly 1,000 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Habitat Conservation Plan, which will last for 50 years no  
matter who owns the property. It forbids logging on the steepest 
hillsides and requires no-cut buffer zones along all year-round and 
seasonal streams in its vast timberlands in Humboldt County, about 
250 miles north of San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement ``is a big step toward protecting the ancient  
forests of Northern California,'' said Sierra Club Executive 
Director Carl Pope. 
</P>
<P>
	But other environmentalists condemned the plan for failing to  
restrict logging in more of the craggy redwood forests, home to 
more than 160 wildlife species. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have only protected a tiny fragment of what has already  
been fragmented,'' said Julia ``Butterfly'' Hill, vowing to remain 
in the redwood tree near the Headwaters groves s to protest the 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Protesters shouted similar complaints during a news conference  
held by the governor, state officials and environmental leaders in 
a grove of a dozen small redwoods outside the state Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	``What about the orphans of the Headwaters Forest agreement? Too  
many areas are sacrificed,'' shouted Susan Moloney of Garberville. 
``What we got is great, but we needed so much more. It was too 
little for too much money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While federal and state officials said they made no concessions  
after Pacific Lumber rejected the plan on Friday, company president 
John Campbell said a series of clarifications assured they will be 
able to make a profit harvesting timber. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell said there had been ``subtle changes'' that will allow  
them to selectively cut trees on unstable ground before the 
``no-cut'' buffer zones are identified. 
</P>
<P>
	``That will help improve our yield,'' he said. ``They have  
decided it is appropriate for us to selective log while we do the 
watershed assessment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But state Resources Secretary Mary Nichols said federal and  
state biologists had only provided Pacific Lumber with letters 
revising their estimates of how much lumber they believe the firm 
can cut annually under the new restrictions, from 137 million to 
170 million board-feet annually. 
</P>
<P>
	She said those figures ``are revised estimates, not concessions.  
... There are no side agreements. It's not a compromise. These are 
science-based numbers.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
