<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Lewinsky Discusses Affair on TV  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Monica Lewinsky on Wednesday disclosed an  
abortion, thoughts of suicide, and she gave the world an unabashed 
account of her life. In an ABC television interview and a separate 
book, the 25-year-old former White House intern spoke openly of 
sexual encounters with the president and several other men. But she 
saved some of her sharpest words for Kenneth Starr, the prosecutor 
who transformed her affair with Clinton into an impeachment crisis 
while providing her immunity from criminal charges. Ms. Lewinsky 
said in her book, ``Monica's Story,'' that Starr's office ``was 
sick'' for asking so many detailed questions about her sexual 
encounters. Also, Ms. Lewinsky said she now regards President 
Clinton ``to be a much bigger liar than I ever thought.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Helps Torricelli Raise $2M  
</P>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- President Clinton paid back the loyalty of  
one of his staunch impeachment defenders Wednesday, helping 
Democratic Sen. Robert Torricelli raise $2 million for a 
re-election campaign three years away. Appearing at a 
$1,000-per-ticket reception for Torricelli's 2002 re-election bid, 
Clinton praised him as a ``ferocious advocate'' for New Jersey and 
human rights and thanked him for his support. 

</P>
<P>
	Arizona Executes 2nd German Citizen  
</P>
<P>
	FLORENCE, Ariz. (AP) -- Despite pleas from the German government,  
a German citizen was executed Wednesday, a week after his brother 
was put to death for the same crime. Walter LaGrand, 37, died in 
the gas chamber for his role in the 1982 murder of a bank manager. 
His brother Karl, 35, was executed Feb. 24. Both brothers chose the 
gas chamber in hopes that courts would rule that the method is 
cruel and unusual punishment and therefore unconstitutional. The 
case drew widespread attention in Germany, which has no death 
penalty, prompting repeated diplomatic protests. 

</P>
<P>
	Sweden Found Free of Nazi Plunder  
</P>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- A two-year probe of Sweden's business  
dealings with Nazi Germany showed that little of the gold and other 
treasures accepted by the small neutral country were plundered from 
European Jews, a commission said Wednesday. The government 
commission had been appointed to determine the extent to which 
stolen gold, diamonds, art and other assets passed through Sweden 
as part of its trade with Germany during World War II. ``Sweden was 
not like Norway, where the state actually confiscated Jewish 
property,'' commission member Lennart Kanter said. ``We were not 
like Switzerland, which was known as the banking country'' of the 
1940s German regime. 

</P>
<P>
	UN: Violence Helps Spread of AIDS  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Violence against women is helping to  
spread the virus that causes AIDS, U.N. officials said Wednesday. 
Marital abuse, sexual coercion, rape and the trafficking of women 
and children are forms of violence that lead directly to HIV 
infection, experts told the U.N. Commission on the Status of Women. 
Violence against girls and women throughout the world causes more 
death and disability among females between the ages of 15 and 44 
than cancer, malaria, traffic accidents and even war, according to 
the World Health Organization. 

</P>
<P>
	Goldman Sachs To Vote on IPO  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Goldman Sachs Group LP, the last of Wall  
Street's large private investment banks, will ask its partners to 
vote next week on a plan to sell a 10 to 15 percent stake in the 
firm to the public. The firm's 220 partners are expected to approve 
the deal Monday, clearing the way for a stock sale in May or June. 
Goldman Sachs originally planned to go public last year but aborted 
its attempt in September because turmoil in financial markets 
scared off many investors and ate into Goldman's profits. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Stocks Edge Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices edged higher at the end of  
morning trading Thursday as the Nikkei gained 32.88 to 14,203.24. 
In New York on Wednesday, the Dow industrials finished down 21.73 
at 9,275.88. 

</P>
<P>
	Jazz Crush Grizzlies 109-86  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Utah won its 19th-straight home game as  
Karl Malone had 16 points and 10 rebounds in a 109-86 victory over 
the Vancouver Grizzlies on Wednesday night. The Jazz are the only 
Western Conference team the Grizzlies have never beaten. Malone has 
scored 308 points in Utah's 13 straight wins over Vancouver, more 
than any other player. 

</P>
<P>
	Agassi in Quarterfinal at Templeton  
</P>
<P>
	SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) -- Andre Agassi brushed Mariano Zabaleta  
of Argentina aside Wednesday night, winning 6-2, 6-0 to advance to 
the quarterfinals of the Franklin Templeton Tennis Classic for the 
fourth time. The first three times the mercurial star reached the 
quarterfinals in Scottsdale (1993, 1994, 1998), he went on to win. 
Agassi, seeded third and ranked ninth in the world, faces a more 
difficult test Friday against No. 6 Cedric Pioline. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
