<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cargo Ship's Bow Hits Beach Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WALDPORT, Ore. (AP) -- The broken bow of the cargo ship New  
Carissa washed back onto the beach Wednesday after attempts over 
the past month to firebomb it, pump it and tow it out to sea all 
failed to make the oil-laden menace go away. 
</P>
<P>
	The bow nosed onto the beach at dawn just off a rocky stretch of  
the Oregon coast after a storm 50 miles out in the Pacific ripped 
the hulk free from the tug that was towing it out to sea to be 
sunk. 
</P>
<P>
	Just hours earlier, Coast Guard Capt. Mike Hall lit a cigar to  
celebrate the departure of the wreckage and said: ``Certainly the 
worst-case scenario is that she would come up on shore again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Within hours of the grounding -- 60 miles north of where the ship  
originally scraped bottom Feb. 4 -- sticky tar balls began showing 
up on the beach, apparently from the bow's tanks, which were still 
holding up to 130,000 gallons of heavy bunker fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers in yellow rain slickers fanned out near the 420-foot  
wreck with shovels to scoop up oil, and booms were set up to 
protect the fragile estuary around nearby Alsea Bay. At least five 
birds were seen coated with oil. 
</P>
<P>
	Coast Guard officials scrambled to bring in another tug to pull  
the wreck back out to sea, but high winds and 20-foot swells 
prevented them from getting started. 
</P>
<P>
	For residents along Oregon's ruggedly beautiful coast, the ship  
has taken on the persona of a horror-flick villain who simply will 
not die. 
</P>
<P>
	When Jan Livingstone of the town of Yachats heard the ship broke  
free of its tow line Tuesday night, she told her husband in jest: 
``It will be on our beach in the morning.'' When she woke up, it 
was making its way through the surf outside her window. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hey, we were just joking,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	The cargo ship originally ran aground near Coos Bay in a storm  
and began leaking some of the 400,000 gallons of fuel oil aboard. 
Officials feared a disastrous spill if the ship broke apart in the 
surf, so they used plastic explosives and napalm to set the ship 
ablaze. 
</P>
<P>
	But the fire succeeded in burning away only about half the oil  
on board, and the ship split in two, fouling the beaches with 
70,000 gallons of black slime. 
</P>
<P>
	After storms scuttled a painstakingly slow process of trying to  
pump the oil out, authorities went forward with a plan to tow the 
bow 200 miles out to sea and sink it with gunboats in thousands of 
feet of water. 
</P>
<P>
	They were using what they thought was an extra-tough,  
3-inch-thick, 1,100-yard tow rope flown in from the Netherlands. 
But the line frazzled from rubbing against the bow and snapped in a 
storm that kicked up 70 mph winds and 30-foot swells. Soon, it was 
Coos Bay all over again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to have not seen it here now,'' said Coast Guard  
spokesman Matthew Brewer. ``We're just going to have to do it all 
again.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
