<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs Amish Labor Exemptions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amish children would be allowed to work in  
sawmills and other woodworking settings under legislation the House 
passed to get around Labor Department child-protection regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure, approved Tuesday on a voice vote, was needed to  
help preserve Amish religious traditions that call for youngsters 
to work in apprenticeship settings beyond eighth grade. Critics 
questioned the wisdom of letting teen-agers work in potentially 
dangerous settings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Inexperience, small size and the lack of maturity can all act  
to increase the risk of accidents,'' said Rep. William Clay of 
Missouri, ranking Democrat of the House Education and Workforce 
Committee. ``It poses undue jeopardy in the health and safety of 
children too young to legally smoke, too young to consume alcohol 
products and too young to defend this country in the military.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters termed the bill ``common-sense legislation'' to  
resolve a conflict between government regulations and the Amish way 
of life. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is extremely important that we strike a delicate balance  
between honoring the differences between religions of this country 
and having a safe and healthy workplace,'' said Tim Roemer, D-Ind. 
``This legislation strikes this principal compromise between these 
two interests.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The measure now goes to the Senate, where a similar bill died  
last year partly over doubts about the constitutionality of 
exempting one religious group. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. William Goodling, R-Pa., chairman of the labor committee,  
urged lawmakers to disregard the constitutional considerations, 
saying that was for the courts and not Congress to resolve. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would let Amish teen-agers work in sawmills,  
woodworking shops and other industries considered essential by the 
Amish but harmful by the Labor Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal child-protection laws prohibit children under 16 from  
working in manufacturing operations such as sawmills and children 
under 18 from working in other hazardous occupations, even for 
tasks that do not require operating mechanical equipment. Amish 
businesses have been fined thousands of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	The Amish are known for shunning modern conveniences and taught  
to live apart from the world and abstain from worldly goods. Some 
150,000 Amish live in 22 states and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	Their religious traditions forbid formal schooling beyond eighth  
grade, and youngsters are supposed to work with family and 
community members to gain hands-on experience in a craft. Although 
the Amish livelihood has traditionally been rooted in agriculture, 
many families have turned to woodworking and other small industries 
because of the growing costs of farming. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Amish view this work as part of their schooling,'' said  
Rep. Joseph Pitts, R-Pa., the bill's chief sponsor. ``The 
regulations have severely threatened the lifestyle and religion of 
this humble community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the legislation, teen-agers would be able to work in  
limited woodworking settings and still would be prohibited from 
directly operating mechanical equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
