<HEADLINE> Ark. Pastor Accused in Church Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The former pastor of a tiny church that  
burned in 1996 amid a series of church blazes around the South was 
accused Wednesday of setting the fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Daniel Harris, 37, who now lives in Marlow, Okla., was  
charged with one count of arson. He faces up to 20 years in prison 
and a fine of up to $250,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Johnson said Harris had not yet  
been arrested. Johnson would not answer questions about a possible 
motive. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris could not be reached for comment. A telephone operator  
said there was no listing for an Eric Daniel Harris in Marlow. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kentucky Missionary Baptist Church near Benton burned on  
Aug. 24, 1996, amid a series of fires in both predominantly black 
and white churches. Kentucky Missionary's 45-member congregation is 
white. 
</P>
<P>
	The day after the fire, Harris said in an interview: ``We were  
out here shedding tears and helping each other get through this. 
It's like watching your home burn.'' He said in the interview that 
a passing motorist noticed the fire and contacted him. 
</P>
<P>
	Rev. Dennis McClintic, who replaced Harris as pastor about two  
years ago, said the congregation is heartbroken and somewhat 
stunned by the news of Harris' indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to pray for his family. We are going to pray for  
him. The members here are not ones to hold a grudge,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
