<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans End Rally / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures retreated early today  
on the Chicago Board of Trade as a two-day rally prompted increased 
farmer selling of ample stored supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers were taking advantage of higher prices to get rid of  
crops that have seen little sign of increasing in value over the 
past few months, as weak demand walks hand-in-hand with large world 
supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans also fell under pressure from a worsening currency  
crunch in Brazil, which may lead to increased selling of competing 
crops there. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat retreated on ideas that moisture over the weekend may  
benefit newly emerged crops, while cooler weather may slow rapid 
early development. Wheat rose sharply a day earlier on fears 
below-normal temperatures in winter wheat growing regions would 
damage the crop, which accounts for about 75 percent of total U.S. 
wheat production. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures fell in step with soybeans and wheat.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for May delivery fell 3 cents to $2.60 3/4 a bushel; May corn  
fell 1 1/2 cents to $2.14 1/4 a bushel; May oats fell 1/2 cents to $1.04 3/4 a 
bushel; May soybeans fell 2 cents to $4.69 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,  
while feeder cattle were mixed and pork futures retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	April live cattle rose .05 cent to 67.75 cents a pound; March  
feeder cattle fell .23 cent to 73.17 cents a pound; April lean hogs 
fell .78 cent to 42.27 cents a pound; March pork bellies fell .32 
cent to 47.45 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
