<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers Do OK With Gretzky Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Rangers have suddenly found  
themselves after losing Wayne Gretzky. 
</P>
<P>
	Since their top scorer was sidelined by a neck injury on Friday,  
the Rangers have put together a three-game unbeaten streak to keep 
their playoff hopes alive. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think anyone would have thought we'd have the success  
that we've had over the last three games -- five points out of six 
against the quality of teams we've played,'' Rangers coach John 
Muckler said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're all very good hockey clubs, so over the last three  
games you have to be proud of our team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	First, the Rangers beat the Phoenix Coyotes 3-0. Then the  
Philadelphia Flyers 6-5. And Tuesday night, the Rangers tied the 
league-leading Dallas Stars 2-2. 
</P>
<P>
	It has been an impressive stretch for the Rangers, not only  
because of the teams they have played but because of their injury 
situation. Gretzky hasn't been the only one out. Todd Harvey, Jeff 
Buekeboom and Peter Popovic have also been sidelined. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone realizes that collectively, we have to fill the  
void,'' said Adam Graves, who has played on the top line with 
Gretzky for most of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury to Gretzky couldn't have come at a worse time for the  
Rangers. They're in a five-team struggle for a playoff berth. Even 
with Tuesday night's tie, they dropped four points out of the final 
spot, currently held by the Boston Bruins. 
</P>
<P>
	Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said he ``could see the desperation  
(in the Rangers') eyes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers thoroughly impressed Hitchcock.  
</P>
<P>
	``This was as hard as this team has played us in a long time,''  
Hitchcock added. 
</P>
<P>
	That has basically been the Rangers' game plan since Gretzky  
went down and the team learned he would be missing for a minimum of 
two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're playing better defensively,'' Muckler said. ``We're  
doing more forechecking. A lot of people have stepped up. We talked 
about this when Wayne went down. The guys in the dressing room 
weren't afraid of that challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're playing as a team. They're working hard. They believe  
in each other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Petr Nedved has been among the most prominent of the Rangers to  
step forward. Since taking over Gretzky's center spot on the 
Rangers' top line, Nedved has so far produced three goals and three 
assists in the three games. 
</P>
<P>
	Another key player in the streak has been Graves, who scored his  
30th goal Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``He does so many things for us,'' goaltender Mike Richter said  
of Graves. ``He's a great penalty killer. Once he gets the puck, 
he's a very difficult player to get it away from. He battles in 
front. He gets hard goals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York's special teams have also rated a star in the last  
three games as the Rangers evened their home record at 14-14-3. 
Against Dallas, the Rangers killed all seven of the Stars' power 
plays. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our play has improved and that has given us the confidence and  
the ability to win games,'' Richter said. ``We finally started 
making Madison Square Garden a tough place to play.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
