<P>
	Computer Stocks Have Rough Day  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Computer stocks dropped after 3Com Corp., which  
sells Internet data, voice and video systems, said that 
third-quarter operating earnings will be far below analysts' 
expectations because of an ``unexpected slowdown'' in sales to 
businesses in the United States and Latin America. 3Com's statement 
followed similar warnings of soft computer sales from Compaq 
Computer and Micron Electronics, a unit of Micron Technology. 3Com 
stock was down 2 3/8 at 24 5/8 in leading volume in Nasdaq trading, after 
dropping from 27 late yesterday in after-hours trading. Stocks were 
also pushed lower by the bond market, where prices sank after the 
National Association of Purchasing Management said its index of 
non-manufacturing activity rose to 57.0 percent in February, from 
January's 54 percent. But, the group's index of non-manufacturing 
prices eased, to 46.5 percent from 47 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Cheaper or Free Internet Entry Seen  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The early success of firms offering internet  
access free may present a challenge to today's practice of pay to 
get in. Last week, Gateway announced that it would throw in a free 
year of its Internet service with any computer purchase of more 
than $1,000. But even more threatening to the stranglehold of the 
pay-for-service providers has been the early success of some new 
rivals that let you dial up for free. One such is Freeserve, which 
has more than a million Britons signed on since it began operating 
in September. It has already surpassed America Online as Britain's 
most popular Internet access provider. 

</P>
<P>
	Dell Opens Online Superstore  
</P>
<P>
	ROUND ROCK, Texas (AP) -- Dell Computer Corp. opened an online  
superstore today for consumers to buy computer-related products. 
The store, which can be found at www.gigabuys.com, offers shoppers 
more than 30,000 computer-related products from many leading 
brands, including printers, digital cameras, scanners, games, 
software and business products, the company said. 

</P>
<P>
	Amway Plans New Web Site in Sept.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Amway may be venturing into the faceless world  
of the Internet, but the direct-selling giant will still depend on 
real people to promote its business online. Amway, known for its 
cheery salespeople who sell household goods to friends in their 
living rooms, announced today that it will launch a new Web site, 
Quixtar.com, in September. Amway's move online isn't a reach for 
the Ada, Mich.-based company. It has already solved one of the 
biggest challenges faced by Internet retailers -- it has an 
established distribution network in place. 

</P>
<P>
	No-Additive Cigarettes Not Safer  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators said today they have  
reached an agreement with R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. to put notices 
on the company's Winston cigarette ads that just because they have 
no additives does not mean they are safer. The agreement will 
settle a charge by the Federal Trade Commission, which regulates 
advertising, that the ads for Winston ``no additives'' cigarettes 
are deceptive. The federal agency charged that RJR implied in the 
ads, without any basis, that the Winston cigarettes are safer to 
smoke because they contain no additives. 

</P>
<P>
	GM February U.S. Sales Up 17 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. today reported its February  
U.S. sales surged a surprising 17 percent, due in part to 
aggressive spending on rebates and other discounts. GM saw 
improvement across the board compared with February 1998. Its car 
sales were up 19 percent, while sales of light trucks increased 15 
percent. The No. 1 automaker has been trying to reverse a slide in 
its U.S. market share, which fell to 29 percent last year. 

</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong, Disney Discuss Theme Park  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Walt Disney Co. Chairman Michael Eisner  
appears to be a step closer to entering China in a major way, as 
Hong Kong and Disney officials confirmed today they have been in 
talks about building a theme park in the former British colony. It 
might be located on an outlying island where the new airport is 
located. A decision is expected by June. Disney, which already has 
parks in the United States, France and Japan, including Tokyo 
DisneySea opening in 2001, could benefit from a Hong Kong theme 
park to ``gain a foothold in the region'' to build business for 
everything from movies to consumer products, said James Zoltak, 
West Coast Editor of Amusement Business magazine, a trade 
publication. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Imports of Wine Double  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Move over, sake. The Japanese, encouraged by  
affordable foreign brands and reports of health benefits, are 
guzzling imported wine in record amounts. Wine imports more than 
doubled in 1998 to reach all-time highs both in terms of volume, 
88.5 million gallons, and value, $1.4 billion, the Tokyo Customs 
Office says. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Levies Sanctions in Trade Fight  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration said today that,  
starting immediately, more than $500 million worth of European 
imports will be subject to eventual punitive trade sanctions 
because of an ongoing trade fight between the U.S. and Europe over 
bananas. The sanctions would take effect immediately but would be 
paid retroactively when, and if, a World Trade Organization panel 
approves the United States' request to penalize the importers. The 
100 percent punitive duties, by doubling prices, could effectively 
knock products ranging from French handbags to German coffeemakers 
out of the U.S. market. 

</P>
<P>
	Bahrain Opens Market to Foreigners  
</P>
<P>
	MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) -- Bahrain, the leading financial center in  
the Middle East, opened its doors today for increased foreign 
participation in stock trading in an effort to boost its economy. 
According to a decree issued by Bahrain's ruler, Sheik Isa bin 
Salman Al Khalifa, citizens of the six-nation Gulf Cooperation 
Council will be allowed to own 100 percent stakes in companies 
listed in the local stock exchange, the official Gulf News Agency 
reported. Other foreigners will be allowed to hold 49 percent 
stakes, the agency added quoting Commerce Minister Ali Saleh 
al-Saleh. 

</P>
