<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Will Explain Tripp's Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Virginia congressman demanded to know today  
why the Defense Department was paying Linda Tripp more than $90,000 
a year at the same time it is making drastic cuts elsewhere in the 
Pentagon's civilian work force. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll answer that one for the record,'' Defense Secretary  
William Cohen told Rep. Jim Moran, D-Va., indicating he would 
submit his answer in writing later. 
</P>
<P>
	``I suspected you would,'' Moran told Cohen, who was testifying  
before the House Appropriations defense subcommittee on President 
Clinton's fiscal 2000 defense budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Moran, who represents the northern Virginia suburbs of  
Washington, where many Pentagon workers live, said it was 
``something that has been griping me for some time,'' particularly 
since so many of civilian defense jobs in the area had been cut by 
Clinton in the name of government streamlining. 
</P>
<P>
	Tripp, the Pentagon worker who secretly recorded conversations  
with Monica Lewinsky about her young co-worker's relationship with 
President Clinton, began a new job Wednesday, working as a public 
affairs specialist in the Defense Manpower Data Center. She will 
keep her previous salary of $94,098. 
</P>
<P>
	She will work in an office building near the Pentagon.  
</P>
<P>
	Tripp's turning over of the tapes to Independent Counsel Kenneth  
Starr led eventually to Clinton's impeachment trial, where he was 
acquitted. Although in her previous position as director of the 
Joint Civilian Orientation Conference she had an office in the 
Pentagon, she mostly worked from home once the scandal erupted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see that one particular employee, who has been paid over  
$90,000 a year for the last two years to do nothing, by her own 
admission, she spent much of her year listening to some stupid 
adolescent talk about her sex life,'' Moran said. 
</P>
<P>
	``So you've rehired her in some makeshift job that looks to be  
another kind of job that gives a black eye to the credibility of 
the whole federal work force,'' Moran said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tripp, who lives in Maryland, is under investigation there by a  
state prosecutor who is looking into whether she violated 
Maryland's wiretapping law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
