<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Ordered Killings for Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An immigrant who got his start pumping gas and  
became a millionaire with a chain of service stations in four 
states has been convicted of ordering two contract killings to 
protect his operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Gurmeet Singh Dhinsa, 36, was found guilty today in federal  
court of murder in the aid of racketeering. 
</P>
<P>
	He was also convicted of rigging gas pumps to rip off motorists,  
evading taxes and terrorizing fellow immigrants who threatened to 
expose him. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury will return on Monday to hear evidence on whether he  
should get the death penalty or life without parole. 
</P>
<P>
	Dhinsa arrived in the United States in 1982 from India's Punjab  
region and took a job pumping gas. He saved enough money to lease 
that gas station, then began opening others. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually, his City Gas chain had 51 stations in New York, New  
Jersey, Pennsylvania and Delaware, and employed 300 people. Annual 
revenue topped $60 million. 
</P>
<P>
	But the city repeatedly cited Dhinsa for overcharging customers.  
And in 1990, he was arrested in the kidnap-torture of one of his 
attendants. He served 90 days in jail on lesser charges. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, another City Gas employee vanished. When the employee's  
brother confronted Dhinsa, the businessman allegedly paid a 
criminal to kill the brother. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Dhinsa struck again in 1997, ordering the  
killing of a cab driver who was cooperating in an FBI investigation 
of City Gas. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Benton Campbell described Dhinsa as a ``man who uses  
murder as a way of doing business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Gerald Shargel said Dhinsa was a victim of  
false testimony from the hit men and rumors spread by a rival 
faction of Sikhs in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
