<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chiang Booted From Taiwan Banknotes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- In another sign his legacy has fallen, the  
face of late Chinese Nationalist leader Gen. Chiang Kai-shek will 
disappear from most of Taiwan's banknotes, giving way to symbols of 
high-tech industry and lively students. 
</P>
<P>
	Chiang's smiling face will be removed from the notes for 500 and  
1,000 Taiwanese dollars, which are worth about $15 and $30, but 
will appear on a newly minted, and presumably less circulated, 200 
dollar note, worth about $6, the Central Bank said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	After leading China through World War II before he lost a civil  
war to the Communists and retreated to Taiwan, Chiang was long 
revered as Taiwan's absolute leader. But admiration for Chiang has 
dropped steadily since his death in 1975, and opposition parties -- 
legalized after the end of martial law in 1987 -- have branded him a 
dictator. 
</P>
<P>
	As Chiang's image is removed from the larger-denomination bills,  
designs of students, baseball players, and indigenous endangered 
species of salmon, birds and deer will appear. 
</P>
<P>
	The face of Sun Yat-sen, who led the revolution that overthrew  
the last Chinese emperor and founded the Chinese republic in 1911, 
will remain on Taiwan's smallest-denomination banknote, the 100 
dollar bill, worth about $3. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose Lin, a Taipei office worker, welcomed the change.  
</P>
<P>
	``For a long while, we have had too many political symbols and  
too few designs with indigenous color,'' she said. But Lin agreed 
it was a good idea to keep Chiang on some small bills. 
</P>
<P>
	``People still respect him and there is no need to eliminate all  
his images,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	After Chiang's death, he had remained a symbol for Taiwan's  
reunification with China, a goal since placed on the back burner by 
his Nationalist successors who have sought to affirm the island's 
separate status from the mainland. 
</P>
<P>
	Chiang's portraits and statues have been removed from local  
government offices controlled by opposition politicians. But his 
name is still used for Taipei's international airport and a 
memorial park dedicated to him in the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	While seeking images to replace Chiang on the banknotes,  
authorities rejected suggestions they use political figures 
considered to have contributed to developing Taiwan prior to 1949. 
They likely wanted to avoid any perceptions that they were seeking 
to promote Taiwan's formal independence from China. 
</P>
<P>
	Those figures included Liu Ming-chuan, the first Qing dynasty  
governor of Taiwan, appointed in 1886, and Koxinga, the 
half-Japanese patriot who drove 17th century Dutch colonizers out 
of Taiwan. 
</P>
<P>
	The new banknotes will start circulating in July next year when  
the Central Bank takes over currency making duties from the Bank of 
Taiwan, a big commercial bank, under a government restructuring 
plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
