<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 00:32:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Independent Counsels Losing Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is trying to build  
momentum in Congress for allowing the independent counsel law to 
expire on June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional officials said President Clinton's personal  
attorney, Bob Bennett, would argue the administration's case 
against the Watergate-inspired law in testimony today before the 
Senate Governmental Affairs Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration, battered by Independent Counsel Kenneth  
Starr's five-year probe, reversed course Tuesday and announced it 
was withdrawing support for the law. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration's witnesses are speaking to a Congress  
already hostile to renewing the law. Angered by independent counsel 
investigations of President Reagan and then Clinton, lawmakers of 
both parties oppose the law's renewal without at least a major 
overhaul. 
</P>
<P>
	House members and senators have suggested changes in the law,  
but without a consensus, sentiment is growing for letting it 
expire. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the administration for the first time went on record  
against the statute when Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder told a 
House subcommittee that it ``has failed in its goal of removing 
politics from the process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The act was supposed to increase trust in our government;  
unfortunately, it has diminished it,'' Holder told the House 
Judiciary subcommittee on commercial and administrative law. 
</P>
<P>
	``The climate of politicization pervades the process, regardless  
of which way a specific decision, investigation or prosecution 
comes out,'' he said in prepared remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a marked reversal from five years ago, when Clinton and  
Attorney General Janet Reno successfully lobbied for the law's 
renewal. 
</P>
<P>
	Holder emphasized several times that the administration's  
reversal ``does not have to do with any particular inquiry or 
investigation. It has to do with the fact that the types of 
decisions we are talking about here can be controversial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the White House, spokesman Barry Toiv said Clinton ``concurs  
with the judgment of the Justice Department that the statute should 
not be renewed -- that its flaws outweigh its benefits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Toiv said Clinton's judgment was ``a policy decision based on  
his observation of how the law's been implemented.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under questioning from subcommittee Chairman George Gekas,  
R-Pa., Holder told the panel that he first secured Reno's approval, 
then submitted his testimony to White House Counsel Charles Ruff 
late last week. ``He indicated to us that we proceed,'' Holder 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The law provides for an independent counsel selected by three  
judges to investigate allegations against specified administration 
officials. Reno has had seven independent counsels appointed in 
Clinton's six years in office, more than any other attorney 
general. 
</P>
<P>
	Without renewal, the law will expire June 30 and any future  
investigations of high-ranking government officials would be 
handled by the Justice Department. In rare cases, Holder said, the 
attorney general could appoint special prosecutors in cases where 
conflicts of interest clearly exist. 
</P>
<P>
	That was how the system worked until President Nixon fired  
special prosecutor Archibald Cox during the Watergate scandal. 
Nixon's move convinced Congress that probes of presidents and other 
high-ranking officials should be conducted by outsiders not 
accountable to those they investigate. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-one years after its inception, Republicans and Democrats  
complain the law does not hold independent counsels accountable for 
their conduct of investigations or for the millions of public 
dollars they spend. 
</P>
<P>
	Holder also told the panel that Justice officials met recently  
with Starr and listened to his objections about the department 
investigating his conduct during the Clinton probe, but no 
negotiations took place and Reno will make any final decisions 
about who will conduct the investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
