<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 16:05:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Beckham Stars in Manchester Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Dwight Yorke scored the goals but it was David  
Beckham who inspired Manchester United to a 2-0 victory over Inter 
Milan in the European Champions Cup on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The talented midfielder set up both goals with right wing  
crosses before halftime and Manchester United, whose only Champions 
Cup success was in 1968, will be confident of reaching the 
semifinal. 
</P>
<P>
	In other quarterfinal matches, defending champion and seven-time  
titlist Real Madrid was held to a 1-1 tie at home by Dynamo Kiev 
and Bayern Munich downed Kaiserslautern 2-0 in a meeting of two 
German Bundesliga clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	Juventus, which is bidding to make the final for the fourth  
season in a row, beat Olympiakos 2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	It was clearly Beckham's night in the Old Trafford confrontation  
with Diego Simeone, the player whose self-confessed play-acting led 
to the Englishman's much-publicized expulsion in last summer's 
World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Simeone played inventively and forcefully in Inter's  
midfield, Beckham set up both of Yorke's goals with precision 
crosses from the right. 
</P>
<P>
	Three Inter defenders left Yorke unmarked in the seventh minute  
as he headed home Beckham's measured cross and, when the 
fair-haired star launched another from the right just before 
halftime, the Tobagan striker climbed above the Inter defense for 
his eighth goal in seven Champions Cup games. 
</P>
<P>
	``David Beckham was absolutely magnificent,'' United manager  
Alex Ferguson said. ``But we had a lot of good players. Two-nil is 
a great result for us and we will score over there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Andrei Shevchenko gave Dynamo Kiev a 56th minute lead at the  
Bernabeu stadium in Madrid but Predrag Mijatovic hit back for Real 
11 minutes later as the defending titlist earned a tie. 
</P>
<P>
	Two goals in four minutes put Bayern in charge of its showdown  
with Kaiserlautern, the team which surprisingly beat it to the 
Bundesliga title last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Struggling in the league without star striker Alessandro Del  
Piero who is out until next season with a serious knee injury, 
Juventus went two goals ahead on Filippo Inzaghi's shot in the 38th 
and Antonio Conte's 11 minutes from the end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
