<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Retirement Community Now a City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAGUNA WOODS, Calif. (AP) -- When elected officials went to work  
Wednesday in America's newest and perhaps oldest city, they learned 
it was Leisure World no longer. 
</P>
<P>
	With all precincts reporting, 51.7 percent of the 10,336 voters  
supported turning the gated retirement community of Leisure World 
into a city, now called Laguna Woods. Absentee votes were still 
being counted, but they weren't expected to change the outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory Tuesday also led to election of an interim council  
for the city, which has a minimum age of 55 and average age of 77. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have an awful lot of work to do,'' said Bert Hack, one of  
five council members elected. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the vote was so close, there's fence-mending to do with  
neighbors who didn't want their private retirement community of 
18,000 to become just another town. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to keep things the way they were,'' Hack said. ``While  
there are a lot of changes happening outside, we want to keep 
things the way they are in the community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leisure World, about 50 miles south of Los Angeles, advertised  
itself as the biggest retirement center on the West Coast. Opened 
in 1964, it is slightly younger than Leisure World in Seal Beach, 
to the northwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of cityhood had worried that the new government would  
encourage strip malls around the community or try to raise taxes in 
more direct ways. 
</P>
<P>
	``I keep asking those people who left the city, `Why do you want  
to be in a city?''' said Bea Hassel Rogatz, oldest council 
candidate at 91 and a cityhood opponent. She was not elected. 
</P>
<P>
	The fenced enclave has two professional golf courses, eight  
tennis courts, an 844-seat theater, five large swimming pools, 
spas, lawn bowling greens, shuffleboard courts and a fitness 
center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
