<HEADLINE> 2 Planes Nearly Collide Over Kansas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Two large cargo planes almost collided  
33,000 feet over Kansas after apparently losing radio contact with 
an air traffic control center, a federal investigator said today. 
</P>
<P>
	No one was injured.  
</P>
<P>
	The incident Tuesday morning involved a Federal Express  
McDonnell Douglas DC-10 traveling from Portland, Ore., to Memphis, 
Tenn., and an American International Airways Lockheed L-1011 en 
route from Los Angeles to Indianapolis, National Transportation 
Safety Board air safety investigator Jim Silliman said today. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're continuing the investigation, trying to get more details  
from both cargo holders,'' Silliman said today from Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	One crew said it might have come as close as 100 feet, Silliman  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, a spokesman for Kitty Hawk Inc., which recently bought  
American International Airways, disputed that report. 
</P>
<P>
	``The closest report I'm getting from the crews, it was a half a  
mile,'' Tom Christopher said from the Grapevine, Texas-based 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Both planes apparently lost contact with the Kansas City control  
center. 
</P>
<P>
	Air traffic controllers reported that the two planes merged into  
one blip on radar, The Washington Post reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of one crew said their plane might have come as close as  
100 feet to the other, Silliman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither plane had a traffic alert and collision avoidance  
system, although they are not required to be equipped with them, 
Silliman said. 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't know how many people were on the planes, but said each  
would have had at least three. 
</P>
</TEXT>
