<DOCNO> APW19990303.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 10:17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Ringo Starr </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Ringo Starr was 22 when he became the drummer  
for the Beatles. It was August 1962, before the Beatles became the 
world's most popular band. 
</P>
<P>
	Decades after the Beatles disbanded, Starr, 58, still finds it  
``a thrill every night'' to play drums and sing with some of his 
favorite musicians. 
</P>
<P>
	That's why Starr is on the road with his latest All-Starr Band --  
there have been five in the past 10 years -- playing 30 dates in 22 
U.S. cities. The tour ends in Orlando, Fla., on March 29. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I thought about doing it in 1989, I didn't want to end up  
in front all night. I get other drummers and other singers, plus 
guitars and keyboards. It's a great way for me to do it. I do my 
stuff, say 'Hi, peace and love,' and I play on the drum kit,'' 
Starr said. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's All-Starr band includes Timmy Cappello, Simon Kirke,  
Gary Brooker, Todd Rundgren and Jack Bruce. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether the Beatles would be doing a reunion tour if John  
Lennon were alive, Starr said, ``I have no idea.'' Then he added, 
``More than likely. We would have stood a better chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Miramax Films just announced plans to release the  
Beatles' 1964 film, ``A Hard Day's Night,'' with new footage and a 
digitally restored soundtrack. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the breakup of the Beatles, Starr has appeared in more  
than a dozen movies. 
</P>
<P>
	He has also made some solo albums, recording whatever interests  
him. 
</P>
<P>
	His first album was ``Sentimental Journey,'' filled with songs  
from his childhood. His second was a country-music album recorded 
in Nashville, Tenn. His third, ``Ringo,'' released in 1973, had a 
little help from his former Beatle bandmates (although they weren't 
in the recording studio at the same time). 
</P>
<P>
	Starr answered questions while the All-Starr Band was in New  
York for two concerts at the Beacon Theater. 
</P>
<P>
	1. Why do you put together the All-Starr Bands, and how do you  
know the musicians you choose will work well together? 
</P>
<P>
	Starr: I do it because I get to play with an incredible array of  
musicians. I personally have a lot of fun. We don't know if it'll 
work. We end up in rehearsals and pray to God it is going to 
happen. So far in the 10 years it has always worked. 
</P>
<P>
	2. The next All-Starr Band live CD will be released in May. Are  
you disappointed that radio doesn't pick up your new material? 
</P>
<P>
	Starr: You'd like all radio stations to pick up on you. There's  
a lot of pressure on most stations just to play top 40s or oldies 
but goldies -- which I slip right into. There are still some DJs 
around but they're being dictated to by the policy of the station. 
I must have had dinner with every radio station in America. They 
still don't play it (the new music). Maybe it's the food, I don't 
know. 
</P>
<P>
	3. How did you feel when the Beatles came to New York the first  
time? 
</P>
<P>
	Starr: It was like this big octopus was coming up to bring the  
plane down; the energy was coming to get it. The kids were outside 
waiting for us. There was media madness going on. We had all these 
TVs on and radios on in the hotel. We could call a radio station 
and hear ourselves. It was incredible. It was the most exciting 
period of my life. 
</P>
<P>
	4. How would you describe touring with the All-Starr Band?  
</P>
<P>
	Starr: It is not quite so crazy now. Touring is touring. The gig  
-- playing the show -- is the best thing you can do. We're musicians. 
Getting there is boring. You get on the bus, plane or train, go to 
the other places. If they had that transporter -- if it was actually 
'Star Trek' -- it would make life a lot easier. Playing the gigs is 
the thrill. 
</P>
<P>
	5. When you recorded ``With a Little Help From My Friends,'' did  
you think it would become an anthem or were you thinking of it only 
as an album track? 
</P>
<P>
	Starr: Just an album track. I didn't think, 'Oh, in 1999 I'll be  
out touring with the All-Starrs singing it.' At the time, you're 
just doing it. Thank God I did do that track. Other friends -- with 
their help -- have given me a career, really, these last 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
