<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Prices Fall Again / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices fell again Wednesday as investors  
remained bearish, pushing the yield to a seven-month high. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1 5/32, or  
$11.56 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, rose to 5.69 percent from 5.61 percent late 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time the yield was this high was July 31, when the  
yield was 5.71 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices sank after the National Association of Purchasing  
Management said its index of non-manufacturing activity rose to 57 
in February, from January's reading of 54. Analysts said the 
increase was a sign that inflation was on the rise, even though the 
same group's index of non-manufacturing prices eased to 46.5 from 
47. 
</P>
<P>
	Many believe the Federal Reserve is poised to slow borrowing and  
spending with a boost in interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan declined to address monetary policy  
during Social Security testimony before the House Commerce 
Committee Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising interest rates hurt bonds by making their yields less  
competitive, while inflation makes fixed-income investments less 
attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market Tuesday, prices of short-term Treasury  
securities fell 3/32 point, while intermediate maturities fell 7/32 
to 1/2 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lehman Brothers Daily Treasury Bond Index, reflecting price  
movements on bonds with maturities of a year or longer, fell 1.87 
points to 1,276.97. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 4.59 percent as the  
discount fell 0.07 percentage point from late Tuesday to 4.47 
percent. Six-month yields fell to 4.71 percent, as the discount 
fell 0.02 percentage point from late Tuesday to 4.54 percent. 
One-year yields rose to 4.87 percent, while the discount fell .03 
percentage point from Tuesday's auction rate to 4.63 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.75 percent from 4.69 percent late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell to 123 5/8 from 124 1/32. The average 
yield to maturity rose to 5.25 percent from 5.23 percent Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
