<DOCNO> APW19990303.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 15:36:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Retailers Report Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Kmart Corp. and Tiffany &AMP; Co. topped Wall Street's expectations  
with strong fourth-quarter profit reports. Kmart's business was 
fueled by shoppers looking for affordable prices and wide 
selection, while Tiffany attracted consumers willing to spend top 
dollar for luxury goods. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Kmart Corp.    	
</P>
<P>
	The Troy, Mich.-based Kmart, which is the nation's third-largest  
retailer, earned $353 million, or 65 cents a share, in the fourth 
quarter ended Jan. 27, compared with $186 million, or 35 cents a 
share, a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1997 results include a $114 million charge relating to a  
voluntary early retirement program. Excluding the charge, earnings 
were 50 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for the quarter were $10.4 billion, up from $9.75 billion  
a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Kmart's results topped Wall Street analysts' expectations. Its  
stock fell 18 3/4 cents to $17.50 in trading on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kmart is on the right track and gaining speed,'' said Floyd  
Hall, Kmart chairman, chief executive and president. 
</P>
<P>
	Kmart enjoyed strong sales of key brands, including Martha  
Stewart Everyday home fashions, Route 66 apparel and accessories 
and Sesame Street children's clothing. 
</P>
<P>
	It also found success in its recently reformatted Big Kmart  
stores, which pair full supermarkets with its discount stores 
concept. Of Kmart's 2,161 stores, 1,245 are now Big Kmarts. 
</P>
<P>
	For all of 1998, Kmart earned $518 million or $1.01 a share,  
compared with $249 million or 51 cents per share for 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1998 results include a $19 million pretax charge for its  
early retirement programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for the year totaled $33.67 billion, up from $32.2 billion  
a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to last year's earnings, Kmart also released  
Wednesday its sales figures for February, the first glimpse of how 
it is doing in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Same-store sales, which tracks sales at stores open more than a  
year, rose 5.8 percent last month. Total sales, which includes all 
of its stores, rose 7.4 percent in February. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Tiffany &AMP; Co.    	
</P>
<P>
	The New York-based upscale retailer earned $53.29 million, or  
$1.49 a share, in the fourth quarter ended Jan. 31, compared with 
$42.09 million, or $1.17 a share, in the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales rose 20 percent to $442.8 million, up from $367.7 million  
a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Tiffany's results topped Wall Street analysts' expectations. Its  
stock closed up $2.12 1/2 at $61 in trading on the NYSE. 
</P>
<P>
	Tiffany's sales in the United States rose 24 percent from a year  
ago, fueled by continued U.S. economic growth and high levels of 
consumer confidence. Shoppers bought up lots of its gold and silver 
jewelry, crystal vases and china dinnerware. 
</P>
<P>
	Its international sales were up 21 percent from a year ago, with  
gains even coming in economically troubled Asia. Sales in Japan 
rose 13 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite challenging conditions in certain markets during the  
year, Tiffany's growth strategies continued to demonstrate their 
ability to generate strong sales and earnings growth,'' said 
Tiffany chairman William Chaney. 
</P>
<P>
	For the year, Tiffany earned $90.06 million, or $2.60 a share,  
compared with $72.82 million, or $2.02 a share, the year before. 
Sales for the year were $1.17 billion, up from $1.02 billion in 
1997. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 15:36:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German's Execution Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FLORENCE, Ariz. (AP) -- Amid pleas of mercy from the German  
government, a federal appeals court on Wednesday ordered Arizona 
not to use the gas chamber to execute a German man whose brother 
was put to death last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9th Circuit Court of Appeals refused to issue a stay for  
Walter LaGrand, 37, who was scheduled to die in a cloud of cyanide 
fumes Wednesday afternoon for his role in the 1982 murder of a bank 
manager. 
</P>
<P>
	But the judges did say that the gas chamber is cruel and unusual  
punishment, and therefore unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	The state appealed to the Supreme Court, but it was unclear when  
the execution would proceed. If the state is forced to ask for 
another death warrant from the Arizona Supreme Court, it would 
likely hold up the execution for weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the 9th Circuit issued a stay in a nearly identical  
appeal by LaGrand's brother, Karl. But the Supreme Court overturned 
it in a matter of hours, and Karl was executed by injection for his 
part in the bank murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Walter LaGrand's case also was heard Wednesday in the  
International Court of Justice in The Hague, Netherlands. Germany 
asked the world court to intervene after Arizona Gov. Jane Hull 
rejected appeals from German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder and 
Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer to stop the execution. 
</P>
<P>
	The international court has no enforcement powers, but in a  
special, half-hour hearing, Judge Christopher Weeramantry of Sri 
Lanka urged the U.S. government to use ``all the measures at its 
disposal'' to prevent the execution. 
</P>
<P>
	The court also said the United States should pay unspecified  
damages for the death of LaGrand's brother, Karl, 35, who was the 
first German citizen executed in the United States since World War 
II. 
</P>
<P>
	Like his brother, Karl requested the gas chamber in hopes that  
the Supreme Court would agree that the method is unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	The high court disagreed and lifted the 9th Circuit's stay. Karl  
then accepted the state's last-minute offer of lethal injection. 
Walter rejected such an offer and said he would prefer a more 
painful execution in the gas chamber to protest the death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Arizona executed an inmate in the gas chamber, in  
1992, his death took 11 minutes and was considered so gruesome that 
the law was changed to require lethal injection. Killers sentenced 
to death before 1992, like the LaGrands, are given a choice. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany does not have the death penalty and contends Arizona  
failed to advise the LaGrand brothers of their right to consular 
assistance at their trials. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona officials conceded they violated the Vienna Convention  
but insisted the LaGrands were accorded all the rights any U.S. 
citizen would have received. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 38 states with capital punishment, only Arizona,  
California, Maryland, Missouri and Wyoming offer the gas chamber as 
an optional method, according to Richard Dieter, executive director 
of the National Death Penalty Information Center. Only 10 of the 
more than 500 inmates executed since the death penalty was restored 
in 1976 have been put to death in the gas chamber, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 15:06:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lewinsky Book Not Kind to Ginsburg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- William Ginsburg, a once-obscure malpractice  
lawyer who talked his way to stardom in the Monica Lewinsky case, 
is portrayed as a villain in the new book about the former White 
House intern. 
</P>
<P>
	Hired by Ms. Lewinsky's father to represent his daughter,  
Ginsburg is described in ``Monica's Story'' as a relentless 
self-promoter, a meddler in the Lewinsky family's private affairs, 
a purveyor of crude comments and a man who shaded the truth. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsburg denied the allegations when portions of the book were  
read to him. ``Her need to blame me is understandable,'' he said. 
``She can't blame her parents. They're part of her support tree. So 
I'm a very good person to take shots at.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the months after Ms. Lewinsky's name burst into public view  
in January 1998, the only way to miss the Los Angeles attorney was 
to give up television and radio and never read a newspaper. He 
appeared on every Sunday talk show. 
</P>
<P>
	But while Ginsburg was serving publicly as Ms. Lewinsky's  
lawyer, spokesman and bodyguard, he generated increasing friction 
in the Lewinsky family and eventually was replaced by two veteran 
Washington attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsburg acted as a surrogate father when he accompanied Ms.  
Lewinsky around Washington in the early months of the scandal, 
telling reporters how he knew her when she was an infant. 
</P>
<P>
	``He maintained that he had kissed her inner thighs when she was  
just six days old -- even though in reality he did not meet her 
until she was in her early twenties,'' the book by Andrew Morton 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not true,'' Ginsburg said. ``I knew her when she was  
very young.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A chapter on Ginsburg begins with his telling Ms. Lewinsky that  
at a dinner in March 1998, President Clinton told the lawyer to 
wish his client ``all the best.'' Ms. Lewinsky was elated that 
``the man she had striven so valiantly to protect still cared ... 
It was only about a month later that she discovered that Ginsburg 
had been pulling her leg,'' the book said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no memory of that,'' Ginsburg replied.  
</P>
<P>
	In the moments when Ms. Lewinsky craved privacy, the book said,  
Ginsburg would tip off the media on her whereabouts. 
</P>
<P>
	In April 1998, he invited Ms. Lewinsky to accompany him to  
Philadelphia for an American Bar Association speaking engagement, 
so she could escape her Washington apartment. Ginsburg told her 
they would visit the Liberty Bell. 
</P>
<P>
	Believing they would arrive incognito, Ms. Lewinsky was ``taken  
aback'' to find camera crews, still photographers and reporters 
massed outside their hotel, the book said. One journalist walked up 
and asked when they would be visiting the Liberty Bell. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsburg said he didn't tip off the media, but speculated that  
the bar association did so. 
</P>
<P>
	The book said Ginsburg told Ms. Lewinsky's father, Bernard, that  
he was trying ``to wean her off the limos'' to move around 
Washington -- when, in fact, she usually walked or took a cab when 
she covertly left her apartment in the Watergate complex. 
</P>
<P>
	``The truth emerged only when she noticed her father signing yet  
another large check to Ginsburg, to pay a bill which included 
$5,000 for limos for 'Monica's security,''' the book related. 
</P>
<P>
	Ginsburg said he did order cars with drivers for Ms. Lewinsky's  
safety because ``hordes of reporters were surrounding us,'' along 
with ``paparazzi'' on motorcycles. 
</P>
<P>
	One particular action by Ginsburg led to his firing by the  
Lewinsky family. In ``An Open Letter to Kenneth Starr'' that 
appeared in ``California Lawyer'' magazine, Ginsburg virtually 
admitted that Ms. Lewinsky and the president had sexual relations -- 
although at the time she was standing by her affidavit in the Paula 
Jones case denying an affair. 
</P>
<P>
	The article was designed in part to ``bring the president to  
reality,'' the lawyer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
