<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Goldman Sachs To Vote on IPO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The partners at Goldman Sachs Group LP, the last  
of Wall Street's large private investment banks, will vote next 
week on whether to sell a stake in the firm to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	The firm's 220 partners are to vote on the deal Monday. If  
approved, it would clear the way for a stock sale of 10 to 15 
percent of the firm in May or June. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldman Sachs originally planned to go public last year but  
aborted its attempt in September because turmoil in financial 
markets scared off many investors and ate into Goldman's profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts and investors said Goldman Sachs' IPO last year would  
have valued the firm at about $30 billion. They estimated, however, 
that the IPO would be discounted by as much as 25 percent in 
today's market. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market would not place as high a valuation on Goldman now,  
but it would still provide it with a very handsome valuation 
because of Goldman's pedigree,'' said Michael Flanagan, an 
independent brokerage industry analyst with Financial Service 
Analytics. 
</P>
<P>
	While the stock market has gained 11 percent since Goldman Sachs  
abandoned its plans, the firm's public competitors, such as Merrill 
Lynch &AMP; Co. and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. are still trading 
off their highs. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, Jon S. Corzine stepped down as co-chief executive in  
order to focus on the firm's initial public stock offering, and 
many insiders expect him to leave after the sale is complete. For 
now, Corzine shares the chairman's title with Henry M. Paulson Jr., 
who took over as the sole chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	The two officials issued a joint statement, saying: ``We have  
recommended that the firm become a public company to secure 
permanent capital to grow; to share ownership broadly among our 
employees; and to permit us to use publicly traded securities to 
finance strategic acquisitions that we may elect to make in the 
future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some industry watchers, including Goldman Sach's former  
co-chairman John Whitehead, have expressed concern that the 
130-year-old firm would lose some of its prestige and control by 
becoming a public company. 
</P>
<P>
	But Flanagan bets Goldman will do all that it can to preserve  
its reputation as one of the most desirable places to work on Wall 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been known as an elite, private culture,'' he said, ``and  
I suspect the firm would like to retain elements of that mystique 
to the extent that a public firm can.'' 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 21:23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Monica's Story' Criticizes Tripp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Meddlesome witch. Praying mantis. Delusional.  
Monica Lewinsky and her family spared no venom when describing 
Linda Tripp in Ms. Lewinsky's book, ``Monica's Story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp, a Pentagon employee who surreptitiously taped  
conversations with Lewinsky and turned them over to prosecutors, is 
portrayed as a disgruntled, manipulative and disturbed woman who, 
in an act of revenge, lured her young friend into a trap to 
incriminate President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``She is like a meddlesome witch, a praying mantis,'' says  
Marcia Lewis, Ms. Lewinsky's mother. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp ``sought Monica out, a vulnerable easy target,'' Mrs  
Lewis said. She also calls Mrs. Tripp ``delusional'' and says she 
had ``an obsession with Clinton, at one point claiming that Hillary 
Clinton was jealous of her because she suspected that she was 
having an affair with the president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp had a ``secret addiction: she was trying to live her  
life through Monica, the book says. 
</P>
<P>
	``For some bizarre reason of her own, she was stalking'' Ms.  
Lewinsky, the book says. ``Not physically, but attempting to invade 
her psyche.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In recent interviews, Mrs. Tripp, who worked at the White House  
before being transferred to the Pentagon, has said that she exposed 
the relationship out of concern for Ms. Lewinsky because Clinton 
``abused, used, discarded'' the former intern. 
</P>
<P>
	She has also said that Ms. Lewinsky passed along ``threats''  
from Clinton and concealed information that would hurt the 
president, who was impeached as a result of the affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp began a new job at the Pentagon on Wednesday, keeping  
her previous salary of $94,098 a year. She had been working at home 
since the scandal broke in January 1998, but now will work as a 
public affairs specialist in an office at the Defense Manpower Data 
Center near the Pentagon. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Couter, her spokesman, said Mrs. Tripp had no comment on  
the book. Mrs. Tripp, the Pentagon worker who secretly recorded 
conversations with Ms. Lewinsky about her young co-worker's 
relationship with President Clinton, began a new job Wednesday, 
working as a public affairs specialist in the Defense Manpower Data 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Up to now, Ms. Lewinsky has made few public statements about  
Mrs. Tripp. The book provides the first glimpse of Ms. Lewinsky's 
view of her former friend. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Tripp is likened to Svengali, a character in a 19th century  
novel who, through hypnosis, transforms a talentless young woman 
into a famous vocalist. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like she was brainwashing me,'' Ms. Lewinsky says.  
</P>
<P>
	When she poured out the story of her affair with the president  
in long phone calls with Mrs. Tripp, Ms. Lewinsky thought she was 
confiding in a friend, the books says. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, she was gently being ``lured into a trap, the unwitting  
bait with which to catch the president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The book suggests that Mrs. Tripp was motivated to betray her  
young friend out of revenge against the White House and a deep 
loathing for Ms. Lewinsky, who represented everything Mrs. Tripp 
was not: ``Young, pretty, well-educated, sexually liberated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lewinsky and her family were elated when Maryland  
prosecutors decided to investigate whether Mrs. Tripp had broken 
state law by secretly taping phone conversations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone in our family wants Linda Tripp to lie awake at night  
worrying about going to jail,'' Ms. Lewinsky says in the book. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
