<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> $4 Billion in Foreign Aid Requested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Agency for International Development is  
asking Congress for nearly $4 billion in foreign aid next year, 
with increases in development assistance, child survival programs 
and AIDS prevention. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope to see the day when our foreign assistance budget is  
far greater than it is today,'' said Brian Atwood in appealing to 
the House International Relations Committee for a 1.6 percent 
budget increase. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Atwood's final appearance before the committee after six  
years as AID chief. He is to become ambassador to Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood, who has had to deal with years of declining foreign aid,  
outlined proposals for non-military assistance totaling $2.5 
billion for Asia and the Near East, $818 million for Africa and 
$653 million for Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, AID's budget request for fiscal 2000 is $7.2 billion, a  
$118 million increase over this year. The funding is part of the 
$21.3 billion international affairs budget President Clinton has 
sent to Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Atwood heard complaints from lawmakers ranging from government  
purchase of foreign cars to population policies. 
</P>
<P>
	He promised a report on vehicle purchases by his agency.  
</P>
<P>
	In response to a question by Rep. Chris Smith, R-N.J., Atwood  
said he disagreed with media mogul Ted Turner's proposal for a 
``one-child'' policy for all couples worldwide to help control the 
world's population. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said he appreciated Atwood's answer, because Turner's $1  
billion contribution to the United Nations gives him influence on 
global issues. ``Big Brother shouldn't be telling us we can't have 
brothers and sisters,'' Smith said after the hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite budget cuts in recent years, Atwood said the United  
States remains the world's leading donor nation. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we turn away from the developing world, we invite more  
failed nations, more suffering, more disease, more civil wars and 
terrorism,'' he said. ``We risk exposing ourselves to dangers from 
which all our military might cannot protect us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among major items in AID's proposed budget are:  
</P>
<P>
	--$930 million in non-military support to Israel, a $150 million  
decrease from 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	--$715 million for Egypt, down $60 million.  
</P>
<P>
	--$150 milion for Jordan for water management and other  
non-military programs. 
</P>
<P>
	--$512 million for the African Development Fund, a $59 million  
increase over this year. 
</P>
<P>
	--$457 million to expand private markets, support agriculture and  
set up small-scale credit programs for the rural and urban poor 
</P>
<P>
	--$445 million for child survival programs, including $25 million  
for an initiative to eradicate polio. 
</P>
<P>
	--$400 million for family planning programs worldwide.  
</P>
<P>
	--$290 million to support international efforts to ``reduce the  
threat of global climate change, conserve biological diversity, 
support sound energy services and manage natural resources.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--$220 million for disaster assistance, up $20 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 19:13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eagles Sign Tackle Mark Wheeler </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia Eagles filled a defensive  
need for the first time in NFL free agency, signing tackle Mark 
Wheeler to a four-year contract Wednesday. Terms of the contract 
were not announced. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials hope Wheeler will bolster a defense that allowed an  
average of 4.6 yards per running play in 1998, ranking 27th in the 
NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're really excited,'' said Eagles defensive coordinator Jim  
Johnson, who said Wheeler would compete with Bill Johnson and 
Hollis Thomas for a starting job. ``Looking at free agency, we were 
looking for a guy to bring some toughness as far as a 
run-stopper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wheeler spent four seasons in Tampa Bay and the last three in  
New England. The former Texas A&AMP;M player was a third-round draft 
pick by the Bucs in 1992. He had five sacks and 61 tackles in 16 
starts at nose tackle that year. 
</P>
<P>
	He started 30 games in the next three seasons and 15 games  
during New England's 1996 Super Bowl season, then had four sacks 
and 36 tackles after starting 14 games the following year. Last 
season, he played in only 10 games, suffered a sprained knee, and 
ended with just 26 tackles and no starts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
