<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vero Beach Tries To Keep Dodgers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Vero Beach is trying to avoid joining  
Brooklyn as a former home of the Dodgers. 
</P>
<P>
	The team has trained for the last 50 springs in the small  
eastern Florida city. But now the Dodgers are thinking of switching 
their spring base to Arizona -- unless Vero makes a better offer. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the state's House Tourism Committee approved a  
bill that essentially would allow the Dodgers to stay in their 
spring stadium, but not own it. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill now goes to the state's House Finance and Taxation  
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 20 major league teams that train in Florida, only the  
Dodgers own their facility. The others are owned by a county, city, 
or a combination of both. 
</P>
<P>
	But now the Los Angeles franchise has been offered a $15 million  
complex on the Fort McDowell, Ariz., Mohave-Apache Indian 
Community. That complex, which would include a stadium, practice 
fields, clubhouse and offices, could be ready by 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida bill would authorize the use of a county tourism tax  
-- a tax on hotels and motels -- to go toward acquisition of a 
stadium. Under state law, that money now can be used for stadium 
construction and renovation, but not purchase of an existing 
stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	In essence, Indian River County would buy the stadium from the  
Dodgers, then lease it back to them. 
</P>
<P>
	That could mean a big cut in operating expenses, even for one of  
baseball's richest teams. Rupert Murdoch's Fox Group recently 
purchased the Dodgers from the O'Malley family, which had owned the 
team since 1950 and moved it to the West Coast in 1958. 
</P>
<P>
	But the bill's sponsor, state Rep. Charles Sembler, said he's  
not concerned about the team's economics. He's concerned about the 
city's economics. The Dodgers generate about $30 million annually 
for the community. 
</P>
<P>
	``Indian River County is either retirement or citrus,'' Sembler  
said. ``The only thing that we have is the Vero Beach Dodgers. If 
we were competing for a new team today, there is no way it would 
happen. This is one small portion, but without it, the Dodgers in 
essence will be gone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But another lawmaker says he can't understand why a sports  
franchise owned by a huge corporation needs financial help from a 
city of 17,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	``With them paying the enormous, outrageous salaries, why don't  
we require them to take a few pennies off of each of their salaries 
to fund all of these things they want,'' state Rep. Jerry Melvin 
said. ``They charge so much for the games, the average taxpayer 
can't go to them anyhow.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
