<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong, Disney Discuss Theme Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Hong Kong officials have been in talks with the  
Walt Disney Co. about building a theme park here and expect to 
decide by the end of June on whether to proceed, financial 
secretary Donald Tsang said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Tsang said the talks have involved building a park on outlying  
Lantau Island. He cautioned that much remains to be done to 
conclude the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	A Disney spokesman here confirmed that the company is in  
preliminary talks with the Hong Kong government to ``explore the 
feasibility of locating a theme park destination resort in Hong 
Kong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Disney, based in Burbank, Calif., has theme parks in Florida,  
California, France and Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Tsang confirmed the long-rumored talks with Disney as he  
presented a budget proposal that includes both a tax rebate and a 
deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the budget plan would dip into Hong Kong's cash  
reserves to cover expenses in the coming fiscal year, Tsang 
insisted the territory is ``living within our means.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also proposed merging the stock and futures exchanges and a  
pay freeze for civil servants. 
</P>
<P>
	The budget for the fiscal year that begins April 1 will be 242  
billion Hong Kong dollars, the equivalent of $31 billion, slightly 
lower than this year's estimated expenditures of 245.1 billion Hong 
Kong dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Tsang said in his budget speech that financing next year's  
spending will force the government to reduce its financial reserves 
to 389 billion Hong Kong dollars, or $49.9 billion, by March 2000 
from an estimated 458 billion Hong Kong dollars as of April 1, 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	He predicted Hong Kong's economy can recover later in the year  
and show annual growth of 0.5 percent for 1999, compared with a 
drop of 5.1 percent in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are signs that we have passed the worst of the crisis,''  
he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
