<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GE To Cut 225 Jet Engine Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LYNN, Mass. (AP) -- The General Electric Co. said it will lay off  
200 to 225 jet-engine production workers here this month because it 
failed to win a large contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said about two-thirds of those laid off will be hourly  
workers, and the remainder will be salaried employees. 
</P>
<P>
	The layoffs will reduce the number of workers at the plant to an  
all-time low of about 4,800, said Richard Gorham, a company 
spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is all cost-driven on our production end. No other area  
of our business will be affected,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, United Parcel Services Inc. chose Pratt &AMP; Whitney in  
Connecticut, rather than GE, to produce engines for its cargo 
planes. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract was worth up to $3 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was a significant loss for us,'' said Robert N. Risch, GE's  
government relations manager in New England. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've won our share of contracts to be sure, but when you drop  
a big one, you have to adjust to it,'' he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
