<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 05:47:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Military Pay Boost Concerns Cohen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen is cautioning  
Congress that a military pay-raise bill gaining wide congressional 
support may force cutbacks in other vital Pentagon programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our concern has been: Will Congress pay for it?'' said Defense  
Secretary William Cohen. 
</P>
<P>
	He reminded the Senate Budget Committee on Tuesday that the  
measure, approved overwhelmingly by the Senate on Feb. 25 and now 
before the House, is $7 billion to $11 billion more costly over 
five years than the pay-and-benefit package President Clinton 
proposed for the military in his fiscal 200 budget. 
</P>
<P>
	And Congress has not said where it would find the additional  
money, which represents a 4.8 percent across-the-board military pay 
raise next January and expanded educational and retirement 
benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's not paid for, I then come back with a $7 billion or  
$11 billion hole in the budget, which I then have to take out of 
modernization or operations,'' Cohen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen also said a provision of the bill that would allow GI  
educational benefits to be passed along to other family members 
needs more study. He suggested it could lead to a ``GI Bill without 
the GI.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Currently the GI Bill provides educational benefits for active  
members of the service and veterans. 
</P>
<P>
	``The question would become in the future: Do we then have a  
benefit passed on to that service member's children, who then have 
the benefit but don't have the obligation of actually serving?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate passed the legislation by a 91-8 margin, even though  
the point was made at the time that senators were violating their 
own budget process in voting for new spending without first coming 
up with a way to pay for it. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen's objections are not new. He made roughly the same points  
in a letter to senators when the bill was under debate. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure is now before the House and its Armed Services  
Committee, where the bigger pay raise also has wide support. 
Congressional sponsors of the package said the money somehow will 
be found -- even if it means raising the defense spending cap and 
dipping into the anticipated surplus -- in a way that does not 
require cuts in other defense programs. 
</P>
<P>
	In any event, it seems unlikely that President Clinton would  
veto the more generous pay and benefits package. ``We never want to 
be in a position of saying we're paying our people in the military 
enough. We're not,'' Cohen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's budget would raise salaries of the nation's 1.4  
million active-duty military by 4.4 percent next January, with 3.9 
percent increases in succeeding years. The Senate-passed bill 
starts out with a 4.98 percent raise, then awards further annual 
increases at half a percentage point above the rate of inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the administration and Senate measures would allow service  
members to retire at 50 percent of their salaries after 20 years of 
service, up from the 40 percent level now. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration proposal does not contain a provision for  
transferring GI Bill benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate-passed measure would increase the monthly GI Bill  
educational stipend from $528 to $600, eliminate the $1,200 that 
military members now must pay up front to be eligible, and permit 
unused GI educational benefits to be transferred to other family 
members. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're nervous about the transfer of GI benefits,'' said Deputy  
Defense Secretary John Hamre. ``It represents an IOU against our 
modernization program.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The overall pay-and-benefit package was the first piece of  
legislation to pass the Senate after the end of President Clinton's 
impeachment trial, and it gained overwhelming support even though 
it violated a legal spending cap for Pentagon spending -- and 
supporters gave no indication of how it would be financed. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen told the committee that the administration felt it's own  
package, including the 4.4 percent increase ``would adequately 
address the needs of service men and women.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen also reiterated the administration's request to authorize  
new rounds of base closings, in 2001 and 2005. It would save up to 
$3 billion per year, he testified. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican-led Congress has reacted coolly thus far to the  
request for additional base closings. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, while not addressing the  
base-closing issue directly, complained that the Pentagon was 
wasting billions through inefficiency and poor management 
practices. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a total breakdown in controls. It's so bad the books  
can't be audited,'' Grassley said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
