<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chaos Erupts in Alabama Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- Saying he feared a ``madman,'' an  
Alabama Democrat threatened to call for the National Guard after 
the Republican lieutenant governor reclaimed his powers over the 
state Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowell Barron, the Senate president pro tem, was so furious  
Tuesday that he also threatened to begin impeachment proceedings 
against Lt. Gov. Steve Windom. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have done nothing but create anarchy and chaos,'' Barron  
said. ``We are fearful of giving this power to a madman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The scrum started when Windom, the first Republican elected  
lieutenant governor in Alabama this century, pushed through new 
operating rules on the opening day of the regular session that 
restored much of his power to control the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	He had lost most of those powers in January during an  
organizational session controlled by new Democratic Gov. Don 
Siegelman and his allies. Windom took them back Tuesday with a 
quick voice-vote that set off howling protests. 
</P>
<P>
	The rules, among other things, allow Windom to appoint new  
committees to consider major bills. The rules could be rewritten 
again when the Senate meets today. 
</P>
<P>
	The opening of a regular session is normally a congenial day  
when senators bring their families to visit. Tuesday was anything 
but congenial. 
</P>
<P>
	Kathryn Vetter, a retired school principal visiting from  
Claremore, Okla., described the Senate chamber as a ``war zone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Five-year-old Crystal Smitherman, daughter of Sen. Rodger  
Smitherman, became so frightened by the screaming adults that she 
started crying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
