<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tenn. Sen. Won't Run for President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Sen. Fred Thompson said he will not run  
for president in 2000, saying it would be impractical for three 
Tennessee candidates to be in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican said a lot of people from around the country had  
encouraged him to run. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was surprising to me. (I thought) I should not dismiss this  
out of hand, and I didn't,'' he said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson said he will support former Gov. Lamar Alexander, a  
Tennessee native who is due to announce next week that he will be 
making his second attempt at the Republican nomination. Alexander 
and Thompson are old friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore, also from Tennessee, is seeking the  
Democratic nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson was elected to the Senate in 1994 to fill the remaining  
two years of Gore's term. He was re-elected in 1996 to a full 
six-year term. 
</P>
<P>
	Now chairman of the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee, he  
was minority counsel for the Senate Watergate Committee in the 
early 1970s and later became an actor, appearing in movies such as 
``The Hunt for Red October'' and ``In the Line of Fire.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
