<DOCNO> APW19990303.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 14:35:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Proposed Banking Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Highlights of legislation proposed by Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas,  
chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, to overhaul the financial 
services laws. President Clinton has threatened to veto the 
proposal. 

</P>
<P>
	--Lifts the Depression-era barriers between banks, brokerage  
firms and insurance companies, allowing them to merge and get more 
deeply into each other's businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Calls for most new financial activities to be conducted by  
affiliated companies within bank holding companies, rather than 
operating subsidiaries of banks. 
</P>
<P>
	--Exempts banks from having to get a satisfactory  
community-lending rating from the government in order to set up 
holding companies to conduct new financial activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
