<DOCNO> APW19990303.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 06:02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Launches Troop Buildup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMBON, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia launched a major troop buildup  
today in a riot-torn provincial capital, and soldiers fired warning 
shots to prevent Christians and Muslims from clashing. 
</P>
<P>
	Troops fired in the air in front of a church in coastal Ambon  
and blocked hundreds of Muslim refugees, some carrying knives, who 
tried to approach Christians protesters from a nearby mosque. 
</P>
<P>
	In the nation's capital, Jakarta, about 2,000 Islamic students  
gathered outside military headquarters and accused soldiers of 
supporting Christian rioters. They chanted ``holy war'' and ``God 
is great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, military chief Gen. Wiranto dismissed the police  
chief in charge of Ambon, where religious clashes have claimed at 
least 38 lives in the past week. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 150 people have been slain since the violence erupted  
in January in Maluku province, once known as the Spice Islands. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest unrest in Ambon, Maluku's capital, broke out after a  
Christian refugee was stabbed at a church. Angry Christian men then 
tried to stop a car believed to be owned by Muslims. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, five people were killed when Christians attacked  
worshippers at a mosque near Ambon, 1,400 miles east of Jakarta. 
The military denied its officers shot four Muslims and refuted 
allegations that it had taken sides in the fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of houses have been burned and tens of thousands of  
people have fled their homes in the Ambon rioting. Rival mobs have 
fought with swords, bows and arrows and gasoline bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1,400 troop reinforcements arrived in Ambon, on Tuesday  
and today. Their numbers bolstered hundreds of police and soldiers 
already in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiranto, who like many Indonesians uses only one name, pledged  
that hundreds more soldiers would be sent to Ambon in the next few 
days and said they had orders to shoot troublemakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I ordered the troops to shoot at their feet so as to paralyze  
them, but not kill them,'' Wiranto said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of houses have been burned, and tens of thousands of  
people have fled their homes in the rioting. 
</P>
<P>
	In Jakarta, the students condemned the military's handling of  
the violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``The soldiers are involved. They are taking sides,'' said one  
protester, who identified himself as Reza. 
</P>
<P>
	About 90 percent of Indonesia's 210 million people are Muslim,  
making it the world's most populous Islamic state. Much of Ambon's 
population, however, is Christian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
