<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong, Disney Discuss Theme Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- When Walt Disney Co. Chairman Michael Eisner  
visited China last fall, he was impressed by the large number of 
McDonald's restaurants. He would later tell shareholders, he felt 
``completely sure'' the Chinese people ``love Mickey no less than 
Big Mac.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Mickey appears to be a step closer to entering China in a  
major way. Hong Kong and Disney officials said Wednesday they have 
been in talks about building a theme park in the former British 
colony, possibly on an outlying island where the new airport is 
located. A decision is expected by June. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney, which already has parks in the United States, France and  
Japan, including Tokyo DisneySea opening in 2001, could benefit 
from a Hong Kong theme park to ``gain a foothold in the region'' to 
build business for everything from movies to consumer products, 
said James Zoltak, West Coast Editor of Amusement Business 
magazine, a trade publication. 
</P>
<P>
	``Disney obviously doesn't want to just go in and make a splash  
in the Hong Kong market,'' said Zoltak. ``It's looking at China and 
the giant population. It's looking at Southeast Asia. .... It is an 
emerging economy. It has a lot of potential. The time to get in is 
before it booms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Countries throughout Asia are reeling from an economic crisis.  
Hong Kong is sunk in a recession with high unemployment, a sharp 
drop in tourism and a weak real estate market. 
</P>
<P>
	Local boosters believe a Disney park could help change all that,  
and support for the park runs deep. Rumors of the theme park talks 
have sent up the price of stocks in tourism-sensitive businesses 
such as Cathay Pacific and Kowloon Motor Bus Co. 
</P>
<P>
	It was only a couple of years ago that Disney was under attack  
from China over the Martin Scorsese film ``Kundun,'' which was 
critical of China's Tibet policies. But relations have thawed since 
then, with Eisner visiting the country last fall. In June, Disney 
named veteran executive John Feenie to oversee the entertainment 
and media company's expanding ventures in China. 
</P>
<P>
	``China is a nation of enormous opportunity for our company,''  
Eisner said at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong financial secretary Donald Tsang confirmed the theme  
park talks in his annual budget address. He said the discussions 
have involved building a park on Lantau Island, where the new 
international airport was built. He cautioned that much remains to 
be done to conclude the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials declined to discuss the size of a possible park or how  
it would be financed and operated. For the new park in Tokyo, for 
instance, Disney licenses its names and characters acts as a 
consultant on the park's construction and operation. The park will 
be fully owned and operated by Oriental Land Co. which also owns 
and operates Tokyo Disneyland. 
</P>
<P>
	In Burbank, Calif., Disney spokesman John Dreyer said Wednesday  
the talks with Hong Kong are in a ``very preliminary stage'' but 
noted: ``There's tremendous long-term potential in Asia and in 
China and we're exploring expanding all of our businesses in 
China.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The process of building a theme park takes some time,'' added  
Dreyer. ``We prefer to build in a downturn and come in on an 
upturn.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The theme park business is far from a sure bet in China and  
efforts to build parks on the mainland have largely stumbled in the 
last couple of years. Investors have misjudged customer projections 
and the challenges of dealing with the Chinese bureaucracy. 
</P>
<P>
	But Zoltak of Amusement Business said Hong Kong is ``a  
completely different animal. It's a modern city and incomes are 
higher.'' Also, Hong Kong draws tourists from throughout southeast 
Asia, as well as North America and Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's probably a good place to do this,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Since opening the original Disneyland in Anaheim, Calif., in  
1955, Disney has expanded to Tokyo, France, and Florida, where it 
as four parks in the Orlando area. It is adding a second park in 
Anaheim and is considering adding a small park in France. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 09:16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hino Motors Cuts Administrators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese truckmaker Hino Motors Ltd. will reduce  
its administrative staff by 10 percent, or 400 jobs, this year by 
asking employees to volunteer for early retirement, the company 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hino, an affiliate of Toyota Motor Co., is expected to suffer a  
huge loss for the fiscal year ending in March because truck sales 
have fallen sharply since Japan sank into recession last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Hino would likely fire some workers to reach the target if too  
few volunteer for early retirement, the Nihon Keizai newspaper 
reported, citing Hino President Hiroshi Yuasa. 
</P>
<P>
	A company spokesman refused to comment on the report.  
</P>
<P>
	Firing workers is still extremely rare at big companies in  
Japan. Most companies choose instead to trim work forces by 
freezing new hiring, or finding jobs for workers in affiliated 
firms. 
</P>
<P>
	Hino, which has 9,600 employees, will likely post a net loss of  
about 30 billion yen ($248 million) for the year ending March 31, 
the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's most recent forecast was for a net loss of 9.2  
billion yen ($76 million). 
</P>
<P>
	Hino hasn't announced a revision to its forecast for earnings  
but planned to make such an announcement in mid-March, said the 
spokesman, who declined to give his name. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 18:12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hair Test May Reveal Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Australian researchers say they have developed a test for breast  
cancer that can be done be analyzing a single pubic hair. 
</P>
<P>
	Radiologists at the University of New South Wales in Sydney  
found that microscopic characteristics in the hair may reveal 
whether a woman has breast cancer. They also believe that the hair 
may indicate whether a woman is carrying a certain gene mutation 
that raises the risk of later developing the disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Pubic hair was found to be easier to read than scalp hair  
because it it less likely to be damaged by perms, dyes or the sun. 
</P>
<P>
	Other scientists, however, said the study is too small to be  
conclusive. And they questioned whether the method is an 
improvement over existing tests -- mammograms for finding cancer, 
blood tests for identifying genetic risks. 
</P>
<P>
	The test is not approved for clinical use.  
</P>
<P>
	The study was reported Thursday in the journal Nature.  
</P>
<P>
	One of the Australian researchers, radiologist Veronica James,  
said the hair test could help women living in poor, remote areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Samples for this test could be posted from anywhere in the  
world in an envelope,'' Ms. James said. ``In many poorer countries, 
no mammography is available.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the study, researchers used sensitive X-ray equipment to  
analyze the scalp hair of 23 women who earlier had been diagnosed 
with breast cancer, and found their hair contained one or more 
extra rings in the keratin, or protein layer. Of 28 women who were 
known to be cancer-free, all but four did not have the extra rings. 
</P>
<P>
	The same pattern was found in 12 women whose pubic hair was  
analyzed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can look at the patterns we are getting from our hair  
samples and know that the diseased ones are different from the 
normal ones because they have changed in structure,'' Ms. James 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Five women in the study had not been diagnosed with breast  
cancer, but earlier tests found they carried a mutation of the 
BRCA-1 gene associated with an inherited form of the disease. Hair 
from all five patients contained full or partial extra rings 
similar to those seen in the breast cancer patients. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. James said the results suggest that a woman's hair could  
indicate the presence of the BRCA-1 mutation even before cancer is 
detected. 
</P>
<P>
	During the research, the scientists realized that a lifetime of  
chemicals and sun had damaged the molecular structure of the 
women's hair. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their scalp hair was useless until it grew out again three  
months later,'' Ms. James said. ``So with a lot of fun and 
laughter, the women disappeared behind a curtain with scissors and 
envelopes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Savitz, chairman of epidemiology at the University of  
North Carolina, said pubic hair is a more reliable biological 
sample than scalp hair; he has used it to determine people's 
history of cocaine use. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Australian study was too small and its results must be  
repeated in larger studies, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Savitz said he also questions widespread screening for the rare  
BRCA-1 form of the disease -- which accounts for as few as three in 
211 breast cancer cases, according to one 1998 study -- especially 
when there is no ``useful'' way to prevent it. 
</P>
<P>
	Women who have the defective genes sometimes choose drastic  
options, such as having their breasts removed while they are still 
healthy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
