<DOCNO> APW19990303.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 12:26:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Jury Gets Cable Car Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- Jurors today began weighing the fate  
of a Marine pilot charged with involuntary manslaughter for flying 
his jet into an Italian ski lift cable, killing 20 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The eight Marine officers closeted themselves shortly after 2  
p.m. following summations by prosecutors and defense lawyers that 
lasted nearly four hours. 
</P>
<P>
	In his statement, prosecutor Maj. Daniel Daugherty described  
Capt. Richard Ashby as ``outright dangerous,'' but Ashby's lawyer 
countered that it was an accident ``and nothing more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When he violated all these things and didn't know local rules  
and regulations, people died and a $60 million aircraft is in 
ruins,'' Daugherty said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason the accused is guilty ... is he was too low, he was  
too fast, he was too aggressive. He was outright dangerous,'' 
Daugherty said. 
</P>
<P>
	In his closing statement, defense attorney Frank Spinner posed  
the question of whether the tragedy was ``a training accident or 
was it something more?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a training accident and nothing more,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Testimony in Ashby's manslaughter trial began Feb. 8 and ended  
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby, 31, of Mission Viejo, Calif., was at the controls of an  
EA-6B Prowler jet on Feb. 3, 1998, when it struck the Mount Cermis 
gondola cable near Cavalese, Italy. He is charged with involuntary 
manslaughter and other counts and could get 206 years in prison if 
convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	In his summation, Daugherty said the safe conduct of the flight  
depended on Ashby's decisions, but he made bad choices -- flying the 
jet above the 517 mph restriction for the low-level training 
mission, and far below the 2,000-foot altitude limit. Ashby's jet 
hit the cable 370 feet above the valley floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Daugherty argued that Ashby should have known he was flying too  
low and too fast by merely looking around. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have the roads, the cars, the houses, the humanity of it  
all. Captain Ashby ignores it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Spinner said a number of factors converged as Ashby flew the jet  
down the alpine valley -- the ground rose 150 feet, the altimeter 
malfunctioned and an optical illusion made Ashby believe he was 
flying higher than he really was. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't avoid what you can't see,'' he said. ``This was a  
trap. This was an accident waiting to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby testified earlier he didn't know about the mission's speed  
limit and thought the altitude restriction was 1,000 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Daugherty said that to hide evidence of their recklessness it  
appeared Ashby and his navigator, Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, 
destroyed a videotape on which Schweitzer had filmed the early 
portions of the flight. The tape has never been located. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby testified earlier that he took the tape to his quarters,  
where Schweitzer picked it up. Ashby never saw it again, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The simple conclusion you can draw is that tape and video  
camera had nothing to do with the accident,'' Spinner told jurors 
today. ``It was a private tape; it wasn't a government tape.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides agree the gondola cable wasn't marked on the map  
Ashby was issued by the Air Force. Ashby testified last week that 
he didn't know of the ski lift and that he didn't see the cable 
until the last second. 
</P>
<P>
	``Negligence is knowing the cable is there and flying as if it  
is not. ... Negligence is not the occurrence of normal deviations 
in flight,'' Spinner said. ``It would have been negligence if that 
aerial cableway was on their map and they ignored it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During a brief recess after closing arguments, Vera Eyskens,  
whose daughter Rose Marie Eyskens of Kalmthout, Belgium, died in 
the accident, embraced Daugherty. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened on the final leg of a 42-minute training  
route through the Italian Alps. Europeans were outraged, and 
Italians demanded that U.S. landing rights be revoked at bases in 
their country. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't recall in 20 years of investigating accidents any  
pilot being held criminally responsible for an accident,'' said 
Jeff Edwards, an investigator who worked for the defense team. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers have suggested the aviators were charged because  
of political pressure that went as high as the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer, 31, faces similar charges and a separate  
court-martial. Charges against the other two crewmen were 
dismissed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 12:26:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
