<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Imports of Wine Double </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Move over, sake. The Japanese, encouraged by  
affordable foreign brands and reports of health benefits, are 
guzzling imported wine in record amounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Wine imports more than doubled in 1998 to reach all-time highs  
both in terms of volume, 88.5 million gallons, and value, $1.4 
billion, the Tokyo Customs Office says. 
</P>
<P>
	France was the top exporter, with 29.1 million gallons, for a  
32.9 percent market share. Next were Italy, with 14.7 percent and 
Chile with 9.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States was fourth, with 6.6 million gallons for a  
market share of 7.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Wine sales have been climbing steadily since 1994, but a real  
boost came in late 1997 with reports that wine, particularly red, 
could play a role in preventing hardening of the arteries. 
</P>
<P>
	Red wine-producing countries have benefited. Imports of French  
wine more than tripled between 1994 and 1998, and sales of Chilean 
wine, among the most affordable of foreign brands, jumped by nearly 
17 times. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese still have a way to go, however, before matching  
the wine-drinking habits of the West. 
</P>
<P>
	Per capita consumption is around a half gallon a year in Japan --  
compared to 16.4 gallons in France, 15.6 gallons in Italy and 1.8 
gallons in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
