<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Weapons Monitors Urged for Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal research laboratories have been asked  
to speed up development of more sophisticated systems for detecting 
chemical and biological agents, so they can be in place during the 
next Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've challenged our national laboratories to complete this  
important system by 2002 -- in time to make it available for use at 
the Olympics in Salt Lake City,'' Energy Secretary Bill Richardson 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson said the rapid detection of a release of chemical or  
biological agents by terrorists ``could turn a medical nightmare 
into a manageable problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech to the National Press Club, Richardson said he was  
confident researchers at the federal labs will be able to develop 
within three years biological agent detectors ``small enough to fit 
into the hand of a fireman or a cop that tells within seconds if a 
chem-bio agent is present.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Currently such detection equipment normally fills a room in a  
laboratory and often takes days to fully analyze the agent. 
Researchers have developed an instrument the size of a suitcase 
that can analyze a biological agent within hours. 
</P>
<P>
	But Richardson said more research on even smaller equipment and  
faster analysis is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he wants the labs to ``demonstrate and deliver the first  
phase of a biological detection system -- an integrated network of 
sensors and analytical software in time for use at the next Winter 
Olympics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Rogue countries, terrorists and the suppliers of the nuclear,  
biological and chemical tools of their trade are using increasingly 
sophisticated means to evade detection,'' he warned. ``Our methods 
and technology must outpace this growing threat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson said he also had directed the labs to expand  
cooperation in nuclear proliferation detection efforts. He 
announced creation of a Nuclear Proliferation Data Exploitation 
Center through which experts would share information on nuclear 
proliferation and make it available to U.S. intelligence agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration asked Congress for $32 million for the next  
fiscal year, an increase of nearly 70 percent, for chemical and 
biological defense programs, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
