<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Athletics' Stairs Has New Physique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Once stocky, Matt Stairs has shed about 25 pounds  
of fat on an all-protein diet and a rigorous workout schedule. The 
reason for this offseason burst of activity is simple: He plans to 
go 20-20 this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Getting 20 homers and 20 stolen bases are two reasons the  
Oakland Athletics outfielder put himself at the mercy of team 
strength coach Bob Alejo this winter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I worked out hard,'' Stairs said. ``Bob put me on a strict  
protein diet, we did a lot of cardiovascular every day for about 45 
minutes, then weight training for another two hours.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stairs, 31, is still following the routine. As proof, he held  
out a cup of foamy brown goo: a protein shake. He also eats 12 to 
14 eggs a day and about five or six chicken breasts or steaks. 
</P>
<P>
	A while back, he was still able to eat bread before noon. No  
more. 
</P>
<P>
	``I used to like going to Burger King,'' he said, shaking his  
head. ``Now I go to Burger King and get four BK Broilers and throw 
the bread away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In all, Stairs has lost about 25 pounds of fat and has added  
muscle, for about 9 pounds of total weight loss. He lost four 
inches from his midsection alone, prompting him to joke that he can 
now see his stomach muscles. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't think I had those,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	At 5-foot-9, Stairs is now down to 206, less than he has weighed  
for most of this decade, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, Stairs hit 26 home runs and stole eight bases in 11  
attempts. But he was hampered by an inflamed Achilles tendon that 
kept him mostly in a designated hitter role. He had surgery to 
correct the problem during the offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second straight season the Canadian-born Stairs had  
more than 25 homers; in 1997, he had 27. 
</P>
<P>
	So the A's already know he can hit. They're betting the leaner  
and more determined Stairs will reach his steals goal, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``Matt runs better than most people give him credit for, and I  
know he worked out religiously in the offseason,'' manager Art Howe 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to going 20-20, Stairs said he'd like to drive in  
100 runs and score 100 runs. And he'd like to spend more time in 
the outfield, which is where his newfound stamina comes in. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I wanted to get to the point where I could play 120  
games in the outfield,'' he said. ``That's what we're shooting for: 
120 games. I figured the best way to do it was to get into top 
shape and go from there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When he wasn't working out, Stairs was doing what all good  
Canadians do in the winter -- watching hockey. Stairs, who now lives 
in Oakland, has season tickets to San Jose Sharks games. 
</P>
<P>
	He said being a fan was a pleasant break from his workout  
schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, Stairs originally wanted to play hockey, but it wasn't  
in the cards, especially after he made the Canadian Olympic 
baseball team that went to Seoul in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried out (for hockey),'' he said, letting his Canadian  
accident slip. ``But I suffered a bad knee injury and that was it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't decide to play baseball, really. I guess it was  
politics back then, they needed somebody from the East Coast to 
play on the Olympic team and I made it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
