<HEADLINE> Wisc.-Milwaukee Hoops Coach Fired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Ric Cobb was fired Wednesday as coach of the  
Wisconsin-Milwaukee men's basketball team after failing to post a 
winning season in four years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Men's basketball is our flagship sport,'' athletic director  
Bud Haidet said. ``It's imperative to the overall athletic program 
that our men's basketball team be successful. I feel a change in 
the coaching staff is needed to accomplish our goals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Haidet said a search for Cobb's replacement was under way and he  
hoped to have a replacement as early as April 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb, whose coaching contract expires at month's end, was  
reassigned to director of community outreach, a new job in the 
athletic department. 
</P>
<P>
	``To be honest, I really don't know what the reassignment is. I  
mean, this was all done in a five-minute period,'' Cobb said by 
phone from his home. ``They brought me in and told me I'd been 
reassigned and the athletic director told me how much he liked me 
and they went through the reassignment papers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a done deal when I went in the meeting. I didn't have a  
say-so in anything,'' Cobb said. ``So, I don't know what I'm going 
to do at this stage. I'm still working at UWM, and I'll look at 
some options if anything comes up. I don't know if I want to stay 
in coaching or not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb, who was 28-81 in four seasons, said his successor will  
reap the benefits of a slowly revitalized program that is poised to 
succeed under juniors-to-be Chad Angeli, Damion Ninkovic and Jared 
Hardwick. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great situation for somebody coming behind me because  
this team should be the MCC champions next year,'' Cobb said. ``I 
felt the team was turning the corner. ... It's a shame I won't be 
there to lead them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Panthers finished 8-19 this season after losing to  
Wisconsin-Green Bay in the Midwestern Collegiate Conference 
tournament, in which Cobb's teams went 0-4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
