<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 06:05:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Tackle Major Antitrust Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- During the 1980s, a declawed Federal Trade  
Commission would have been unlikely to take on a high-profile 
antitrust case against one of the world's biggest technology 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	But in just a week, the commission will face off against Intel  
Corp. in the other major computer-courtroom drama unfolding in 
Washington -- bringing it out from behind the shadow of its sister 
federal antitrust agency, the Justice Department, and its case 
against Microsoft Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The high-stakes Intel case is indicative of the changing tide at  
the commission, which almost doubled its antitrust enforcement 
actions from 1997 to 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	With an aggressive leadership and buoyed by some large  
victories, the commission in recent years has vigorously exercised 
the authority given it by the 1976 Hart-Scott-Rodino Antitrust 
Improvements Act. 
</P>
<P>
	``The principal reason is not our doing but the world's doing,''  
said Robert Pitofsky, the commission's chairman. ``The behavior by 
some firms really raises antitrust questions more frequently.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, a wave of mergers has swept the nation in the past few  
years. More than $1 trillion in mergers occurred in fiscal year 
1998, and nearly 4,800 requests were filed by companies to have 
merger proposals reviewed by antitrust agencies as required by law. 
That is a 28 percent increase from previous years' filings. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, many believe the FTC has been newly aggressive in  
using its antitrust power and in grabbing headlines from Justice, 
harkening back to the 1960s, when it argued many antitrust cases 
before the Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Intel case was probably filed in part to say, `Hey, look  
at us! We're here, too, and we can enforce the same laws,''' said 
Bill Shughart, a University of Mississippi economics professor. 
Shughart, who worked at the FTC in the late 1970s and early 1980s, 
said he couldn't imagine the commission at that time bringing a 
similar complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission alleges that Intel illegally withheld from three  
companies technical information about its new generation of 
computer chips to ``extort'' valuable technology that the companies 
developed independently. Intel, based in Santa Clara, Calif., makes 
chips that run 80 percent of world's computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts attribute a good part of the agency's new gusto to  
Pitofsky, a lawyer sworn in as commissioner in 1995. In 1994, 
Pitofsky chaired a Pentagon advisory panel to address whether the 
defense industry should be granted antitrust exemptions as it 
downsized in the post-Cold War era. The task force recommended 
against it. 
</P>
<P>
	The chairman is the first to admit that mergers are not  
intrinsically harmful but rather the inevitable consequence of 
economic globalization, deregulation and an increase in the 
importance of high-tech industries. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's probably a sensible response to some changes that  
are going on,'' Pitofsky said. ``But independent deals can be very 
much of a threat to consumer welfare.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the FTC and Justice both embroiled in big computer cases,  
the fine line that distinguishes the two agencies seems a bit 
blurred. 
</P>
<P>
	``Generally there has been a gentleman's agreement between the  
two agencies not to compete to file lawsuits against the same firms 
at the same time,'' said Shughart. An agency might opt for a case 
based on workload or prior expertise: Airline mergers tend to end 
up at Justice, gasoline companies at the FTC. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies with mergers of a certain size must inform both  
agencies. Historically, the assistant attorney general of the 
antitrust division -- currently Joel Klein -- and the FTC chairman 
chat by phone to determine jurisdiction. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC has handled probably two-thirds of all mergers, because  
it has broader jurisdiction on civil matters, said Robert Burka, a 
private antitrust expert. In contrast, Justice can bring criminal 
cases and the FTC can't. 
</P>
<P>
	After its period of vigilant regulation in the 1960s, the FTC in  
the late 1970s moved away from traditional antitrust cases and 
focused instead on trying to stop states from using legislation to 
create monopolies, said Don Boudreaux, president of the Foundation 
for Economic Education in Irvington, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	But by the early 1990s, the commission started to accelerate its  
activity in mergers and predatory pricing, producing a string of 
successes: 
</P>
<P>
	--Staples and Office Depot in July of 1997 called off their $3.5  
billion merger after the commission got a court injunction arguing 
the deal would reduce competition and lead to higher prices. 
</P>
<P>
	--Rite Aid Corp. dropped a $1.8 billion deal with Revco in 1996  
after the FTC said Rite Aid would gain too much of the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitofsky concedes some deals can create efficiencies that could  
benefit consumers. He cites the alliance between Chrysler Corp. and 
Germany's Daimler-Benz AG, approved in July. 
</P>
<P>
	``We became fairly persuaded there were true efficiencies in  
putting together the two companies,'' Pitofsky said. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 06:45:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tennessee Sen. Not Running for President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Sen. Fred Thompson says he will not run  
for president in 2000 and will support his fellow Tennessean, 
former Gov. Lamar Alexander, in the race for the Republican 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson said yesterday that his Senate workload will preclude a  
run for the White House and he thinks it would be impractical for 
three men from Tennessee to be in the race. Vice President Al Gore 
is expected to seek the Democratic nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander plans to formally announce his candidacy Tuesday in  
Nashville and Thompson said that encouraged him to rule out his own 
race now. He said he supports Alexander because ``he has a basic 
conservative message, but he's moderate in temperament.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had ``never been on the verge'' of running for  
president despite media speculation. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it hadn't been for his announcement coming up, I'd probably  
just kind of let it die a natural death,'' Thompson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson was elected to the Senate in 1994 to fill the remaining  
two years of Gore's seat after Gore was elected vice president. He 
was elected in 1996 to a full six-year term. 
</P>
<P>
	He was minority counsel for the Senate Watergate Committee in  
the 1970s, and later became an actor in movies such as ``The Hunt 
for Red October'' and ``In the Line of Fire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson said he was surprised when ``a lot of people ... from  
various parts of the country'' had encouraged him to run, adding he 
thought ``I should not dismiss this out of hand, and I didn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now these are uncertain times. People may be more in the  
mood for caretaker government than any bold initiatives right now 
for a while.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
