<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Seeks Funds for Embassy Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department wants to spend close to  
$300 million next year to improve security at American embassies 
around the world. Some Republicans on Capitol Hill say that's not 
enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``The department's inability or refusal to accelerate  
construction of safer embassies leaves us vulnerable to additional 
attacks from terrorists interested in making political 
statements,'' Rep. Chris Smith, R-N.J., said at a hearing Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Undersecretary of State Bonnie R. Cohen, who oversees management  
issues, acknowledged that 80 percent of U.S. embassies have been 
built too close to the street ``and are in need of substantial 
security improvement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The state of disrepair of many of our buildings overseas is  
shocking,'' Cohen said at a hearing of the House International 
Relations subcommittee overseeing operations. 
</P>
<P>
	She cited problems at the U.S. Embassy in Beijing, where she  
said sewer gas leaks through the building. She pointed out that 
non-Americans also are endangered by inadequate conditions, noting 
that most of the 250 people killed and 5,500 wounded in the U.S. 
embassy bombing in Nairobi were Kenyans. 
</P>
<P>
	That bombing and another one in Tanzania at the same time last  
August prompted the stepped-up concern for embassy security. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's concerns followed similar objections to the  
administration approach by Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., last month, who 
said the administration should be spending about $700 million more, 
for a total of $1 billion next year increasing embassy security. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith suggested more aggressive pursuit of a $3 billion plan to  
step up protection over the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Frankly,'' said Smith, ``I am concerned that the cost of this  
delay could be measured in the lives of Americans and other 
innocent people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He challenged the administration to come up with a revised plan  
for protecting 122 diplomatic missions and said he would help see 
that actions are fully funded. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, testifying at a Senate  
hearing last month, said every embassy is under threat. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen's testimony Tuesday included a summary of steps taken to  
improve the safety of embassies since the bombings, including: 
</P>
<P>
	-- Deployment of 120 diplomatic security agents on temporary duty  
at various posts. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Increase of local guards by over 1,000 worldwide.  
</P>
<P>
	-- Changes in traffic patterns around embassies in several  
cities. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Construction of barriers, the increased use of video cameras  
and other physical protections at several embassies. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Land acquisition to provide increased protective space for  
five posts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
