<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Duke's Battier Plans To Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- No. 1 Duke's chances of winning the  
Atlantic Coast Conference tournament already looked pretty good. 
They got even better Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Shane Battier, whose severely sprained left ankle kept him out  
of the Blue Devils' regular-season finale, went through a one-hour 
practice at full speed Wednesday night and reported no problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Barring any overnight complications from pain or swelling,  
Battier said he expected to be on the floor Thursday night when the 
Blue Devils (29-1) meet Virginia (14-15) in a first-round game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's safe to say I'll play,'' Battier said.  
</P>
<P>
	Coach Mike Krzyzewski wasn't ready to pronounce Battier  
completely recovered but said he was impressed with how the 
sophomore forward looked in the spirited workout at the Charlotte 
Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was very encouraging,'' Krzyzewski said.  
</P>
<P>
	The coach said he would not start Battier but would use him  
according to feel. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he's feeling good and I'm feeling good,'' Krzyzewski said,  
``he'll play a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Battier said he had planned to practice on a limited basis  
Wednesday night, but the ankle felt so good early in the session 
that he decided to keep testing it. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time the session ended, Battier had worked up a good  
sweat by taking part in all the team drills. He dunked several 
times, hit a number of 3-pointers, set some picks, made some solid 
plays on defense and ran the floor well, looking all the while like 
he wasn't bothered by the high ankle sprain. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, Battier appeared much more at ease than Krzyzewski, who  
is scheduled for hip replacement surgery as soon as the season 
ends. Krzyzewski limped around the practice floor and alternately 
leaned on the scorer's table or sat on the Duke bench to rest the 
sore hip. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just can't move around well,'' he said, breaking into a wide  
smile. ``But it doesn't hurt my thinking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Battier put an ice bag on his ankle after practice, a move he  
called nothing more than standard procedure. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was really kind of surprised at how good it felt,'' he said.  
``As the practice went along, I decided to do more and more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's good news for a team that just completed an unprecedented  
16-0 run through the ACC and has won 24 games in a row. Battier is 
one of the nation's best defenders, as evidenced by his 
team-leading 30 charges taken and 53 blocks, second only to center 
Elton Brand's 71. 
</P>
<P>
	Without Battier, the Blue Devils closed the regular season with  
a 20-point victory over North Carolina last Saturday. Battier's 
replacement, freshman Corey Maggette, had 14 points and 11 
rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Guys on this team are real competitive,'' point guard William  
Avery said. ``Shane's probably looking at it like he can't let this 
guy come in and take his job.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
