<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Entertainment highlights during the week of March 7-13:  
</P>
<P>
	55 years ago: ``The Purple Heart'' starred Dana Andrews, Farley  
Granger and Richard Conte. 
</P>
<P>
	45 years ago: John Huston's ``Beat the Devil'' starred Humphrey  
Bogart, Robert Morley, Peter Lorre and Jennifer Jones. The film 
became a cult favorite. 
</P>
<P>
	40 years ago: The Harvard Lampoon voted Kirk Douglas ``worst  
actor'' for the film, ``The Vikings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Egypt banned Elizabeth Taylor's films because she helped  
raise money for Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	35 years ago: Richard Burton and Peter O'Toole starred in  
``Becket.'' 
</P>
<P>
	30 years ago: The Beatles held the top two places on the U.S.  
album chart with ``The Beatles'' and the soundtrack album to the 
animated feature film, ``Yellow Submarine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And ``Mrs. Robinson'' by Simon &AMP; Garfunkel won two Grammy  
Awards, including Record of the Year. 
</P>
<P>
	25 years ago: John Denver sang about fresh air and Rocky  
Mountain highs on his ABC special. 
</P>
<P>
	And Bad Company performed its first concert in England. The band  
was made up of former members of Free, King Crimson and Mott the 
Hoople. 
</P>
<P>
	20 years ago: Jack Lemmon, Jane Fonda and Michael Douglas  
starred in ``The China Syndrome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	15 years ago: Daryl Hannah and Tom Hanks starred in ``Splash.''  
The film was directed by Ron Howard. 
</P>
<P>
	10 years ago: Longtime James Bond actor Roger Moore gave up the  
lead role in a new Andrew Lloyd Webber musical, saying he couldn't 
sing well enough. Moore had been rehearsing ``Aspects of Love'' in 
London. 
</P>
<P>
	And comedian Bill Cosby dominated the People's Choice Awards for  
the fifth straight year. Cosby was voted favorite male TV performer 
and favorite all-around male star. His NBC series won favorite 
comedy in the 15th annual entertainment popularity contest 
conducted by a nationwide poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago: The Nashville Songwriters Association  
International gave Clint Black a special Pegasus award for his 
contributions to the organization. Black had raised more than 
$60,000 for the songwriters' group with concerts in Nashville, 
Tenn. 
</P>
<P>
	And Jon Secada, Gloria Estefan and Miguel Morejon won the Latin  
Song of the Year award for ``Just Another Day Without You'' at the 
first BMI Latin Music Awards. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken 10 years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``Unless you can get the performances on the screen, all else  
will ultimately fail.'' -- Barry Levinson, who praised ``Rain Man'' 
stars Dustin Hoffman and Tom Cruise after being named best director 
of a feature film for 1988 by the Directors Guild of America. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken five years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``He lived music, ate music, breathed music.'' -- Billy Joel,  
referring to Beethoven, his favorite composer. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken one year ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``This is one of the proudest moments of my life. It's  
tremendous.'' -- ``Titanic'' director James Cameron, winner of the 
Directors Guild of America award for best director. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
