<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stocks rose Wednesday on positive  
local news, with the big Tokyo market soaring on lower interest 
rates and a weaker Japanese yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose  
249.30 points, or 1.79 percent, to close at 14,170.36. On Tuesday, 
the average had lost 300.69 points, or 2.11 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	On the currency market, the U.S. dollar jumped to 121.18 yen in  
late trading, up 1.10 yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and higher 
than its late New York level of 120.23 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks rose after the central bank drove Japan's already  
super-low short-term interest rates to nearly zero by flooding the 
interbank loan market with cash. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors who had worried that a recent rise in interest rates  
would erode corporate profits by raising borrowing costs welcomed 
the lower rates, while the weakening yen boosted exporter stocks. 
Japanese products are more competitive abroad when the yen falls. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, shares ended slightly higher, after seesawing  
through the afternoon session as Financial Secretary Donald Tsang 
announced a new budget that analysts said contains little good 
news. 
</P>
<P>
	Confirmation that the territory is in serious talks with Walt  
Disney Co. on building a theme park here gave the market a slight 
boost, but the lack of new measures to stimulate the property 
market quickly dampened any enthusiasm. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index ended up 8.82 points, or 0.09  
percent, at 9,922.40. The index had slumped 106.88 points Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors have been disappointed with the budget so far  
because it has not been very stimulative,'' said Sean Li, a trader 
at Amsteel Securities (Hong Kong) Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	In Taipei, financial stocks led a strong rally amid expectations  
that those companies will benefit from recent cuts in reserves they 
are required to hold. 
</P>
<P>
	The Weighted Price Index gained 139.60 points, or 2.2 percent,  
to 6,403.14. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kuala Lumpur, shares slumped amid continued uncertainties  
over Malaysia's economic and political outlook ahead of state 
elections in Sabah, the first popularity test for Prime Minister 
Mahathir Mohamad's party since the arrest of former Deputy Prime 
Minister Anwar Ibrahim. The elections will be held March 12-13. 
</P>
<P>
	The KLSE Composite Index closed at 513.23, down 12.80 points, or  
2.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai stocks rose after the country's lower house  
approved a bill to set up Thailand's first bankruptcy court. The 
SET index gained 2.69 points, or 0.8 percent, to 341.51. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares rose slightly as uncertainty over the  
country's banking reforms encouraged buying in the mining and 
telecommunication sectors, which are considered safer bets. The JSX 
Composite rose 0.841 points, or 0.2 percent, to 395.807. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine stocks rallied on expectations that inflation  
in February, to be announced Friday, might have dropped to a 
single-digit level. The PSE index rose 38.54 points, or 1.9 
percent, to 2,008.92. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Blue chip shares fell as interest in smaller  
companies stole the limelight. The Straits Times Index fell 2.80 
points, or 0.2 percent, to 1,415.81, 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: South Korean shares rose for the fourth straight day on  
lower interest rates. The Kospi index rose 0.52 points, or 0.1 
percent, to 534.49 points. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian shares fell slightly as late selling offset  
gains made earlier in the day. The All Ordinaries index fell 2.9 
points, or 0.1 percent, to 2,889.9. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand's NZSE-40 capital index fell slightly,  
despite a rise by market heavyweight Telecom Corp. of New Zealand 
Ltd.. The index fell 0.25 points, or 0.01 percent, to 2,157.77 
points. 

</P>
</TEXT>
