<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Race May Have Motivated Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND PARK, Fla. (AP) -- They were high school sweethearts, one  
black one white. The woman was shot and killed while riding in the 
man's car last month. 
</P>
<P>
	A 23-year-old man was arrested yesterday and charged with the  
black woman's killing, described by police as a possible hate 
crime. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were some remarks made at a bar prior to him leaving the  
night of the shooting, that he was going to go out and shoot a 
black person,'' Lt. Glenn Osani said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Jody J. Bailey, 20, was killed Feb. 24 when the driver of  
another car pulled up next to the car she was riding in and fired 
at least five rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	She was hit in the temple and pronounced dead at the hospital.  
Her fiance, Christian Martin, 20, was not injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Police arrested Robert R. Boltuch of Sunrise at a friend's house  
on Tuesday, Osani said. He was not armed and did not resist arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Boltuch, 23, who had been working as a waiter until the  
shooting, was booked at the Broward County Jail on charges of 
first-degree murder and attempted first-degree murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin and Bailey were high school sweethearts who'd dated for  
three years. Both were students at Florida Atlantic University. 
</P>
<P>
	Osani said the State Attorney's Office will make a decision on  
whether or not to charge Boltuch with a hate crime. 
</P>
<P>
	``I emphasize the fact that the race aspect is still only a  
possible motive,'' Osani said. 
</P>
<P>
	A hate crime classification upgrades the possible penalties if  
there are convictions. First-degree murder in Florida can result in 
a death sentence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
