<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boat Deaths Prompt Safety Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The commercial fishing industry is ranked the most  
dangerous industry in America, a grim distinction highlighted by 
four recent sinkings that killed 11 East Coast clam fishermen in 
less than a month. 
</P>
<P>
	With that background, a Coast Guard safety panel is expected to  
recommend mandatory inspections of fishing boats and licensing of 
skippers, said panel member Bob Higgins, a Coast Guard safety 
coordinator. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of all the different issues brought to the table, licensing  
and inspections were the two leading components,'' Higgins said 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel was created in January after the four fishing vessels  
sank in the Atlantic between Dec. 28 and Jan. 18. Three accidents 
took place off New Jersey's coast, and one happened off New 
Bedford. 
</P>
<P>
	Commercial fishing has 131 deaths per year per 100,000  
employees, according to the Occupational Health and Safety 
Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress has rejected licensing requirements three times because  
of concern the industry already is over-regulated. And the 
recommendations will probably meet with widespread opposition from 
the industry, which some say is drowning in regulations that 
protect fish. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fishing fleet is in such a battle over fishing  
regulations, this will be one more thing they'll put out and the 
guys will go berserk,'' said William Adler, a lobsterman and member 
of the Coast Guard's commercial fishing enforcement working group. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know they're trying to stomp out all possible ways people  
can get killed and that's very important. But the sinkings are 
still going to take place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The panel's recommendations are due March 19.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
