<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sharon Proposes Unity Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon today  
proposed creating a government of national unity in order to 
postpone May elections and help find a way to end Israel's 
occupation in southern Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
	The opposition Labor Party rejected Sharon's plan, saying it was  
proof that the government of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has 
failed to solve any of the nation's pressing problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharon may have floated the idea, in part to take the air out of  
a surprise pledge by Labor Party leader Ehud Barak that, if elected 
in the May 17 vote, he would bring Israeli troops home within a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Netanyahu is leading a government that has been bogged down in  
every field,'' the Haaretz daily quoted Barak as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharon is Netanyahu's closest political ally and it is unlikely  
the foreign minister would have made the suggestion without 
clearing it with Netanyahu first. 
</P>
<P>
	With his earlier pledge, Barak placed the debate over Israel's  
17-year military presence in Lebanon at the heart of the election 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	There is growing frustration in Israel over the guerrilla war in  
southern Lebanon, where 901 Israeli soldiers have died since 1982. 
Seven Israelis have been killed this year in ambushes and roadside 
bombings by the Shiite Muslim guerrilla group Hezbollah. 
</P>
<P>
	In an attempt to take back the initiative in the election  
campaign, Netanyahu said he would also try to pull troops out of 
Lebanon within a year, though he said he could not commit to a 
date. In a television talk show Tuesday evening, the prime minister 
invited Barak to present his plan to the Cabinet. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharon said a broad-based government was needed to solve  
Israel's most pressing problems, including the guerrilla war in 
Lebanon and the unfinished negotiations with the Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	``We immediately need to set up an emergency national unity  
government, headed by Likud and Labor, in order to make a decision 
on a unilateral withdrawal from Lebanon and on implementing the 
(peace) agreement with the Palestinians,'' the Yediot Ahronot daily 
quoted Sharon as saying. Sharon's spokesman, Raanan Gissin, 
confirmed the remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related development, Defense Minister Moshe Arens said that  
Israel may walk away from a U.S.-brokered 1996 agreement with 
Hezbollah that neither side will target civilians. 
</P>
<P>
	Arens told The Jerusalem Post in an interview published today  
that he felt the understandings with Hezbollah hurt Israel's 
interests. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a large measure (the agreements) tie the Israeli Defense  
Forces' hands and won't allow it to use its full capability and 
provide a large degree of immunity to the Hezbollah,'' Arens said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if Israel might abandon the understandings, Arens said:  
``It is a possibility among a number of options that we have to 
look at.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the agreement, both sides pledge not to fire from or  
into civilian areas. An international monitoring group reviews 
compliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
