<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fluctuate; Dow Down 4.34 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock indexes wavered between positive and  
negative territory as Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan 
reiterated reservations about investing Social Security funds in 
equities. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 4.34 at 9,293.27. The blue-chip index had risen as high as 
9,337.00, up nearly 40 points, before retreating. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was up 1.44 at 1,226.94, and the technology-heavy Nasdaq 
composite index was up 2.94 at 2,261.97. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues led advancers by 11 to 9 on the New York Stock  
Exchange, where volume came to 341.10 million shares, up from 
Tuesday's pace of 314.08 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Addressing a Congressional subcommittee this morning, Greenspan  
warned that President Clinton's proposal to invest a significant 
portion of the nation's Social Security Trust Fund could render the 
stock market less efficient. It could also harm the economy, he 
said, by potentially channeling investment dollars into poorer 
performing companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The remarks ruffled a market that was already poised to continue  
the correction it started last week. That correction has been 
focused in technology shares, and no other sector has stepped 
forward to lead the market higher, said Scott Bleier, chief 
investment strategist at Prime Charter in New York. ``This market 
is locked in a trading range,'' Bleier said. ``You are in the 
process of building some very serious negative sentiment, far more 
negative than we've see in several months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added Michael Farr, a partner in the investment firm of Farr,  
Miller &AMP; Washington, in Washington D.C.: ``You're looking to what 
might be a stimulus for the markets, and it's certainly not coming 
from Mr. Greenspan this morning,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow industrials were led lower by Union Carbide, which was  
down 1 5/8 at 43 3/16 after rising 9 percent Tuesday on takeover 
speculation. Consumer stocks were also lower, with Eastman Kodak 
down 1 3/8 at 63 11/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks were mixed after another warning about  
declining computer sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest one, from 3Com Corp., which sells data, voice and  
video systems for the Internet and intranets. The company said late 
Tuesday that third-quarter earnings from ongoing operations will be 
about 23 cents a share, far below analysts' previously expected 36 
cents. 
</P>
<P>
	The company blamed an ``unexpected slowdown'' in sales to  
businesses in the United States and Latin America. 3Com stock was 
down 3 3/8 at 23 5/8 in leading volume in Nasdaq trading, after dropping 
Tuesday in after-hours trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the technology sector was turning higher after a  
mixed morning. Intel was up 1 15/16 at 111 3/4 in Nasdaq trading, but 
Dow component Hewlett-Packard, which gained Tuesday on a 
restructuring announcement, was up another 5/16 at 68 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices were lower after the National Association of  
Purchasing Management said its index of non-manufacturing activity 
rose to 57.0 percent in February, from January's 54 percent. But, 
the group's index of non-manufacturing prices eased, to 46.5 
percent from 47 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The bullish economic data erased a slight gain in bonds this  
morning. The 30-year Treasury was down 23/32 point at 5.66 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The higher interest rates will exacerbate a slower economy, so  
that things are feeling kind of toppy in the stock market here,'' 
Farr said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 11:56:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Concorde May Be Banned in Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Concorde -- the pride of European aviation  
and the world's only supersonic passenger jet -- would be banned 
from the United States under a bill the House passed Wednesday to 
retaliate against new environmental rules the European Union is 
considering. 
</P>
<P>
	Indignant House members passed by voice vote a measure that  
would keep Concorde aircraft from operating over U.S. soil if the 
European Parliament adopts a plan that would end up restricting the 
use of some U.S.-based aircraft to cut down on air pollution. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. planes under question either have new engines installed  
or are fitted with ``hushkits,'' devices similar to mufflers, Rep. 
Bud Shuster, R-Pa., said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill's supporters said the European plan could cost American  
businesses more than $1 billion in sales of spare parts and 
engines, reduce the resale value of more than 1,600 U.S. aircraft 
and cause severe losses to manufacturers of hushkits. 
</P>
<P>
	``The European restriction would apply only to U.S. aircraft  
even though, in some cases, they are quieter than their European 
counterparts that would not be restricted under the regulations,'' 
the House Republican Conference said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	During floor debate, members of the House called the proposed  
regulations a discriminatory, anti-American trade action thinly 
disguised as environmental protection. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why is the European Community taking anti-competitive action  
as they have done with their proposal to eliminate some 1,600 U.S. 
aircraft from the European air system?'' said Rep. James Oberstar, 
D-Minn., who introduced the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure now goes to the Senate.  
</P>
<P>
	Shuster said he hoped the threat of legislation alone would  
persuade the Europeans to table their plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's our hope that we don't need to proceed further in the  
Senate and have this signed into law,'' he said. ``This is blatant, 
outrageous discrimination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	'' None of us relishes taking this type of retaliatory measure,  
but fair is fair,'' said Rep. Louise Slaughter, D-N.Y. ``This sends 
a simple message to our friends across the pond that we will 
respond in kind when they take this type of action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, supporters said, the Concorde has been exempt from  
U.S. noise standards for 20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``According to a preliminary analysis from the Federal Aviation  
Administration, a ban on Concorde flights will reduce the noise 
footprint around New York's John F. Kennedy International Airport 
by at least 20 percent,'' the House Republican Conference said. 
</P>
<P>
	The needle-nosed plane, famous for rocketing through the sky at  
more than twice the speed of sound, made its first flight March 2, 
1969. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 661.  
</P>
</TEXT>
