<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ark. Pastor Accused in Church Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The former pastor who said he cried  
when his tiny church burned to the ground has been charged with 
setting the 1996 fire, one in a series of church blazes across the 
South. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Harris, 37, who now lives in Marlow, Okla., was charged  
with one count of arson Wednesday. He faces up to 20 years in 
prison and a fine of up to $250,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Johnson said Harris had not been  
arrested, and refused to answer questions about a possible motive. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris could not be reached for comment in Marlow.  
</P>
<P>
	The Kentucky Missionary Baptist Church near Benton burned on  
Aug. 24, 1996, amid a series of fires in both predominantly black 
and white churches. Kentucky Missionary's 45-member congregation is 
white. 
</P>
<P>
	The day after the fire, Harris said in an interview: ``We were  
out here shedding tears and helping each other get through this. 
It's like watching your home burn.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said that a passing motorist noticed the fire and contacted  
him. The fire happened on his 35th birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rev. Dennis McClintic, who replaced Harris as pastor about two  
years ago, said the congregation is heartbroken and somewhat 
stunned by the news of Harris' indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to pray for his family. We are going to pray for  
him. The members here are not ones to hold a grudge,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In March 1997, Gov. Mike Huckabee traveled to the site of the  
Kentucky Missionary Baptist fire to sign an act making church arson 
a felony under state law. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bill shows that we honor and respect the institutions of  
family and government,'' Huckabee said then. ``When we lose them, 
we lose the essence of what we are.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
