<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 08:26:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Auditors: Clinton Plan Breaks Caps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress' chief fiscal analyst said today that  
President Clinton's budget would bust spending caps for next year 
by $30 billion. Republicans immediately used the report to 
criticize the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	In the $1.77 trillion budget for fiscal 2000 that he proposed  
last month, Clinton proposed billions in extra spending for 
schools, health and other areas. He would keep the added spending 
within budgetary limits by paying for them with higher cigarette 
taxes and other revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	But in testimony before the Senate Budget Committee, Dan  
Crippen, new director of the nonpartisan Congressional Budget 
Office, said Clinton's proposed savings would not keep spending 
within limits because under budget law, those revenues ``do not 
count as offsets'' against such spending. 
</P>
<P>
	The spending caps, enacted two years ago in the budget-balancing  
pact between Clinton and Congress, were designed to bring 
expenditures under control. Fiscal 2000 begins on Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	In his prepared remarks, Senate Budget Committee Chairman Pete  
Domenici, R-N.M., said Clinton's budget continues ``a troubling 
pattern'' from the administration. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Clinton has repeatedly used budget devices ``to make  
promises for new or increased spending in his budget, claim that it 
is paid for no matter how unlikely the offsets, and then throw the 
whole muddle into the lap of the Congress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The CBO study also said Clinton's budget would produce surpluses  
totaling $73 billion less than he claims over the next five years, 
discounting the president's plans for using anticipated federal 
surpluses for shoring up Social Security, Medicare, and other 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	If Clinton's Social Security plan is factored in, the surpluses  
would be $436 billion smaller through 2004 than he says, CBO said. 
</P>
<P>
	The analysis came as GOP congressional leaders decided to try to  
quickly push a plan through Congress allowing Social Security funds 
to be used only for shoring up the massive pension system or 
shrinking the national debt. 
</P>
<P>
	By rushing the measure to Clinton before turning to tax cuts and  
other priorities, Republicans hope to buffer themselves against 
politically potent Democratic accusations that the GOP is plotting 
to divert needed Social Security funds for tax reductions for the 
wealthy. 
</P>
<P>
	As the year's budget fight begins, the CBO report is certain to  
be used by Republicans to accuse Clinton of spending more and doing 
less to protect federal surpluses than he claims. 
</P>
<P>
	The spending limit in question -- $537 billion for fiscal 2000 --  
applies to so-called discretionary spending. This includes 
everything but automatically paid benefits such as Medicare, as 
well as payments to holders of federal debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Linda Ricci, a spokeswoman in the White House budget office,  
said Clinton's aides have not seen the CBO figures yet. But she 
added that the two agencies often use different assumptions on the 
pace of spending or collecting revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every element of the president's budget is fully paid for,''  
she said. ``The offsets exist. It is simply a matter of the CBO 
choosing to put our offsets in a different category than we have. 
This is a balanced budget.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Staying within the spending cap is proving a problem for  
Republicans as well. They are struggling to live within it while 
meeting bipartisan calls for extra spending for defense, schools 
and perhaps other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican lawmakers and aides have acknowledged that it is  
likely they will have to exceed the spending limit eventually. 
Publicly, however, many GOP lawmakers insist they hope to live 
within the cap. 
</P>
<P>
	In its study, the CBO was more optimistic than the White House  
when it came to predicting the size of federal surpluses over the 
next decade if no tax or spending changes were made. 
</P>
<P>
	Except for 2009, the CBO envisions a bigger surplus than Clinton  
did for every year, a total of nearly $200 billion more than he did 
over the decade. For the next five years alone, the CBO sees 
surpluses totaling $953 billion, some $125 billion more than the 
White House projected. 
</P>
<P>
	Without any action, the CBO envisions a 1999 surplus of $111  
billion, growing to $133 billion next year and hitting $383 billion 
by 2009. The White House projected a $79 billion surplus this year, 
$117 billion next year and $393 billion in 2009. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's budget would leave the 2000 surplus at $113 billion  
without his Social Security plan and $80 billion with it, the CBO 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
