<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cathay Pacific Seeks Pay Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Cathay Pacific Airways and its pilots could be  
heading toward turbulent times, after the company said Wednesday it 
wants to cut senior cabin crew's pay by an average of 8 percent in 
exchange for stock options. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay, which is trying to slash costs and return to  
profitability, said in a statement that some pilots enjoy pay 
``significantly above the market level'' but added it had no plans 
``for less senior crew to take any form of salary concession.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A union leader attacked Cathay's ``deplorable'' labor relations  
and questioned management's motives, asking whether Cathay is using 
Asia's economic troubles as an excuse to slash salaries just so it 
can maximize profits when business takes off again. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot analyze whether there really is a need for our  
members to make concessions,'' said John Findlay, general secretary 
of the Air Crew Officers Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay has told its 1,300 pilots it needs to cut costs to  
weather the regional troubles that have pushed the airline into the 
red. But the company has made no detailed proposals and has refused 
to provide pilots with any projections about whether business will 
bounce back along with Asia's economies, Findlay said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the company wants to take advantage of the current economic  
difficulties, that's greedy,'' Findlay told a reporter. ``If the 
company is in a serious financial problem and can demonstrate it, 
of course we will sit down and talk about it. Thousands of jobs 
depend on Cathay Pacific.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any showdown with pilots would come close behind the company's  
dispute with flight attendants that left much ill feeling among the 
staff. Cathay demanded that flight attendants work more hours in 
exchange for a pay raise, then told 4,200 members of the cabin crew 
union that the union had no right to serve as their collective 
bargaining agent in the case. 
</P>
<P>
	The flight attendants caved in, though their union vaguely vowed  
to fight on. Findlay said pilots would deliver ``a much different 
response,'' declining to rule out industrial action. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay bosses said Wednesday evening they have been unable to  
have a substantive dialogue with the pilots union for months -- 
although group public affairs general manager Andrew Herdman would 
not specify why. 
</P>
<P>
	The company plans to send its proposals directly to pilots  
instead of the union -- which it says it must do under Hong Kong 
labor law in a case where workers are being asked to make 
concessions, Herdman said. The move does not preclude talks with 
the union, Herdman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The South China Morning Post said some pilots would face salary  
cuts of up to 27 percent. Cathay would not comment on the figure, 
though it said some pilots based overseas on Hong Kong expatriate 
pay packages would suffer the biggest cuts because they get 
salaries that are up to twice what their local counterparts make. 
</P>
<P>
	The Post said Cathay was seeking annual savings of 500 million  
Hong Kong dollars ($64 million) from the pilots, but the company 
would not confirm or deny that figure. 
</P>
<P>
	The union accused Cathay of trying to negotiate through the news  
media in an absence of any formal talks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Negotiations should be taking place between the parties  
involved,'' Findlay said. ``Their management style is, quite 
frankly, deplorable.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
