<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer Star Admits His Dive on Foul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	National Sportsmanship Day came and went in these United States  
without creating much of a stir. 
</P>
<P>
	A curious thing happened in Europe, though, where Argentine  
soccer star Diego Simeone finally owned up to taking a dive on the 
foul that got Englishman David Beckham ejected from last summer's 
World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	It took a brave man (or a foolish one) to do what Simeone did --  
which was not so much apologize as say, ``Better luck next time, 
suckers!'' Especially since was quoted as saying such on Tuesday, 
one day before his Italian club team, Internazionale of Milan, 
wound up in England playing Beckham's Manchester United side in a 
European Champions Cup quarterfinal. 
</P>
<P>
	As sportsmanship goes, this episode did not have a promising  
beginning. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously I was clever by letting myself fall ... and the  
referee fell into the trap ... showing the red card,'' Simeone said 
in the Italian sports daily Gazzetta dello Sport. ``You can say 
that my falling turned a yellow card into a red card.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Watching the foul on replay now, the impressive thing is that  
Simeone was able to make such a meal out of it. The sequence begins 
late in the first half as Beckham, dribbling with the ball, is 
tackled to the ground. He and Simeone get tangled up and the 
whistle blows. As they begin untangling, Beckham, still face down, 
kicks back with his right foot -- a nudge, almost -- and grazes the 
Argentine captain. 
</P>
<P>
	``In reality,'' Simeone said, ``it was not a violent blow. It  
was just a kick with no force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But forceful enough, apparently, to convince referee Kim Neilsen  
to eject Beckham, one of his England brightest young talents. The 
10 countrymen he left behind held on to tie 2-2 in regulation 
before losing on penalty kicks. Naturally, Beckham caught most of 
the blame. 
</P>
<P>
	As passionate as Americans are about their games, nothing lights  
us up the way soccer does the rest of the world, and so nothing 
that happens here rivals the way England unloaded on its suddenly 
flawed hero. If the entire nation had shunned Roberto Alomar for 
weeks after he spit on umpire John Hirschbeck, then decided to get 
nasty and personal and threatening as he made the round of 
ballparks the next season, you'd have some idea of the gantlet 
Beckham had to run. 
</P>
<P>
	But either he was brought up right -- or he learned something  
along the way. On the eve of Wednesday's game, Beckham's father 
said his son was prepared to shake hands with Simeone before the 
kickoff. 
</P>
<P>
	``David hasn't forgotten it, but he has put it behind him,'' Ted  
Beckham said. ``It's all history now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Simeone had told the Italian press he doesn't shake hands with  
opponents as a matter of principle. But Wednesday he changed his 
mind. Just before the game, as players from both teams shook hands 
on either side of them, Simeone and Beckham did the same. That 
small bit of civility was only a temporary peace, but it was peace 
nonetheless. Even small victories feel good when you're losing the 
war. 
</P>
<P>
	Athletes at the highest levels are taught, pushed and more than  
ever, praised for exploiting every advantage. To build bulk and 
minimize wear and tear on his body, slugger Mark McGwire uses a 
muscle-building supplement he'd have a hard time recommending to 
his son. Dennis Rodman's off-the-court behavior is drawing raves in 
his latest NBA reincarnation. But watch his behavior on the court 
if you want to see him flout rules. Dick Butkus was as tough as 
anybody who ever played football. He also hit, bit, gouged and 
stomped people when he got the chance, and somehow it came out as 
charming. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he was a cab driver and he had Ray Charles in the back  
seat,'' former NFL kicker Benny Ricardo once joked, ``he'd rev up 
the engine for 50 minutes and charge him full fare.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's a good line, but a costly laugh. We celebrate cunning and  
guile in our sports, then pretend to be surprised when kids do, 
too. The people who run the National Federation of High Schools, a 
clearinghouse for prep sports information, don't keep numbers on 
unsportsmanlike episodes each year. But they will say anecdotal 
evidence suggests high school games are more intense than they used 
to be. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last few years, one high school football player  
cold-cocked a referee by slamming into him from behind, after a 
30-yard run-up, and another was caught wearing steel buckles on his 
helmet sharpened to a razor's edge. The sad thing? The kid's 
father, a pediatric dentist, did the handiwork.. 
</P>
<P>
	Sports used to be where the world went to check its attitude, to  
sit down and watch somebody else play hard but clean for something 
that mattered. It was located somewhere above petty jealousy and 
priced below a week's groceries for a family of four. The stakes 
eventually got so high that winning seems to be all that matters. 
But the more it means, the better it pays, the farther we can 
expect sportsmanship to be nudged out towards the end of that 
ledge. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@apmail.ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 22:31:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Smoking Pill Said To Top Patch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Trying to kick the smoking habit? Maybe you should add the pill  
to the patch. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first head-to-head comparison, the anti-smoking drug  
Zyban proved twice as good as the nicotine patch in helping people 
quit smoking -- and used together were even more effective. 
</P>
<P>
	Used together, they helped more than 35 percent of smokers stay  
off cigarettes for a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The patch had disappointing results, working no better than a  
dummy pill or patch. But the researchers themselves disagreed over 
whether the findings were a fluke, since other studies have shown 
the patch works. 
</P>
<P>
	The study, led by Dr. Douglas Jorenby of the University of  
Wisconsin Medical School's Center for Tobacco Research and 
Intervention, was reported in today's New England Journal of 
Medicine. It was paid for by the maker of Zyban. 
</P>
<P>
	Using both methods at the same time was especially effective in  
helping people prevent weight gain during the first seven weeks. 
Those using both the patch and Zyban put on about 2.4 pounds, 
compared with 3.6 for either method alone and 4.6 on placebos, or 
dummy treatments. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people say the fear of gaining weight stops them from  
even trying to quit smoking or can sabotage them early in the 
process,'' Jorenby said. 
</P>
<P>
	About 46 million Americans smoke, and it will eventually kill  
half of them, at a rate of about 400,000 a year. Three-quarters of 
smokers want to quit, but at most 5 percent manage to do so on 
their own. 
</P>
<P>
	Zyban is the brand name for the antidepressant bupropion. Since  
Zyban was approved in 1997 as the first non-nicotine product to 
help smokers quit, doctors have written 4 million prescriptions for 
it, according to Glaxo Wellcome Inc., the manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
	``The very high success rate with bupropion is extremely  
encouraging,'' said Dr. Alan Leshner, director of the National 
Institute on Drug Abuse. Adding behavioral treatment to the mix 
should bring even more success, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Glaxo Wellcome paid for the study. Jorenby has organized  
presentations for Glaxo Wellcome. Seven of the 11 other researchers 
also have worked for Glaxo Wellcome, Novartis -- which made the 
patches studied -- or a competitor in the quit-smoking business. 
</P>
<P>
	It took a habit of at least 15 cigarettes a day to qualify for  
the study. Smokers who were depressed were turned down. All 893 
participants got patches to stick on and pills to take, but some of 
the patches and pills were dummies. 
</P>
<P>
	After four weeks, the patch had significantly better results  
than the placebo. Buproprion alone was more effective than the 
patch, and both treatments were better yet. 
</P>
<P>
	After a year, more than 35 percent of the people getting both  
treatments were still not smoking, compared with about 30 percent 
of those on bupropion alone. But only 16.4 percent of those on the 
patch were smoke-free, compared with 15.6 percent of those whose 
used placebo patches and pills. 
</P>
<P>
	Jorenby said the finding was a fluke. Other studies have shown  
about a 30 percent success rate for the patch, according to Dr. 
Neal Benowitz of the University of California at San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	``People who failed on nicotine once don't do very well if you  
re-treat with nicotine. My guess is that a fair number of people 
had tried a nicotine patch or nicotine gum before,'' Benowitz said. 
</P>
<P>
	The study did include people who had used patches before, but  
there wasn't any significant difference in their quit rates, said 
another of the researchers, Dr. Michael Fiore, director of the 
tobacco research center. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the difference between bupropion and the patch is a  
real one,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
