<DOCNO> APW19990303.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 11:56:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Leads Agenda Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton stood with congressional  
Democrats today and declared ``we are united'' behind an ambitious 
legislative agenda, looking to gain a tactical advantage over 
Republican lawmakers still wrestling with their plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton met with House and Senate Democrats to roll out their  
1999 ``Families First'' agenda, a four-page political wish list 
topped by a bid to set aside 77 percent of projected federal budget 
surpluses for Social Security and Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	The president boasted that the nation has enjoyed its longest  
peacetime economic expansion, with low unemployment and low 
inflation, during his six years in office. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we had before that was more than a decade in which the  
leaders of the other party talked tough, but took the easy way 
out,'' Clinton said. ``We were unashamed about being compassionate, 
unashamed that we cared about those that needed a hand up in 
life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He commended Republicans for agreeing to reserve billions of  
dollars for fixing Social Security but said they have not signed on 
to his proposals for salvaging Medicare. ``There are still strong 
differences in our approach and we must resolve them in a way that 
benefits the American people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., urged Republicans to  
work with Democrats on health care reforms and legislation that 
benefits working Americans. ``We want to make progress now. This 
month. This year. This session. We can't afford to waste another 
year or two mired in partisan wrangling and gridlock,'' Gephardt 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said, ``Democrats  
are determined and we are unified.'' Picking up that theme, Clinton 
said, ``We stand today unified. We stand today well aware of the 
challenges before us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's bring a new energy to this session of Congress,''  
Clinton declared. ``When we get really frustrated about what seems 
to be excessive partisanship ... let's keep our optimism, our good 
cheer, our resolve and our unity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Czwartacki, spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent  
Lott, R-Miss., replied: ``It's nice to see that three months after 
the Republicans announced their agenda, the Democrats are getting 
around to doing the same. We have already made significant progress 
on our agenda, which emphasized education, strengthening national 
security, among others.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Democrats' agenda closely tracks the priorities Clinton  
articulated in his State of the Union address in January: 
modernizing schools and improving accountability of local school 
systems, approving a ``patients' bill of rights'' on health care, 
expanding pension benefits, increasing the minimum wage, 
dispatching more police officers to fight crime and offering 
several small, targeted tax reductions for purposes such as caring 
for a child or an elderly relative. 
</P>
<P>
	The gathering comes as congressional Republicans try to glue  
together their legislative priorities. So far, they have identified 
goals such as a tax cut, a military pay raise and reforms to Social 
Security and education but have reached no consensus on how to go 
about reaching them. 
</P>
<P>
	Several agree, however, that the Democratic plan is flawed. Sen.  
Larry Craig, R-Idaho, called it last week ``a getting-nothing-done 
agenda,'' as in, ``saying the Republican Congress couldn't get 
anything done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For their part, Democrats are pressing GOP leaders to take up  
their agenda right away. But that is unlikely, for large fights 
loom over the proposals on Social Security, Medicare and education. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday, Republican leaders agreed on a push to allow Social  
Security funds to be used only to shore up the pension system or 
bring down the national debt. In a closed meeting, Senate Majority 
Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi and House Speaker Dennis Hastert, 
R-Ill., instructed budget writers to agree on a workable proposal 
to be announced this week -- and to be on Clinton's desk in a few 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of his fiscal 2000 budget plan, Clinton has proposed  
setting aside 62 percent -- or $2.8 trillion -- of the expected $4.9 
trillion in budget surpluses over the next 15 years to shore up 
Social Security so it can bear the massive waves of expected 
baby-boomer retirements. He also wants Medicare to get 15 percent, 
or $686 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans agree with the notion of preserving 62 percent of  
surpluses for Social Security, but they want to set aside $200 
billion more than Clinton has proposed for that purpose over the 
next decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
