<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court: Feds Must Bargain With Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal agencies can be required to bargain  
with unions representing their employees over subjects the unions 
raise during the life of a contract agreement, the Supreme Court 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-4 ruling said the decision on whether to require such  
bargaining is up to the Federal Labor Relations Authority, which 
oversees labor disputes between federal agencies and their 
unionized workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress delegated to the authority the power to determine --  
within appropriate legal bounds ... -- whether, when, where and what 
sort of midterm bargaining is required,'' Justice Stephen G. Breyer 
wrote for the court. 
</P>
<P>
	The FLRA has said agencies are required to conduct such  
mid-contract bargaining. 
</P>
<P>
	The FLRA is similar to the National Labor Relations Board, which  
governs labor disputes in private industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Treasury Employees Union called the ruling a major  
victory for federal employees and their unions, saying it means 
federal agencies will have to bargain over issues such as safety 
problems that arise during a contract. The NTEU's lawyer argued 
today's case on behalf of another federal workers' union. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's ruling set aside a lower court decision that said the  
Interior Department's U.S. Geological Survey was not legally bound 
to bargain over a proposal raised by the union representing its 
employees in Reston, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	While negotiating a collective bargaining agreement with the  
Geological Survey, Local 1309 of the National Federation of Federal 
Employees sought a contractual right to have the agency negotiate 
``matters not covered by the provisions of this agreement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agency refused to negotiate the proposal, prompting the  
union to file an unfair labor practice complaint with the FLRA. 
</P>
<P>
	The authority ruled against the Geological Survey. On appeal the  
4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed the FLRA's decision, 
saying federal law does not require mid-term bargaining. 
</P>
<P>
	The FLRA had decided in 1985 the law did not require federal  
agencies to bargain mid-term. But after the U.S. Circuit Court of 
Appeals for the District of Columbia ruled in 1987 that federal law 
required such bargaining, the FLRA reversed its stand. 
</P>
<P>
	Breyer noted the FLRA ``says that it has determined, as a matter  
of its own judgment, that the parties must bargain over such a 
provision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, he said, because that judgment followed the District of  
Columbia court's ruling, ``we believe the authority should have the 
opportunity to consider these questions aware that the statute 
permits, but does not compel, the conclusions it reached.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His opinion was joined by Justices John Paul Stevens, Anthony M.  
Kennedy, David H. Souter and Ruth Bader Ginsburg. 
</P>
<P>
	Dissenting were Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices  
Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas. Writing 
for the four, O'Connor said the law ``plainly does not impose a 
general duty on agencies to bargain mid-term.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The cases are National Federation of Federal Employees vs.  
Department of Interior, 97-1184, and FLRA vs. Department of 
Interior, 97-1243. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
