<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Mixed; Dow Off 21.73 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A late rally in technology shares saved the  
stock market from another down day Wednesday, although the picture 
was mixed at the close. 
</P>
<P>
	Two more strong economic reports heightened fears that the  
Federal Reserve might raise interest rates as a hedge against 
inflation, pulling the market lower for most of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue chips finished on the down side, but tech shares bounced  
higher in the last hour thanks to some bargain hunters. They pulled 
some broader indexes slightly higher at the close. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 21.73 at 9,275.88. The  
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index ended up 6.17 at 2,265.20, 
while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index gained 2.20 to 1,227.70. The 
market has been generally weak since last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue chips were responding Wednesday to a slump in the bond  
market, where the 30-year Treasury bond lost $11.56 per $1,000 
valuation. The long bond's yield, which moves opposite the price, 
rose to 5.69 percent, a seven-month high and up from 5.61 percent 
late Tuesday. The yield hasn't been that high since hitting 5.71 
percent last July 31. 
</P>
<P>
	``The specific problem, short-term, is the bond market and  
rising yields,'' said Larry Wachtel, market analyst at Prudential 
Securities. With stock prices so high, ``it's very hard to justify 
these valuations when interest rates are rising.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices sank after the National Association of Purchasing  
Management said its index of non-manufacturing activity rose to 57 
in February, from January's reading of 54. Analysts said the 
increase was a sign that inflation could soon be on the rise, even 
though the same group's index of non-manufacturing prices eased to 
46.5 from 47. 
</P>
<P>
	Computer stocks dropped initially after 3Com Corp., which sells  
Internet equipment, said late Tuesday that third-quarter operating 
earnings will be far below analysts' expectations because of an 
unexpected slowdown in sales in the United States and Latin 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	3Com's statement followed similar warnings of soft computer  
sales from Compaq Computer and Micron Electronics, a unit of Micron 
Technology. 
</P>
<P>
	3Com stock fell 2 7/16 to 24 9/16 in market-leading Nasdaq  
volume. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks were lower through most of the session but  
inched higher at the end as investors perceived there were bargains 
to be had. Intel ended 4 7/8 higher at 114 11/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan helped pressure the  
market downward early in the day when he restated his reservations 
about President Clinton's proposal to invest a significant portion 
of the nation's Social Security Trust Fund in the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	Addressing a Congressional subcommittee, Greenspan again said  
such a plan could encourage investments for political reasons in 
companies that aren't well run, or discourage investments in 
companies that are. 
</P>
<P>
	On the New York Stock Exchange, declining issues led advancers  
by 13 to 9. Volume was moderately heavy at 894.2 million shares, 
about even with Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 0.39 to 582.55, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index fell 4.76 to 694.45. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies fell 2.48 to 391.95. 
</P>
<P>
	In foreign stock markets, the Nikkei 225 index in Tokyo climbed  
1.79 percent. In Europe, The DAX index in Frankfurt dropped 2.21 
percent, the FT-SE 100 index in London eased 0.21 percent, and the 
CAC in Paris gave up 1.10 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
