<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Levies Sanctions in Trade Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A bitter trade battle between the United  
States and Europe over bananas turned even nastier Wednesday as the 
United States began notifying importers that they now are liable 
for hefty penalty tariffs on $520 million worth of European goods. 
</P>
<P>
	If allowed to stand, the tariffs of 100 percent on items such as  
German coffee makers and French handbags effectively would double 
their price, putting them out of reach for most U.S. consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration is seeking to penalize European producers by  
an amount equal to the damages U.S.-based banana companies say they 
are suffering in lost sales because of unfair European trade 
barriers. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. action, which caught European officials by surprise,  
was immediately denounced by the 15-nation European Union. 
</P>
<P>
	The move came only a day after the World Trade Organization  
asked for more information before ruling on the legality of the 
U.S. trade sanctions. The WTO had requested both sides to provide 
that information by March 15. 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States decided to defy the WTO system by  
introducing a form of sanctions which has no WTO authorization 
whatsoever,'' Sir Leon Brittan, EU's trade minister, said in a 
statement issued in Brussels. ``What the United States has done is 
therefore unacceptable and unlawful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States said it would not collect any punitive tariffs  
until the WTO rules on the appropriate size of the sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	But starting Wednesday, importers of those products must post  
bonds and assume liability for paying the higher tariffs if the WTO 
rules in America's favor. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States contends that American banana companies are  
losing $520 million annually in lost sales to Europe because of 
illegal trade barriers that favor bananas imported from former 
European colonies in the Caribbean and Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Chiquita Brands International Inc. and Dole Food Co., the major  
American companies involved, grow their bananas on plantations in 
South America. 
</P>
<P>
	While the United States won a WTO case on this issue, the EU  
argued that the matter needed further review because it has changed 
some banana import rules. The U.S. side says the changes do not 
satisfy American objections. 
</P>
<P>
	The banana fight, which has dragged on for six years, has  
captured attention at the highest levels of government. It was on 
the agenda when French President Jacques Chirac met recently with 
President Clinton. Clinton told reporters the United States 
believed it was crucial for the world trading system that losing 
countries in WTO disputes abide by the decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Europeans contend politics is driving the United States to the  
brink of a trade war with its biggest trading partner. Carl 
Lindner, the head of Chiquita, is a major campaign contributor to 
both Democrats and Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Special U.S. Trade Negotiator Peter Scher told reporters at a  
news conference the penalty tariffs were effective Wednesday. The 
United States decided against holding off possible sanctions 
because it could have encouraged delaying tactics by countries 
losing WTO cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The target list includes Louis Vitton handbags from France,  
sweet biscuits from Britain, Parma ham and pecorino cheese from 
Italy, German coffee makers and a host of less fancy imports 
ranging from plastic packing material to batteries. 
</P>
<P>
	Scher said if the WTO does not allow the full $520 million in  
penalties, the administration will adjust its list to ensure 
compliance with the WTO ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	Requiring bonds until collecting sanctions has not been used in  
a WTO case although the administration did employ a similar 
procedure in a 1995 fight with Japan involving auto trade barriers. 
</P>
<P>
	Those tariffs never went into effect because the administration  
was able to negotiate an agreement to expand sales opportunities 
for American car companies in Japan. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
