<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 12:35:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lemieux Moves To Buy Penguins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- He knew how to get a puck past Andy Moog, but  
can he assemble a multimillion-dollar business deal? 
</P>
<P>
	Mario Lemieux, who led the Pittsburgh Penguins to two Stanley  
Cup championships, wants to rescue the team from bankruptcy, keep 
it in Pittsburgh and collect the $31.4 million he said he is owed. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux is seeking investors to raise $40 million to $50 million  
and said he wants to assume more than $60 million in the team's 
bank loans to buy the Penguins and ensure they don't move to 
another city. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux has filed papers indicating he is owed $31.4 million in  
deferred compensation, which makes him the club's largest unsecured 
creditor. He said he is willing to exchange some of those millions 
for equity in the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``My objective is to, obviously, get paid and keep the team here  
in Pittsburgh where it belongs,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins are about $125 million in debt, or more than the  
franchise's total value. The team filed for bankruptcy protection 
in October. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux said he expects to submit a plan to buy the team to U.S.  
Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz at a March 19 hearing in 
Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	Markovitz last week threatened to place the team into  
receivership unless he saw a finance reorganization plan soon. The 
judge said if he converted the Penguins' bankruptcy into a Chapter 
7 liquidation, he would appoint a trustee to run the club until a 
buyer is found. 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Marino, current co-owner of the franchise, also plans to  
submit a reorganization plan to Markovitz, even though he has lost 
nearly $40 million operating the club the last two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard Baldwin, the Penguins' primary owner from 1991-97 and  
still a co-owner, also is looking at trying to reorganize the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux offered Marino, a Boston multimillionaire, little  
sympathy for his financial losses. He said Marino isn't a creditor, 
and he made a bad investment. Lemieux is chairman of the committee 
representing the team's unsecured creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	Marino had hoped that Lemieux would join him in rescuing the  
club, which declared bankruptcy in October. But Lemieux, who has 
sued Marino to recover money owed to him in a contract approved by 
Baldwin, said last week he would not work with Marino. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux has met with city, county and state leaders to rally  
support for the team. 
</P>
<P>
	At the March 19 hearing, Markovitz is slated to rule on motions  
dealing with whether the team can leave Pittsburgh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 13:46:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Michigan State Is Hoops Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- While the rest of the Big Ten was scrapping and  
scraping, beating each other up in close games and staging more 
drama than a soap opera, Michigan State was rolling through its 
conference schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen straight victories and only one loss -- and that was way  
back in January. Only five games decided by five points or less. 
The No. 2 ranking in the country, its highest since Magic Johnson 
was a Spartan. A second-straight Big Ten title. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartans (26-4, 15-1 Big Ten) are just better than everyone  
else, the rest of the Big Ten coaches say. And that's probably not 
going to change when the Big Ten tournament starts Thursday at the 
United Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I've ever seen a time when there have been so  
many teams that are capable of beating one another in any given 
game. Except Michigan State,'' said Indiana coach Bob Knight. 
``Michigan State has been, throughout the course of the season, 
definitely the very best team in the league.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tournament begins Thursday with Northwestern (14-12, 6-10)  
facing Penn State (13-13, 5-11); Purdue (19-11, 7-9) playing 
Michigan (11-18, 5-11); and Minnesota (17-9, 8-8) meeting Illinois 
(11-17, 3-13). 
</P>
<P>
	Wisconsin (21-8, 9-7) will play Iowa (18-8, 9-7) in the first  
quarterfinal Friday. The Hawkeyes are on a mission for coach Tom 
Davis, who is coaching his last season after being forced out by 
the school administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The three top seeds -- Michigan State, Ohio State (22-7, 12-4)  
and Indiana (22-9, 9-7) -- all have byes until the quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Big Ten is hoping for seven bids to the NCAA tournament.  
Michigan State, Ohio State, Indiana, Wisconsin and Iowa are already 
in, but Minnesota and Purdue might have to win a few games this 
week to qualify. 
</P>
<P>
	Being the top seed is nothing new for the Spartans. They shared  
the regular-season conference championship with Illinois last year 
and were favored in the inaugural Big Ten tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	But they lost to Minnesota in the quarterfinals and were on  
their way back to East Lansing after just one game. 
</P>
<P>
	``All we're trying to do is find a way to win one game in the  
Big Ten tournament, something we couldn't do last year,'' coach Tom 
Izzo said. ``It seems like so few league champs win its conference 
tournament. One thing this team has adjusted to, we've had pressure 
on us all year and we've found a way to win. 
</P>
<P>
	``This team has different goals than last year,'' he added.  
``Last year, I think we were just happy to get into the tournament 
and I think that hurt us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That and Mateen Cleaves' horrid shooting. There's something  
about the United Center that just doesn't agree with Cleaves, the 
Big Ten player of the year for a second straight season. Maybe it's 
the tight rims. Maybe it's the stiff breeze that occasionally blows 
on the floor. Maybe it's nerves. 
</P>
<P>
	Whatever the reason, the United Center is Cleaves' personal  
demon. He was 2-of-18 in the loss to Minnesota last year. When the 
Spartans lost to Duke in the Great Eight last December, he was 
3-of-17. 
</P>
<P>
	But Cleaves has improved since then, Izzo said. So have the  
Spartans. Though they followed up the loss to Duke with a defeat at 
Connecticut, their only loss since was the conference opener to 
Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really a remarkable accomplishment,'' Wisconsin coach  
Dick Bennett said. ``Every single team, no matter how good you are, 
has a little bit of a slump at some point and time. If one were to 
define what happened to them as a slump, it might have come a 
little earlier and then they got it together. 
</P>
<P>
	``Say what you will, but there aren't many teams in the country  
playing more solidly than Michigan State.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And there are plenty of reasons, starting with Cleaves. There's  
also Morris Peterson, who leads the Spartans in scoring and was on 
the All-Big Ten first team despite playing off the bench. There's 
also Michigan State's defense and rebounding. 
</P>
<P>
	Most importantly, Izzo said the team just plays well together.  
</P>
<P>
	``What has made this team so special for two years is the  
chemistry. Why is it that good? If I had the answer,'' he said, 
``I'd probably be a lot wealthier than I am.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
