<HEADLINE> Oasis Settles With Former Drummer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- A British judge approved an $880,000 payment  
Wednesday to former Oasis drummer Tony McCarroll to settle a 
lawsuit he brought against the band after he was fired. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarroll, 27, was sacked in 1996 after a fight with singer Liam  
Gallagher in a Paris bar. Oasis members also claimed McCarroll, who 
was replaced by Alan White, took no interest in improving his 
``poor'' drumming. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarroll sued the band for being ``unlawfully expelled from the  
partnership,'' seeking 20 percent of Oasis's annual earnings, 
estimated at $29 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement, reached minutes after the case began Tuesday in  
the High Court, was made public after the judge approved it 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarroll played on the band's 1995 debut album, ``Definitely  
Maybe,'' and on the single ``Some Might Say,'' from its second 
album, ``(What's the Story) Morning Glory?'' 
</P>
<P>
	A statement from Oasis's attorneys said the band's members were  
pleased with the settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their position has always been that Tony should receive fair  
payment for the recordings made while he was in the group, but no 
more,'' the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
