<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tupperware Stretches Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) -- Until Pam Parish attended a Tupperware  
party last year, she hadn't been able to find the plastic utensils 
and food storage products in ages. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, Mrs. Parish, a 35-year-old teacher's aide and mother  
of two children, has been rapidly filling her kitchen with 
containers, bowls and modular mates. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a long time you didn't hear about anybody having a  
Tupperware party,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tupperware has taken Ms. Parish's predicament to heart.  
</P>
<P>
	For many, Tupperware demonstrations are a throwback to an  
earlier generation when TV's Donna Reed was the standard-bearer of 
domestic rectitude. But the changing customer base of working 
mothers with limited time, as well as economic turmoil in 
international markets and a lack of confidence by investors, has 
resulted in declining sales and a plummeting stock price over the 
past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	So the company that popularized at-home sales demonstrations in  
the 1940s has gone beyond its decades-old tradition of selling its 
wares only at Tupperware parties. Tupperware products are moving 
into shopping mall kiosks, onto the Internet and into television 
infomercials in order to make them more accessible to people who 
want them, but can't find them. 
</P>
<P>
	The products also have been modernized with bright colors and  
new features, including characters from Disney movies under a 
two-year-old partnership with the entertainment company. 
</P>
<P>
	``The company is saying 'Look, it's 1999. We have to figure out  
how to reach more people. We have to get it in their hands,''' Lisa 
Humphreys, a Tupperware sales manager, said after a recent 
demonstration at Ms. Parish's home in Leesburg. 
</P>
<P>
	The company began allowing sales representatives to sell  
Tupperware products at kiosks in a handful of Orlando shopping 
malls last Christmas and plans to expand to other markets this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	It also began airing infomercials for the first time last year  
and promises that customers will be able to buy Tupperware products 
over the Internet by the end of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Tupperware's problems, however, run deeper than not being able  
to get their products into potential customers' hands. 
</P>
<P>
	With 85 percent of its sales coming from outside the United  
States, Tupperware has been buffeted by the economic crises in Asia 
and Latin America. The company, which had $1.08 billion in sales 
last year, has seen revenue slip by more than 10 percent during 
each of the past two years, in part because of currency 
devaluations and the weakened purchasing power of non-U.S. 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Conceding that Tupperware has historically been slow to change,  
chairman and chief executive Rick Goings said the new measures will 
supplement, not replace, the direct sales made at Tupperware 
parties by a million-person sales force in more than 100 countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``This enhances attendance at our parties. It helps our core  
direct-selling business,'' Goings said at Tupperware's sprawling, 
100-acre headquarters in Kissimmee. ``We've been fighting stranded 
customers. There is a pent-up demand for the product.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tupperware is coming to the changes with a great deal of  
reluctance because the company doesn't want to offend its sales 
force, said Budd Bugatch, an analyst who follows Tupperware for 
Raymond James in St. Petersburg. 
</P>
<P>
	Tupperware officials don't want to do anything ``that could be  
perceived or used against them as denigrating or slapping their 
existing distributorship in the face,'' Bugatch said. ``But they 
need a higher level of sales, particularly in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Overall sales slipped by almost 12 percent to $1.08 billion in  
1998. Only the United States, its smallest market, posted a gain (6 
percent) from the previous year. Sales in Asia and Latin America 
decreased by 24 percent and sales in Europe decreased by slightly 
more than 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	While the company is still profitable, its income in 1998  
dwindled to $69.1 million, a 39 percent decrease from the previous 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors have also lost confidence in the company since it went  
public in 1996 as a spin-off of Premark International Inc. 
Tupperware stock has fallen from a high of $55.50 in December 1996 
to a low of around $11 last year. It is currently selling for 
around $18. 
</P>
<P>
	Goings attributed the volatility to the hype surrounding the  
initial public offering. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Tupperware is moving into shopping mall kiosks, don't  
expect any full-fledged Tupperware stores anytime soon. Over the 
decades, Bugatch said, the company has learned that its products 
don't do well at retailers because it's pricier than the 
competition and management believes the products need to be 
demonstrated. 
</P>
<P>
	But the demonstrations fulfill a greater need than just sales,  
Goings said. Most women of an earlier generation learned their 
homemaking skills from watching mothers or grandmothers. In today's 
mobile society where parents and grandparents live across country 
from their children and grandchildren, women are looking to people 
like Martha Stewart for those skills. 
</P>
<P>
	``The role of a local Tupperware woman is being a local Martha  
Stewart,'' Goings said. 
</P>
<P>
	To a certain extent, Mrs. Humphreys, the 33-year-old sales  
manager, feels she is fulfilling that role as she talks about 
recipes, offers health tips and shows off the latest microwaveable 
casserole dish in Mrs. Parish's living room. 
</P>
<P>
	The half-hour demonstration is interspersed with Mrs. Humphreys  
asking trivia questions about food and cooking. The women who 
answer correctly get fake $100 bills they can use to buy Tupperware 
goods during an auction after the demonstration. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tupperware is a relationship business,'' Mrs. Humphreys said.  
``The kiosks are for people who don't know where to get it from.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 05:42:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> USOC Responds to Salt Lake Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Olympics and their scandals are in the  
spotlight in the nation's capital, and a potentially earthshaking 
encore could be in the offing. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Olympic Committee planned to respond today to a  
scathing ethics panel report on management of the games and the 
corruption it has fostered, with recommendations expected on how to 
make sure the bribery case of Salt Lake City's 2002 Winter Olympics 
never recurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Stricter rules for American cities bidding for the Olympics and  
tighter reins on USOC programs could be among the items discussed 
by committee president Bill Hybl at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Senate Commerce Committee announced an April 14  
hearing into the ``scandals plaguing the Olympics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Ted Stevens, a committee member and the author of the  
federal law governing the Olympics in the United States, is 
considering a bill that would hit the International Olympic 
Committee right in the wallet. 
</P>
<P>
	It would strip the IOC of its tax-exempt status, limit tax  
deductions for IOC sponsorship and move control of billion-dollar 
U.S. television rights fees from the IOC to the USOC. 
</P>
<P>
	Commerce Committee chairman Sen. John McCain said witnesses for  
the hearing would be announced later closer to the April date. 
</P>
<P>
	Hybl discussed possible changes with the USOC executive  
committee in a conference call Tuesday night, and it was uncertain 
what specific programs he might announce. 
</P>
<P>
	But sources familiar with the committee said that Hybl would  
recommend far-reaching reforms that would clamp down on the type of 
actions that led to the million-dollar vote-buying scheme in Salt 
Lake's victorious quest for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	More open meetings, internal policy changes on bid-city  
policies, tighter oversight of foreign athlete training programs 
and more athlete involvement in USOC decisions were among the 
topics that Hybl might include in his program, according to the 
sources who spoke on the condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the changes could be accomplished by executive order,  
but others could require changes to the USOC Constitution, which 
could not be done until an October board meeting, the sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	USOC board meetings already are open, and committee staff and  
officials must abide by an 11-page ethics code instituted at the 
start of Hybl's term in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Hybl's conference also was expected to address the ethics  
committee report on Salt Lake presented Monday by former Senate 
Majority Leader George Mitchell, which said the Salt Lake scandal 
grew from a ``culture of improper gift giving'' in the Olympic 
community. 
</P>
<P>
	While it criticized the USOC and Salt Lake Olympic officials, it  
saved its harshest words for the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	It said the conduct ``tolerated by the IOC is potentially  
illegal and inevitably corruptive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The IOC should no sooner tolerate improper gifts by candidate  
cities to its members than it would tolerate such gifts by athletes 
to judges,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also said the USOC should open an independent office  
to oversee American bid committees; bar bid and candidate cities 
from international assistance programs and strictly follow 
guidelines for USOC-run programs; and strengthen guidelines and 
contracts for U.S. cities seeking the games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 05:37:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Tackle Major Antitrust Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- During the 1980s, a declawed Federal Trade  
Commission would have been unlikely to take on a high-profile 
antitrust case against one of the world's biggest technology 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	But in just a week, the commission will face off against Intel  
Corp. in the other major computer-courtroom drama unfolding in 
Washington -- bringing it out from behind the shadow of its sister 
federal antitrust agency, the Justice Department, and its case 
against Microsoft Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The high-stakes Intel case is indicative of the changing tide at  
the commission, which almost doubled its antitrust enforcement 
actions from 1997 to 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	With an aggressive leadership and buoyed by some large  
victories, the commission in recent years has vigorously exercised 
the authority given it by the 1976 Hart-Scott-Rodino Antitrust 
Improvements Act. 
</P>
<P>
	``The principal reason is not our doing but the world's doing,''  
said Robert Pitofsky, the commission's chairman. ``The behavior by 
some firms really raises antitrust questions more frequently.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, a wave of mergers has swept the nation in the past few  
years. More than $1 trillion in mergers occurred in fiscal year 
1998, and nearly 4,800 requests were filed by companies to have 
merger proposals reviewed by antitrust agencies as required by law. 
That is a 28 percent increase from previous years' filings. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, many believe the FTC has been newly aggressive in  
using its antitrust power and in grabbing headlines from Justice, 
harkening back to the 1960s, when it argued many antitrust cases 
before the Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Intel case was probably filed in part to say, `Hey, look  
at us! We're here, too, and we can enforce the same laws,''' said 
Bill Shughart, a University of Mississippi economics professor. 
Shughart, who worked at the FTC in the late 1970s and early 1980s, 
said he couldn't imagine the commission at that time bringing a 
similar complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission alleges that Intel illegally withheld from three  
companies technical information about its new generation of 
computer chips to ``extort'' valuable technology that the companies 
developed independently. Intel, based in Santa Clara, Calif., makes 
chips that run 80 percent of world's computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts attribute a good part of the agency's new gusto to  
Pitofsky, a lawyer sworn in as commissioner in 1995. In 1994, 
Pitofsky chaired a Pentagon advisory panel to address whether the 
defense industry should be granted antitrust exemptions as it 
downsized in the post-Cold War era. The task force recommended 
against it. 
</P>
<P>
	The chairman is the first to admit that mergers are not  
intrinsically harmful but rather the inevitable consequence of 
economic globalization, deregulation and an increase in the 
importance of high-tech industries. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's probably a sensible response to some changes that  
are going on,'' Pitofsky said. ``But independent deals can be very 
much of a threat to consumer welfare.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the FTC and Justice both embroiled in big computer cases,  
the fine line that distinguishes the two agencies seems a bit 
blurred. 
</P>
<P>
	``Generally there has been a gentleman's agreement between the  
two agencies not to compete to file lawsuits against the same firms 
at the same time,'' said Shughart. An agency might opt for a case 
based on workload or prior expertise: Airline mergers tend to end 
up at Justice, gasoline companies at the FTC. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies with mergers of a certain size must inform both  
agencies. Historically, the assistant attorney general of the 
antitrust division -- currently Joel Klein -- and the FTC chairman 
chat by phone to determine jurisdiction. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC has handled probably two-thirds of all mergers, because  
it has broader jurisdiction on civil matters, said Robert Burka, a 
private antitrust expert. In contrast, Justice can bring criminal 
cases and the FTC can't. 
</P>
<P>
	After its period of vigilant regulation in the 1960s, the FTC in  
the late 1970s moved away from traditional antitrust cases and 
focused instead on trying to stop states from using legislation to 
create monopolies, said Don Boudreaux, president of the Foundation 
for Economic Education in Irvington, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	But by the early 1990s, the commission started to accelerate its  
activity in mergers and predatory pricing, producing a string of 
successes: 
</P>
<P>
	--Staples and Office Depot in July of 1997 called off their $3.5  
billion merger after the commission got a court injunction arguing 
the deal would reduce competition and lead to higher prices. 
</P>
<P>
	--Rite Aid Corp. dropped a $1.8 billion deal with Revco in 1996  
after the FTC said Rite Aid would gain too much of the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitofsky concedes some deals can create efficiencies that could  
benefit consumers. He cites the alliance between Chrysler Corp. and 
Germany's Daimler-Benz AG, approved in July. 
</P>
<P>
	``We became fairly persuaded there were true efficiencies in  
putting together the two companies,'' Pitofsky said. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 19:12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hale's Whitewater Trial To Go On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Whitewater figure David Hale lost  
another attempt Wednesday to avoid trial on a charge he misled 
state regulators about the financial health of a burial insurance 
company he owned. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge James Moody ruled that the March 23 trial  
would not constitute double jeopardy, agreeing with a decision 
issued last month by the Arkansas Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale originally was to be tried last April, but a mistrial was  
declared after he checked into a hospital with heart problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale claimed the mistrial was called because a prosecution  
witness left the country. But Moody agreed with the state Supreme 
Court that the mistrial was due to Hale's uncertain health. 
</P>
<P>
	The case against Hale originated in March 1993 when Hale's  
National Savings Life Insurance Co. was instructed by the Arkansas 
Insurance Commission to correct a $38,757 shortfall. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale is accused of moving cash into a company account to create  
the illusion of financial health and then moving the money out. 
</P>
<P>
	Hale made national news when he claimed President Clinton  
pressured him into loaning money for a land deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
