<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mont. Court Rules Snake Is a Weapon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- A poisonous snake is a weapon as far as the  
Montana Supreme Court is concerned. 
</P>
<P>
	The court on Tuesday upheld the assault conviction and 30-day  
sentence of Michael Roullier, who wielded his pet rhinoceros viper 
at two police officers trying to arrest him in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	When police were called to a disturbance at the apartment where  
Roullier and his girlfriend lived, he grabbed the poisonous African 
snake from a cage, held its head and told the officers to get out 
of his way so he could leave. 
</P>
<P>
	When they refused, he said, ``If this snake bites you, you're  
dead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One officer tried to hit the snake with her baton, but Roullier  
shielded it close to his body. When the other officer threatened to 
use pepper spray, Roullier threatened suicide by turning the snake 
on himself. 
</P>
<P>
	After repeated requests, Roullier eventually threw the snake  
behind him and was arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	On appeal, Roullier claimed prosecutors proved only that he had  
possession of the snake, not that he used it as a weapon. 
</P>
<P>
	The high court disagreed. ``Roullier's manipulation of the snake  
amounted to much more than mere possession,'' Justice Terry 
Trieweiler wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Roullier has already served his sentence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
