<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 19:34:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar soared against the yen Thursday morning  
as falling interest rates battered the Japanese currency. Tokyo 
share prices edged slightly higher. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.31 yen in morning trading, up 1.13 yen  
from late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above its level of 121.77 yen 
in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average rose 32.88 points, or 0.23 percent, to  
close the morning session at 14,203.24 points. On Wednesday, the 
average closed up 249.30 points, or 1.79 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar jumped against the yen for a  
second day after Japan's central bank moved to lower short-term 
interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Bank of Japan flooded the interbank loan  
market with cash by purchasing short-term government bonds. The 
action drove the call rate, which is used by major banks when they 
make overnight loans to each other, to a record-low 0.02 percent 
from 0.07 percent the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone has been buying (dollars) today. The market is  
focusing very much on financial issues,'' said Hajime Sato, 
assistant general manager of the treasury department at Daiwa 
International Trust Bank. ``There are still lots of yen-negative 
factors,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan is struggling to recover from its worst recession in  
decades. Lowering interest rates reduces borrowing costs for 
companies and could spur investment and spending. 
</P>
<P>
	But declining rates also lower the return to investors on  
everything from bank deposits to government bonds. A country's 
currency often falls when interest rates do on the theory that some 
investors will pull their money out to seek higher returns 
elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 133.00 yen, up from  
132.25 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, optimism over the lower interest rates and  
stronger dollar helped share prices. Exporters rose on optimism the 
dollar's gain will help them earn more on their overseas sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section rose 6.59 points, or 0.60 percent, to 1,106.40 
points. The TOPIX closed up 7.73 points, or 0.71 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the yield on the 10-year Japanese government bond  
sank to 1.555 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.670 percent, 
driving its price up to 101.98 yen from 101.04 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
