<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Battelle, Roark Head American Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STEAMBOAT SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) -- A year ago, three-time Olympic  
moguls skier Ann Battelle was toying with retirement and Michelle 
Roark was a college student waiting for a chance to compete. 
</P>
<P>
	Now they're World Cup moguls champions and hope to do well in  
the World Championships in Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	Battelle, 31, who lives in Steamboat Springs, clinched her  
individual moguls title by winning the last event of the season 
Feb. 21 in Madarao, Japan. Roark, 24, a Denver resident, is the new 
title-holder in dual moguls, in which skiers compete side by side 
on a snowy bumps run. 
</P>
<P>
	They left Wednesday along with several teammates after a week or  
so at home. They relaxed, looked for a place to keep the crystal 
globes which go to World Cup champs, made a couple of promotional 
appearances and tried to shoehorn some light training into a busy 
schedule before heading to Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always more hectic in Steamboat than when I'm in  
Boulder'' with her boyfriend, Battelle said. ``This was a little 
frantic, but we got everything done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The championships open Sunday in Meiringen, Switzerland and run  
through March 14. Battelle has been fourth in moguls in each of the 
last two World Championships and would like to move up a notch or 
two next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the idea,'' she said before heading to the airport.  
``We'll see what happens. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a strange year but, yeah, I'm glad I came back,''  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Battelle, 31, worked last summer as an intern at the Boulder  
office of Charles Schwab and Co., a major sponsor of the U.S. Ski 
Team. As she worked, Battelle decided she'd return but on a reduced 
competition plan; as it developed, the World Cup schedule unraveled 
and it was a short season, anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	Roark, the 1998 Nor Am moguls champion while studying petroleum  
refining and environmental science at Colorado School of Mines, won 
the first two World Cups of her brief career over Super Bowl 
weekend and also clinched her title in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Roark trained at Winter Park Resort while Battelle spent a  
couple of easy days running moguls at Steamboat. They also mixed in 
a few promotional appearances with local media. 
</P>
<P>
	``And I got some new skis from Volkl,'' Battelle said. ``I have  
to get used to them, but I think we'll be OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Williston, Vt., Battelle never skied moguls until  
she graduated from Middlebury College in 1989 and moved to 
Steamboat Springs. She learned in a hurry, though, thanks to former 
U.S. coach Park Smalley, and by 1992 she made the first of three 
Olympic teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Roark was a figure skater as a youngster but when the financial  
strain became too heavy, she moved to skiing. A former junior 
national champion, she had two knee injuries, which slowed her 
advancement. At 4-11 and just over 100 pounds, she looks like she 
still could compete at the junior level, but after winning the 
NorAm moguls title in '98, she made a big breakthrough this season. 
</P>
<P>
	She won an individual moguls event on Super Bowl Saturday at  
Blackcomb, British Columbia and a dual moguls event the next day to 
give her a springboard to the championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't expect to be going to worlds,'' Roark said, ``so I  
don't have a lot of pressure. I'll try to do my best, which is 
really all I can do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She enjoyed the chance to be home, she added. ``I'm starting to  
get wrinkles, I've been smiling so much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, as she knows, things could be a lot worse. ``Parts of this  
year have been almost like a fairy tale,'' she said, smiling. 

</P>
</TEXT>
