<DOCNO> APW19990303.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 15:26:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fedorov Suspended 5 Games for Slash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Detroit Red Wings forward Sergei Fedorov has  
been suspended for five games without pay for slashing the New York 
Islanders' Zdeno Chara during Saturday's game. 
</P>
<P>
	Fedorov will lose $386,178 in pay and will be eligible to return  
March 17 against Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	The slash occurred with six minutes left in the Wings' 3-1 loss  
in New York. After Fedorov swung his stick with his right hand and 
struck Chara on the neck, Chara collapsed to the ice and remained 
there for several minutes. Fedorov was assessed a match penalty for 
deliberately injuring an opponent. 
</P>
<P>
	Fedorov has been classified as a repeat offender, given that he  
was suspended for two games on March 26, 1998, for a hit from 
behind on Jason Marshall of Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	``While Mr. Fedorov acknowledges and regrets the severity of his  
action, the league has made clear this season there is no 
acceptable explanation for administering blows to the head,'' said 
Colin Campbell, the league's senior vice-president and director of 
hockey operations, after Wednesday's hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	``This suspension also reaffirms the league's position that  
every player is accountable for his stick and that reckless, 
dangerous use of the stick will be met with severe consequences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fedorov said it was accidental.  
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to get up and the stick just got him,'' Fedorov said  
after the game. ``I was on my back, and I thought the puck was 
under me, so I tried to get up quickly and recover my position. I 
didn't mean to injure him.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990303.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-03 14:55:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bennett Agues Against Counsel Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The independent counsel law should be allowed  
to expire because it has evolved into ``a monster'' that strips 
public officials of some constitutional rights, one of President 
Clinton's personal attorneys told a Senate committee Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Can this statute be saved? I have come to the view that it  
cannot, and should not be re-enacted,'' Robert Bennett, who 
represented the president in the Paula Jones case, told the Senate 
Governmental Affairs Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett told the panel he was not speaking for the president,  
but he appealed for the preservation of constitutional rights of 
public officials investigated under the 1978 law. The statute, he 
said, reverses the rights to be presumed innocent until proved 
guilty and the right to remain silent. 
</P>
<P>
	``We ask our public officials to make numerous sacrifices in  
order to enjoy the privilege of public office,'' Bennett said. 
``But sacrificing basic constitutional protections is, I 
respectfully submit, too high a price to ask of anyone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We created this monster,'' he said later.  
</P>
<P>
	Asked later by reporters how much input Clinton had in his  
testimony, Bennett replied, ``Zero, absolutely zero.'' But he 
acknowledged telling White House Counsel Charles Ruff, ``as a 
courtesy,'' of his intent to testify and of his position. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second time in as many days that Clinton allies  
attacked the law before a Congress already hostile to its renewal 
without a major overhaul. But without a consensus on how to fix the 
statute, momentum is building to let it expire. In that case, 
investigations of presidents and other high-ranking officials would 
revert to the Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, some senators and House members are considering ways to  
fix the statute. 
</P>
<P>
	Making a case for the law's survival Wednesday was Nathan Lewin,  
who represented Attorney General Edwin Meese during the second 
independent counsel investigation brought under the 1978 law. 
</P>
<P>
	An independent counsel law ``is essential for public confidence  
in government,'' Lewin told the Senate panel. He said he believes 
its major flaws can be fixed by June 30. ``Some law, even if 
imperfect, is better than none.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's too early to start preparing eulogies,'' said Sen. Joseph  
Lieberman of Connecticut, the ranking Democrat on the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	The Watergate-inspired law provides for an independent counsel  
selected by three judges to investigate allegations against 
specified administration officials. Attorney General Janet Reno has 
appointed seven independent counsels during Clinton's six years in 
office, more than any of her predecessors. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and Reno successfully lobbied for the law's renewal five  
years ago. But with Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's 
investigation and the ensuing impeachment trial, Clinton's allies 
plan a sustained attack against the statute. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett's testimony echoed Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder's  
remarks on Tuesday before a House subcommittee. White House 
spokesman Barry Toiv told reporters the president supports Holder's 
call for the law's expiration. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno is scheduled to testify before the Senate panel, led by  
Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett said his opinion was shaped mostly by Independent  
Counsel Lawrence Walsh's Iran-Contra investigation, during which 
Bennett represented former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't so much Starr; it was really the Weinberger and the  
Walsh investigation that turned me against it,'' Bennett told 
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett said the law cannot be fixed because, in part, it leaves  
open too many opportunities for abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	``Beware of a lawyer with one case who has an endlessly deep  
pocket to finance it and no time limit in which to get the job 
done,'' Bennett said. 
</P>
<P>
	The law also withholds basic constitutional rights from those  
being investigated, Bennett said. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, when the attorney general is conducting a  
preliminary review of the case, the law gives the public official 
``no choice but to forgo his constitutional right to remain 
silent,'' Bennett said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the subject refuses to be interviewed by Justice Department  
investigators, the attorney general is forced to conclude that 
further investigation is warranted. But if the subject does 
cooperate, his statements can be used against him if an independent 
counsel is appointed, Bennett said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
